018|work=[[Zap2it]]|publisher=[[Tribune Media|Tribune Digital Ventures]]|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://worldscreen.com/tvkids/dhxs-mega-man-series-lands-on-sonys-pop/|title=DHX's Mega Man Series Lands on Sony's Pop|first=Joanna|last=Tong|date=October 10, 2018|access-date=October 10, 2018|work=Worldscreen}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.toonbarn.com/mega-man/mega-man-fully-charged-heads-to-south-east-asia/|title=Mega Man: Fully Charged heads to South East Asia|work=ToonBarn|date=June 5, 2019|access-date=October 12, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.toonbarn.com/other-cartoons/australias-9go-adds-new-bakugan-mega-man/|title=Australia's 9Go! adds new Bakugan, Mega Man|work=ToonBarn|date=July 13, 2019|access-date=October 12, 2019}}</ref>

While ''[[Street Fighter]]'' is a Japanese property to begin with, one particular animated television series based on the franchise, ''[[Street Fighter (cartoon)|Street Fighter]]'' (1995), was primarily made in the United States and Canada. The cartoon was produced by Japanese artists, most notably [[Madhouse (company)|Madhouse Studios]] and [[Bandai Namco Filmworks|Sunrise, Inc.]], allowing itself for plentiful anime references and visuals, while also making references to the [[Street Fighter (1994 film)|first movie]] and the earlier games.<ref name="destructoid">{{cite web|url=http://www.destructoid.com/remix-of-usa-street-fighter-cartoon-is-awful-awfully-funny--124258.phtml|title=Remix of USA Street Fighter cartoon is awful...awfully funny!|first=Nick|last=Chester|publisher=Destructoid.com|date=March 9, 2009|access-date=June 10, 2014}}</ref><ref name="1UP">{{cite web|url=http://www.1up.com/features/street-fighter-ii-things-you-did-not-know?pager.offset=1|archive-url=https://archive.today/20140611082205/http://www.1up.com/features/street-fighter-ii-things-you-did-not-know?pager.offset=1|url-status=dead|archive-date=June 11, 2014|title=20 Things You Didn't Know about Street Fighter II|publisher=1UP.com|date=2011|access-date=June 10, 2014}}</ref>

While ''[[Final Fantasy]]'' is also a Japanese property to begin with, one particular animated movie based on the franchise, ''[[Final Fantasy: The Spirits Within|The Spirits Within]]'' (2001), was primarily made in the United States by [[Chris Lee (producer)|Chris Lee]] and the franchise's creator [[Hironobu Sakaguchi]] and stands as the first full-length [[Photorealism|photorealistic]] computer-animated feature film ever made.<ref name=columbia>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/final-fantasy-the-movie/1100-2465389/ |title=Final Fantasy: The Movie |last=Mullen |first=Michael |date=April 28, 2000 |work=[[GameSpot]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201103183426/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/final-fantasy-the-movie/1100-2465389/ |archive-date=November 3, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="time">{{cite magazine |url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,997597,00.html |title=Cinema: A Painstaking Fantasy |last=Taylor |first=Chris |date=July 31, 2000 |magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |access-date=December 23, 2014 |url-access=subscription |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141217070831/http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,997597,00.html |archive-date=December 17, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref> Lee even compared ''The Spirits Within'' to that of [[Walt Disney]]'s ''[[Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs (1937 film)|Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs]]'', which by comparison was the first full-length [[cel animated]] film.

''[[Resident Evil]]'' is originally a Japanese property, but is frequently mistaken to be American due to the popularity and prevalence of the franchise in the United States, which led to the creation of the [[Resident Evil (film series)|film franchise]] and later the [[Resident Evil (TV series)|Netflix series of the same name]]. However, there are several English-language [[Computer-generated imagery|CGI]]-animated films to the franchise, making them easily labeled as anime due to all the films being primarily of Japanese origin. The anime-styled films  ''[[Biohazard 4D-Executer]]'', ''[[Resident Evil: Degeneration|Degeneration]]'', ''[[Resident Evil: Damnation|Damnation]]'', ''[[Resident Evil: Vendetta|Vendetta]]'', and ''[[Resident Evil: Death Island|Death Island]]'', as well as the [[Netflix]] animated series ''[[Resident Evil: Infinite Darkness|Infinite Darkness]]'', are all made in Japan and primarily marketed for American audiences. Unlike the film series or the Netflix series, all of the animations are set within the same universe as the original video game series.<ref name=RottenTomatoes-4DExecuter>{{Cite web |url= http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/biohazard_4d_executer/ |title= Biohazard 4D: Executer |publisher= Rotten Tomatoes}}</ref><ref name=YesAsia-DegenerationBD>{{cite web |url= http://www.yesasia.com/us/biohazard-degeneration-blu-ray-box-blu-ray-w-figure-first-press-limited/1013006471-0-0-0-en/info.html |title= Biohazard Degeneration Blu-ray Box (Blu-ray w/ Figure) (First Press Limited Edition) (English Subtitled) (Japan Version) |publisher= YesAsia}}</ref><ref name=YesAsia-Damnation3dBD>{{cite web |url= http://www.yesasia.com/us/biohazard-damnation-3d-blu-ray-first-press-limited-edition-japan-version/1032091153-0-0-0-en/info.html |title= Biohazard Damnation (3D Blu-ray)(First Press Limited Edition)(Japan Version) |publisher= YesAsia}}</ref><ref name=IGN-2015-10-15>{{cite web|url=http://ca.ign.com/articles/2015/10/15/cg-animated-resident-evil-movie-announced |title= CG-Animated Resident Evil Movie Announced |author=Alex Osborn |publisher= IGN |date=2015-10-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Bankhurst|first=Adam |title=Resident Evil: Death Island Is a New CG-Animated Film Releasing This Summer|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/resident-evil-death-island-is-a-new-cg-animated-film-releasing-this-summer|work=IGN|date=2023-02-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=最新ゲーム情報なら電撃オンライン！ |url=https://dengekionline.com/news/kako/new/200010/1017/1017biomovie.html |access-date=2024-12-25 |website=dengekionline.com}}</ref><ref name="Nifty">{{cite web |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030111085554/http://www.nifty.ne.jp/fanta/tokyo/2000/list1027.htm |script-title=ja:東京国際ファンタスティック映画祭2000 上映リスト10/27 |date=October 2000 |language=ja |publisher=[[Nifty Corporation]] |archive-date=January 11, 2003|url=http://www.nifty.ne.jp/fanta/tokyo/2000/list1027.htm}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sonypictures.com/homevideo/residentevildegeneration/diary/view.html|title=Resident Evil: Degeneration – Production Blog|access-date=2011-12-04|archive-date=2012-11-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121126072600/http://www.sonypictures.com/homevideo/residentevildegeneration/diary/view.html|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2017-02-13 |title=Resident Evil: Vendetta is a Reunion for Chris and Leon |url=https://www.shacknews.com/article/99022/resident-evil-vendetta-is-a-reunion-for-chris-and-leon |access-date=2025-02-05 |website=Shacknews |language=en}}</ref><ref name="dfx-biohazard-1">{{Cite web |url=https://www.dfx.co.jp/en/cgmaking/biohazard/ |title=Digital Frontier &#124; CG MAKING &#124; biohazard DEGENERATION |website=Digital Frontier |access-date=2020-04-19 |archive-date=2021-09-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210919015054/https://www.dfx.co.jp/en/cgmaking/biohazard/ |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="dfx-biohazard-2">{{Cite web |url=https://www.dfx.co.jp/en/cgmaking/biohazard/page02_2.html |title=Digital Fron