* {{Cite web |url=https://techcrunch.com/2020/11/05/facebook-blocks-sharpiegate-hashtag-election-conspiracies/ |first1=Sarah |last1=Perez |first2=Taylor |last2=Hatmaker |title=Facebook blocks hashtags for #sharpiegate, #stopthesteal election conspiracies |website=TechCrunch |date=November 5, 2020 |access-date=November 10, 2020 |archive-date=November 18, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201118144429/https://techcrunch.com/2020/11/05/facebook-blocks-sharpiegate-hashtag-election-conspiracies/ |url-status=live}}
* {{Cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/live-updates-2020-election-results/2020/11/08/932543826/the-next-2020-election-fight-convincing-trumps-supporters-that-he-lost |title=The Next 2020 Election Fight? Convincing Trump's Supporters That He Lost |newspaper=[[NPR]]|access-date=November 10, 2020 |archive-date=November 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201111002534/https://www.npr.org/sections/live-updates-2020-election-results/2020/11/08/932543826/the-next-2020-election-fight-convincing-trumps-supporters-that-he-lost |date=November 8, 2020 |first=Miles |last=Parks |url-status=live}}
* {{Cite news |url=https://www.fastcompany.com/90572604/trump-stop-the-steal-facebook-groups |title=The pro-Trump 'Stop the Steal' movement is still growing on Facebook |first=Mark |last=Sullivan |date=November 5, 2020 |website=Fast Company |access-date=November 9, 2020 |archive-date=November 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201106120623/https://www.fastcompany.com/90572604/trump-stop-the-steal-facebook-groups |url-status=live}}
* {{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/nov/06/tea-party-linked-activists-protest-against-election-fraud-us-cities |title=Tea party-linked activists protest against election fraud in US cities |first=Lois |last=Beckett |date=November 6, 2020 |website=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=November 9, 2020 |archive-date=November 7, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201107140705/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/nov/06/tea-party-linked-activists-protest-against-election-fraud-us-cities |url-status=live}}
* {{Cite web |url=https://www.rightwingwatch.org/post/right-wing-operative-ali-alexander-leads-stop-the-steal-campaign/ |title=Right-Wing Operative Ali Alexander Leads 'Stop the Steal' Campaign |first1=Kristen |last1=Doerer |website=Right Wing Watch |access-date=November 9, 2020 |archive-date=November 5, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201105164317/https://www.rightwingwatch.org/post/right-wing-operative-ali-alexander-leads-stop-the-steal-campaign/ |date=November 5, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> that widespread [[electoral fraud]] occurred during the [[2020 United States presidential election|2020 presidential election]]. Trump and his supporters have asserted, without evidence,<ref>{{Cite news |last=Frenkel |first=Sheera |date=November 13, 2020 |title=Beware of this misinformation from 'Stop the Steal' rallies this weekend. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/11/13/technology/beware-of-this-misinformation-from-stop-the-steal-rallies-this-weekend.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=November 17, 2020 |archive-date=November 17, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201117064704/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/11/13/technology/beware-of-this-misinformation-from-stop-the-steal-rallies-this-weekend.html |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="mjones">{{Cite web |last=Breland |first=Ali |title=Meet the right-wing trolls behind "Stop The Steal" |url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2020/11/stop-the-steal/ |date=November 7, 2020 |access-date=November 10, 2020 |website=Mother Jones |archive-date=November 9, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201109073331/https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2020/11/stop-the-steal/ |url-status=live}}</ref> that he is the winner of the election, and that large-scale voter and [[vote counting]] fraud took place in several [[swing state]]s.<ref name="mjones"/> The [[Associated Press]], [[ABC News (United States)|ABC News]], [[CBS News]], [[CNN]], [[Decision Desk HQ]], [[NBC News]], ''[[The New York Times]]'', and [[Fox News]] projected Biden as the [[president-elect of the United States|president-elect]], having surpassed the 270 [[United States Electoral College|Electoral College]] votes needed to claim victory.<ref name="officially secures">{{Cite news |first1=Michael R. |last1=Blood |first2=Nicholas |last2=Riccardi |url=https://apnews.com/article/election-2020-joe-biden-donald-trump-elections-electoral-college-3e0b852c3cfadf853b08aecbfc3569fa |title=Biden officially secures enough electors to become president |date=December 5, 2020 |website=[[Associated Press]] |access-date=December 6, 2020 |archive-date=December 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201208201209/https://apnews.com/article/election-2020-joe-biden-donald-trump-elections-electoral-college-3e0b852c3cfadf853b08aecbfc3569fa |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2020/11/03/upshot/network-race-call-tracker.html |date=November 7, 2020 |title=Tracking Which News Outlets Have Called the Presidential Race in Each State |first1=Eric |last1=Athas |first2=Seth |last2=Carlson |first3=John |last3=Keefe |first4=Claire Cain |last4=Miller |first5=Alicia |last5=Parlapiano |first6=Margot |last6=Sanger-Katz |website=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=November 8, 2020 |archive-date=November 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201108062817/https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2020/11/03/upshot/network-race-call-tracker.html |url-status=live}}</ref> A ''New York Times'' survey of state election officials found no evidence of significant voting fraud, nor did the [[United States Justice Department|Justice Department]], and dozens of lawsuits filed by Trump and his proxies to challenge voting results in several states failed.<ref name="disputing trump"/><ref name="doa">{{Cite web |date=December 3, 2020 |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/12/03/politics/trump-election-lawsuits/index.html |title=With Trump and allies headed to the Supreme Court, elections cases still dead on arrival |first=Katelyn |last=Polantz |work=[[CNN]] |access-date=December 6, 2020 |archive-date=December 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201208201011/https://www.cnn.com/2020/12/03/politics/trump-election-lawsuits/index.html |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/11/10/us/politics/voting-fraud.html |title=The Times Called Officials in Every State: No Evidence of Voter Fraud |first1=Nick |last1=Corasaniti |first2=Reid J. |last2=Epstein |first3=Jim |last3=Rutenberg |date=November 11, 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=November 14, 2020 |archive-date=November 16, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201116035455/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/11/10/us/politics/voting-fraud.html |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/12/04/donald-trump-in-court-443010 |first1=Kyle |last1=Cheney |first2=Josh |last2=Gerstein |date=December 4, 2020 |title=Donald Trump's brutal day in court |website=[[Politico]] |access-date=December 6, 2020 |archive-date=December 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201206010618/https://www.politico.com/news/2020/12/04/donald-trump-in-court-443010 |url-status=live}}</ref>

"Stop the Steal" was created by Republican political operative [[Roger Stone]] in 2016,<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Kuznia |first1=Rob |title=Stop the Steal's massive disinformation campaign connected to Roger Stone |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/11/13/business/stop-the-steal-disinformation-campaign-invs/index.html |work=[[CNN]] |date=November 14, 2020 |access-date=November 14, 2020 |archive-date=November 14, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201114224241/https://www.cnn.com/2020/11/13/business/stop-the-steal-disinformation-campaign-invs/index.html |url-status=live}}</ref> in anticipation of potential future election losses that could be portrayed as stolen by alleged fraud. A [[Facebook group]] with that name was created during the 2020 counting of votes by pro-Trump group "Women for America First" co-founder and [[Tea Party movement]] activist [[Amy Kremer]].<ref name=removes>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/nov/05/facebook-trump-stop-the-steal-group-removed |title=Facebook removes pro-Trump Stop the Steal group over 'calls for violence' |date=November 5, 2020 |access-date=November 7, 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |first=Julia Carrie |last=Wong |author-link=Julia Carrie Wong |archive-date=November 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201106194126/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/nov/05/facebook-trump-stop-the-steal-group-removed |url-status=live}}</ref> Facebook removed the group on November 5, describing it as "organized around the delegitimization of the election process".<ref name=removes/><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/11/05/technology/stop-the-steal-facebook-group.html |title=The Rise and Fall of the 'Stop the Steal' Facebook Group |first=Sheera |last=Frenkel |date=November 5, 2020 |website=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=November 9, 2020 |archive-date=November 9, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201109094914/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/11/05/technology/stop-the-steal-facebook-group.html |url-status=live}}</ref> It was reported to have been adding 1,000 new members every 10 seconds<ref>{{Cite web |first1=Elizabeth |last1=Culliford |first2=Raphael |last2=Satter |date=November 5, 2020 |title=Pro-Trump Facebook group protesting vote count adding 1000 members every 10 seconds |url=https://www.smh.com.au/world/north-america/pro-trump-facebook-group-protesting-vote-count-adding-1000-members-every-10-seconds-20201106-p56c0d.html |access-date=November 8, 2020 |website=The Sydney Morning Herald |archive-date=November 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201106223819/https://www.smh.com.au/world/north-america/pro-trump-facebook-group-protesting-vote-count-adding-1000-members-every-10-seconds-20201106-p56c0d.html |url-status=live}}</ref> with 360,000 [[Friending and following|followers]] before Facebook shut it down.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Dickson |first=E. J. |date=November 5, 2020 |title=A Pro-Trump 'Stop the Steal' Group Rapidly Grew on Facebook |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/culture-news/stop-the-steal-trump-biden-election-facebook-1086367/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201110215400/https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/culture-news/stop-the-steal-trump-biden-election-facebook-1086367/ |archive-date=November 10, 2020 |access-date=November 10, 2020 |website=[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last1=Schulberg |first1=Jessica |last2=Cook |first2=Jesselyn |date=November 5, 2020 |title=Nationwide 'Stop The Steal' Protests Are Being Pushed By GOP Operatives And The Far-Right |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/stop-steal-protests-republican-operatives-far-right_n_5fa4a744c5b6600956983a3e |access-date=December 14, 2020 |website=HuffPost |archive-date=December 14, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201214184650/https://www.huffpost.com/entry/stop-steal-protests-republican-operatives-far-right_n_5fa4a744c5b6600956983a3e |url-status=live}}</ref> Some "Stop the Steal" Facebook groups had discussed extreme violence, incitement to violence, and other threats.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Mac |first1=Ryan |last2=Silverman |first2=Craig |date=November 5, 2020 |title=Facebook Has A Metric For "Violence And Incitement Trends." It's Rising. |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/ryanmac/facebook-internal-metric-violence-incitement-rising-vote |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201111133157/https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/ryanmac/facebook-internal-metric-violence-incitement-rising-vote |archive-date=November 11, 2020 |access-date=November 11, 2020 |website=BuzzFeed News}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=November 5, 2020 |title=Violence Brewed in Facebook Groups Ahead of 'Stop The Steal' Protests |url=https://www.snopes.com/news/2020/11/05/violence-stop-the-steal-facebook/ |access-date=January 11, 2021 |website=[[Snopes]] |archive-date=November 10, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211110005123/https://www.snopes.com/news/2020/11/05/violence-stop-the-steal-facebook/ |url-status=live }}</ref> CounterAction, a [[social media analytics]] firm, provided ProPublica and the ''Washington Post'' an audit of Facebook groups and posts which identified 650,000 election delegitimization posts leading up to January 6.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Silverman |first1=Craig |last2=Timberg |first2=Craig |last3=Kao |first3=Jeff |last4=Merrill |first4=Jeremy B. |date=4 January 2022 |title=Facebook Hosted Surge of Misinformation and Insurrection Threats in Months Leading Up to Jan. 6 Attack, Records Show |url=https://www.defenseone.com/ideas/2022/01/facebook-hosted-surge-misinformation-and-insurrection-threats-months-leading-jan-6-attack-records-show/360333/ |access-date=8 January 2021 |work=Defense One |publisher=[[Government Executive]] |archive-date=January 9, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220109002558/https://www.defenseone.com/ideas/2022/01/facebook-hosted-surge-misinformation-and-insurrection-threats-months-leading-jan-6-attack-records-show/360333/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Timberg |first1=Craig |last2=Dwoskin |first2=Elizabeth |last3=Albergotti |first3=Reed |date=22 October 2021 |title=Inside Facebook, Jan. 6 violence fueled anger, regret over missed warning signs |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2021/10/22/jan-6-capitol-riot-facebook/ |access-date=8 January 2022 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |archive-date=October 22, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211022233901/https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2021/10/22/jan-6-capitol-riot-facebook/ |url-status=live }}</ref> On January 11, 2021, Facebook announced that it would remove content containing the phrase "stop the steal" from Facebook and Instagram.<ref name="About Facebook 2021">{{Cite web |title=Our Preparations Ahead of Inauguration Day |website=About Facebook |date=January 11, 2021 |url=https://about.fb.com/news/2021/01/preparing-for-inauguration-day/ |first=Guy |last=Rosen |access-date=January 11, 2021 |archive-date=January 11, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210111210541/https://about.fb.com/news/2021/01/preparing-for-inauguration-day/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

[[File:Stop The Steal, St. Paul (50712391846).jpg|thumb|Stop the Steal protesters gathered outside the [[Minnesota State Capitol]] on December 12, 2020. A [[Boogaloo movement]] member was charged in connection to the event.]]
Several "Stop the Steal" groups were founded by right-wing groups<ref name="mjones" /> after Trump published tweets on [[Twitter]] encouraging his supporters to "Stop the Count".<ref name=":11" /> Many unorganized "Stop the Steal" groups protested in various U.S. cities, including Washington, D.C.;<ref>{{Cite web |last=Yancey-Bragg |first=N'dea |title=Trump supporters plan rallies in Washington DC, experts warn extremists may attend |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2020/11/13/trump-supporters-plan-washington-dc-rallies-experts-warn-extremists/6265591002/ |date=November 13, 2020 |access-date=November 17, 2020 |website=[[USA Today]] |archive-date=November 17, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201117011441/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2020/11/13/trump-supporters-plan-washington-dc-rallies-experts-warn-extremists/6265591002/ |url-status=live}}</ref> Detroit, Michigan;<ref>{{Cite web |date=November 4, 2020 |title='Stop the count': Crowd tries to storm Detroit convention centre |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-election-2020/crowd-storm-detroit-vote-count-election-2020-b1598248.html |first=Josh |last=Marcus |access-date=November 17, 2020 |website=[[The Independent]] |archive-date=November 19, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201119004625/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-election-2020/crowd-storm-detroit-vote-count-election-2020-b1598248.html |url-status=live}}</ref> Lansing, Michigan;<ref>{{Cite web |last=LeBlanc |first=Beth |title=Trump supporters dispute Michigan vote count at 'Stop the Steal' rally on Capitol lawn |url=https://www.detroitnews.com/story/news/politics/2020/11/14/trump-supporters-dispute-michigan-vote-count-stop-steal-rally/6282744002/ |date=November 14, 2020 |access-date=November 17, 2020 |website=[[The Detroit News]] |archive-date=November 17, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201117181412/https://www.detroitnews.com/story/news/politics/2020/11/14/trump-supporters-dispute-michigan-vote-count-stop-steal-rally/6282744002/ |url-status=live}}</ref> Las Vegas, Nevada;<ref>{{Cite web |last=Komenda |first=Ed |title=Nevada election 2020: Vote challengers gather outside election department in Las Vegas |date=November 4, 2020 |url=https://www.rgj.com/story/news/2020/11/04/las-vegas-nevada-election-results-department-vote-clark-county-protest-unrest/6169870002/ |access-date=November 17, 2020 |website=Reno Gazette Journal |archive-date=November 18, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201118144536/https://www.rgj.com/story/news/2020/11/04/las-vegas-nevada-election-results-department-vote-clark-county-protest-unrest/6169870002/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=November 8, 2020 |title='Stop the steal' protest outside Clark County Election Center Office |url=https://www.ktnv.com/news/political/elections-local/stop-the-steal-protest-outside-clark-county-election-center-office |first=Astrid |last=Mendez |access-date=November 17, 2020 |publisher=KTNV |archive-date=November 18, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201118202009/https://www.ktnv.com/news/political/elections-local/stop-the-steal-protest-outside-clark-county-election-center-office |url-status=live}}</ref> Madison, Wisconsin;<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Rickert |first1=Chris |first2=Logan |last2=Wroge |title=Trump supporters, counter protesters clash at Madison rally |url=https://madison.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/trump-supporters-counter-protesters-clash-at-madison-rally/article_6ec742ec-4a5f-54d8-81e5-db87ce07c3c9.html |access-date=November 17, 2020 |website=madison.com |archive-date=November 17, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201117181130/https://madison.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/trump-supporters-counter-protesters-clash-at-madison-rally/article_6ec742ec-4a5f-54d8-81e5-db87ce07c3c9.html |date=November 7, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Atlanta, Georgia;<ref>{{Cite web |title=Demonstrators rally for Trump in front of Georgia Capitol |date=November 14, 2020 |url=https://www.wsbtv.com/news/local/demonstrators-gather-front-georgia-capitol-protest-trump-loss/EKHPCSO4NFHEBI6XL5YBEGFTNY/ |access-date=November 17, 2020 |publisher=WSBTV |archive-date=November 17, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201117170107/https://www.wsbtv.com/news/local/demonstrators-gather-front-georgia-capitol-protest-trump-loss/EKHPCSO4NFHEBI6XL5YBEGFTNY/ |url-status=live}}</ref> and Columbus, Ohio.<ref>{{Cite web |first1=Matthew |last1=Thomas |first2=Mary |last2=Smith |date=November 7, 2020 |title=Trump, Biden supporters rally at Ohio Statehouse after Biden projected to win election |url=https://abc6onyourside.com/news/local/protesters-rally-at-ohio-statehouse-after-biden-projected-to-win-election |access-date=November 17, 2020 |publisher=WSYX |archive-date=November 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201108050306/https://abc6onyourside.com/news/local/protesters-rally-at-ohio-statehouse-after-biden-projected-to-win-election |url-status=live}}</ref> Several of these protests included members of extremist groups such as the [[Three Percenters]], the [[Proud Boys]] and the [[Oath Keepers]], which CNN reported was an illustration of "the thinning of a line between the mainstream right and far-right extremists".<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Jones |first1=Julia |last2=Snider |first2=Sara |date=November 15, 2020 |title=MAGA March brings together Trump voters, far-right leaders and counterprotesters, ending in some clashes |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/11/14/us/trump-washington-voters-rally-far-right/index.html |work=[[CNN]] |access-date=November 20, 2020 |archive-date=November 16, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201116183833/https://www.cnn.com/2020/11/14/us/trump-washington-voters-rally-far-right/index.html |url-status=live}}</ref>

In [[Michigan]] on December 7, 2020, "Stop the Steal" protestors gathered outside the private home of Michigan's Secretary of State [[Jocelyn Benson]] to shout obscenities and chant threatening speech into bullhorns. [[Joe Biden|Biden]]'s Michigan win by 154,000 votes had been officially certified by the Michigan Board of State Canvassers in November.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Dozens of armed 'stop the steal' protesters threaten Michigan Secretary of State outside her house |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/michigan-protest-jocelyn-benson-secretary-of-state/ |date=December 7, 2020 |first=Caitlin |last=O'Kane |access-date=December 14, 2020 |work=[[CBS News]] |archive-date=December 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201211090517/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/michigan-protest-jocelyn-benson-secretary-of-state/ |url-status=live}}</ref>

On December 12, 2020, post-election protests were held in Washington, D.C. At least nine people were transported from the protest by D.C. Fire and [[Emergency medical services|emergency medical service]] workers for hospital treatment. Among the injured were four people who suffered stab wounds and were said to be in critical condition. Two police officers suffered non-life-threatening injuries, and two others suffered minor injuries{{Clarification|reason=Difference between non-life-threatening and minor?|date=March 2025}}. An additional 33 people were arrested, including one for assault with a dangerous weapon. Earlier in the day, large groups of protesters and counter-protestors assembled outside the Supreme Court and [[Freedom Plaza]].<ref>{{Cite web |first=Lauren |last=Koenig |title=Several people stabbed and 33 arrested as 'Stop the Steal' protesters and counterprotesters clash in Washington, DC |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/12/12/us/stop-the-steal-protest-washington-dc-trnd/index.html |access-date=December 14, 2020 |work=[[CNN]] |archive-date=December 14, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201214025813/https://www.cnn.com/2020/12/12/us/stop-the-steal-protest-washington-dc-trnd/index.html |date=December 12, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>

By March 2021, organizations linked to the Stop the Steal movement, including the Proud Boys and the [[boogaloo movement]], had largely shifted their efforts to spreading [[COVID-19 misinformation|misinformation]] about [[COVID-19 vaccine]]s as a way of undermining government credibility.<ref>{{Cite news |last=MacFarquhar |first=Neil |date=March 26, 2021 |title=Far-Right Extremists Move From 'Stop the Steal' to Stop the Vaccine |work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/03/26/us/far-right-extremism-anti-vaccine.html |url-status=live |url-access=limited |access-date=March 26, 2021 |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20211228/https://www.nytimes.com/2021/03/26/us/far-right-extremism-anti-vaccine.html |archive-date=2021-12-28 |issn=0362-4331}}{{cbignore}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last1=Devine |first1=Curt |last2=Griffin |first2=Drew |date=February 5, 2021 |title=How two anti-government conspiracy theories converged |url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/02/04/politics/anti-vaxxers-stop-the-steal-invs/index.html |access-date=April 5, 2021 |website=[[CNN]] |archive-date=February 7, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210207205650/https://www.cnn.com/2021/02/04/politics/anti-vaxxers-stop-the-steal-invs/index.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

On April 7, 2021, the U.S. District Court of Minnesota charged self-proclaimed [[Boogaloo movement|boogaloo bois]] member Michael Paul Dahlager with illegal possession of a [[machine gun]]. Dahlager had traveled to the [[Minnesota State Capitol]] in [[Saint Paul, Minnesota|Saint Paul]] for a December 12, 2020, "Stop the Steal" rally where he scouted law enforcement positions and numbers. Dahlager had discussed with confidential informants his willingness to kill law enforcement members and incite violent uprisings against the government.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Brownell |first=Andy |date=April 7, 2021 |title=FBI Says Minnesota Boogaloo Bois Member Scouted the State Capitol |work=KRFO |url=https://krforadio.com/fbi-says-minnesota-boogaloo-bois-member-scouted-the-state-capitol/ |access-date=April 7, 2021 |archive-date=April 8, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210408000705/https://krforadio.com/fbi-says-minnesota-boogaloo-bois-member-scouted-the-state-capitol/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite press release |date=April 7, 2021 |title=Self-Described Member Of Boogaloo Bois Arrested, Charged With Illegal Possession Of A Machine Gun |url=https://www.justice.gov/usao-mn/pr/self-described-member-boogaloo-bois-arrested-charged-illegal-possession-machine-gun |access-date=April 7, 2021 |website=justice.gov |archive-date=April 7, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210407220526/https://www.justice.gov/usao-mn/pr/self-described-member-boogaloo-bois-arrested-charged-illegal-possession-machine-gun |url-status=live }}</ref> Dahlager had allegedly planned to carry out an attack in early 2021 on the state's capitol building, but abandoned it after he believed that informants were among his inner circle. Dahlager pleaded guilty to federal weapons charges in July 2021.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Mannix |first=Andy |date=July 15, 2021 |title=Boogaloo Bois member accused in plot to attack Minnesota Capitol pleads guilty to firearm charge |work=[[Star Tribune]] |url=https://www.startribune.com/boogaloo-bois-member-accused-in-plot-to-attack-minnesota-capitol-pleads-guilty-to-firearm-charge/600078373/ |access-date=July 15, 2021 |archive-date=July 15, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210715210512/https://www.startribune.com/boogaloo-bois-member-accused-in-plot-to-attack-minnesota-capitol-pleads-guilty-to-firearm-charge/600078373/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

In the days after the election, [[Ginni Thomas]], wife of Supreme Court justice [[Clarence Thomas]], exchanged 29 text messages with Trump chief of staff Mark Meadows, urging him to pursue efforts to overturn the election. Thomas asserted "The majority knows Biden and the Left is attempting the greatest Heist of our History" and recited a message circulating in right-wing media that the "Biden crime family & ballot fraud co-conspirators" were being arrested "to face military tribunals for sedition" at [[Guantanamo Bay detention camp]]. Thomas wrote, "Do not concede. It takes time for the army who is gathering for his back." In March 2022, Thomas acknowledged she had attended the January 6 Stop the Steal rally but there was no evidence she had been involved in its organization.<ref>{{cite news |title=Virginia Thomas urged White House chief to pursue unrelenting efforts to overturn the 2020 election, texts show |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2022/03/24/virginia-thomas-mark-meadows-texts/ |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=June 13, 2022 |date=March 24, 2022 |first1=Bob |last1=Woodward |author-link=Bob Woodward |first2=Robert |last2=Costa |author-link2=Robert Costa (journalist) |archive-date=March 28, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220328132724/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2022/03/24/virginia-thomas-mark-meadows-texts/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Garcia |first1=Catherine |title=Ginni Thomas acknowledges attending 'Stop the Steal' rally, but denies organizing it |url=https://theweek.com/us/1011297/ginni-thomas-acknowledges-attending-stop-the-steal-rally-but-denies-organizing-it |access-date=June 13, 2022 |work=The Week |date=March 14, 2022 |archive-date=March 26, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220326223236/https://theweek.com/us/1011297/ginni-thomas-acknowledges-attending-stop-the-steal-rally-but-denies-organizing-it |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Cercone |first1=Jeff |title=There's no evidence Ginni Thomas organized Jan. 6 events |url=https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2022/jan/11/facebook-posts/theres-no-evidence-ginni-thomas-organized-jan-6-ev/ |publisher=[[PolitiFact]]|date=January 11, 2022 |access-date=June 13, 2022 |archive-date=March 26, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220326005223/https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2022/jan/11/facebook-posts/theres-no-evidence-ginni-thomas-organized-jan-6-ev/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

==== Conspiracy theories ====
Multiple [[Conspiracy theory|conspiracy theories]] were promoted, such as the claim that billionaire donor [[George Soros]] "stole the election".<ref>{{Cite news |title=Gingrich Pushes 'Soros Stole the Election' Conspiracy Theory on Fox News |url=https://www.haaretz.com/jewish/gingrich-soros-election-fox-news-1.9297734 |date=November 9, 2020 |agency=[[Associated Press]] |access-date=January 12, 2021 |work=Haaretz |archive-date=January 5, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210105142658/https://www.haaretz.com/jewish/gingrich-soros-election-fox-news-1.9297734 |url-status=live }}</ref> Another is [[Italygate]], a [[QAnon]]-adjacent<ref name="Reuters">{{Cite news |title=Fact check: Evidence disproves claims of Italian conspiracy to meddle in U.S. election (known as #ItalyGate) |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/uk-fact-check-debunking-italy-gate-idUSKBN29K2N8 |access-date=November 20, 2021 |work=[[Reuters]] |date=January 15, 2021 |archive-date=June 8, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210608222430/https://www.reuters.com/article/uk-fact-check-debunking-italy-gate-idUSKBN29K2N8 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Vatican blackout hoax linked to ItalyGate conspiracy theory |url=https://formiche.net/2021/01/vatican-blackout-pepe-arrest-italygate-conspiracy-theory/ |first=Otto |last=Lanzavecchia |work=Formiche.net |date=January 12, 2021 |access-date=November 21, 2021 |archive-date=June 8, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210608232313/https://formiche.net/2021/01/vatican-blackout-pepe-arrest-italygate-conspiracy-theory/ |url-status=live }}</ref> theory originating from a [[fake news website]], which claimed that the election was rigged in Biden's favor by the [[Embassy of the United States, Rome|U.S. Embassy in Rome]], using satellites and military technology to remotely switch votes from Trump to Biden. There is no evidence to support this.<ref name="Reuters"/><ref name="USA Today">{{Cite news |last1=Caldera |first1=Camille |title=Fact check: Claims of electoral fraud in Rome, dubbed 'ItalyGate,' are baseless |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/factcheck/2021/01/08/fact-check-italygate-claims-electoral-fraud-rome-baseless/6567335002/ |work=[[USA Today]] |date=January 8, 2021 |access-date=November 21, 2021 |archive-date=June 16, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210616060906/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/factcheck/2021/01/08/fact-check-italygate-claims-electoral-fraud-rome-baseless/6567335002/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Republican congressman [[Scott Perry]] texted [[White House Chief of Staff]] [[Mark Meadows]] a link to a YouTube video making the allegation.<ref name="Reuters"/><ref>{{cite news |title=CNN Exclusive: Meadows' texts reveal new details about the key role a little-known GOP congressman played in efforts to overturn election |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2022/04/26/politics/mark-meadows-texts-scott-perry-key-role-overturn-election/index.html |work=[[CNN]] |access-date=June 13, 2022 |date=April 27, 2022 |first1=Zachary |last1=Cohen |first2=Ryan |last2=Nobles |first3=Annie |last3=Grayer |first4=Jamie |last4=Gangel |archive-date=April 27, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220427024346/https://edition.cnn.com/2022/04/26/politics/mark-meadows-texts-scott-perry-key-role-overturn-election/index.html |url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' later reported that, during Trump's last weeks in office, Meadows emailed the video to the [[United States Department of Justice|Department of Justice]], seeking an investigation.<ref>Multiple sources:
* {{Cite news |last1=Benner |first1=Katie |title=Meadows Pressed Justice Dept. to Investigate Election Fraud Claims |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/06/05/us/politics/mark-meadows-justice-department-election.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=June 5, 2021 |access-date=November 21, 2021 |archive-date=March 29, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220329084406/https://www.nytimes.com/2021/06/05/us/politics/mark-meadows-justice-department-election.html |url-status=live }}
* {{Cite news |last1=Pengelly |first1=Martin |title=Trump aide asked DoJ to investigate bizarre 'Italygate' claim votes were changed by satellite |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2021/jun/06/donald-trump-mark-meadows-doj-italygate |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=June 6, 2021 |access-date=November 21, 2021 |archive-date=June 16, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210616231224/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2021/jun/06/donald-trump-mark-meadows-doj-italygate |url-status=live }}
* {{Cite news |last1=Bolies |first1=Corbin |title=Meadows Pushed DOJ to Probe Insane 'Italygate' Election Fraud Theory |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/trump-chief-of-staff-mark-meadows-pushed-doj-to-probe-insane-italygate-election-fraud-theory |work=[[The Daily Beast]] |date=June 5, 2021 |access-date=November 21, 2021 |archive-date=June 8, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210608121924/https://www.thedailybeast.com/trump-chief-of-staff-mark-meadows-pushed-doj-to-probe-insane-italygate-election-fraud-theory |url-status=live }}
* {{Cite news |title=Trump's chief of staff pressed the Justice Department to investigate the bizarre conspiracy theory that people in Italy meddled in the 2020 election using military satellites |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/trump-chief-of-staff-pressed-justice-dept-to-probe-conspiracy-theories-2021-6 |first=Tom |last=Porter |work=[[Business Insider]] |access-date=November 21, 2021 |date=June 6, 2021 |archive-date=October 5, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211005195126/https://www.businessinsider.com/trump-chief-of-staff-pressed-justice-dept-to-probe-conspiracy-theories-2021-6 |url-status=live }}</ref>

These conspiracy theories had multiple origins. They were promoted by Trump and other individuals, and were heavily pushed and expanded on by [[far-right]] news organizations such as [[One America News Network]] (OANN), [[Newsmax]], and ''[[The Gateway Pundit]]'', as well as by [[Sean Hannity]] and some other Fox News commentators.<ref name="USATod">{{Cite news |last1=Keveny |first1=Bill |last2=Puente |first2=Maria |title=How conservative media stoked baseless election-fraud claims that motivated DC rioters |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/tv/2021/01/11/dc-riots-how-newsmax-oan-conservative-outlets-fueled-mob/6589298002/ |access-date=January 12, 2021 |work=[[USA Today]] |date=January 11, 2021 |archive-date=November 7, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211107170247/https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/tv/2021/01/11/dc-riots-how-newsmax-oan-conservative-outlets-fueled-mob/6589298002/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="cnn_2020-11-17">{{Cite web |last=Darcy |first=Oliver |title=Company debunks conspiracy theory that its server showed a landslide for Trump |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/11/17/media/scytl-debunks-conspiracy-theory/index.html |date=November 17, 2020 |access-date=November 23, 2020 |work=[[CNN]] |archive-date=November 30, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201130010442/https://www.cnn.com/2020/11/17/media/scytl-debunks-conspiracy-theory/index.html |url-status=live}}</ref> [[RT (TV network)|RT]], a Russian [[state media]] outlet, also promoted the Trump campaign's false claims of electoral fraud.<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Moore |first1=Martin |last2=Colley |first2=Thomas |date=2022-06-13 |title=Two International Propaganda Models: Comparing RT and CGTN's 2020 US Election Coverage |journal=[[Journalism Practice]] |volume=18 |issue=5 |language=en |pages=1306–1328 |doi=10.1080/17512786.2022.2086157 |s2cid=249696725 |issn=1751-2786 |doi-access=free }}</ref> Attempts by Facebook and other mainstream social networks to restrict groups that spread false election claims led to a surge in the popularity of [[Parler]], a right-leaning [[Alt-tech|alternative social networking site]] that has attracted supporters of Stop the Steal.<ref>{{Cite news |first1=Elizabeth |last1=Dwoskin |first2=Rachel |last2=Lerman |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2020/11/10/facebook-parler-election-claims/ |title='Stop the Steal' supporters, restrained by Facebook, turn to Parler to peddle false election claims |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=November 10, 2020 |access-date=November 11, 2020 |archive-date=November 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201111053317/https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2020/11/10/facebook-parler-election-claims/ |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="Brandom-TheVerge">{{Cite web |last=Brandom |first=Russell |date=November 9, 2020 |title=Parler, a conservative Twitter clone, has seen nearly 1 million downloads since Election Day |url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/11/9/21557219/parler-conservative-app-download-new-users-moderation-bias |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201109222652/https://www.theverge.com/2020/11/9/21557219/parler-conservative-app-download-new-users-moderation-bias |archive-date=November 9, 2020 |access-date=November 9, 2020 |website=[[The Verge]]}}</ref> Parler subsequently went offline after [[Amazon Web Services]] withdrew support for the app on January 9.<ref name="Shead 2021">{{Cite web |last=Shead |first=Sam |title=Parler CEO says app will be offline 'longer than expected' because of Amazon, Apple and Google |website=CNBC |date=January 11, 2021 |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2021/01/11/parler-drops-offline-after-amazon-withdraws-support.html |access-date=January 11, 2021 |archive-date=January 11, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210111102253/https://www.cnbc.com/2021/01/11/parler-drops-offline-after-amazon-withdraws-support.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

As of June 2021, Trump continued to echo the conspiracy theory that the election was "stolen"; particularly focusing on the efforts of [[Arizona Senate]] Republicans to audit the results of the election in [[Maricopa County, Arizona|Maricopa County]] and on a lawsuit disputing the results of the election in Georgia. The efforts of Arizona Republicans to audit the results have drawn the attention and support of some Republican politicians, including [[Marjorie Taylor Greene]], [[Matt Gaetz]], and the former president. Trump had reportedly told associates he could be "reinstated" as president by August 2021; however, there is no constitutional mechanism to reinstate a president after the results of an election have been certified by Congress.<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Karni |first1=Annie |last2=Haberman |first2=Maggie |date=June 5, 2021 |title=At Once Diminished and Dominating, Trump Prepares for His Next Act |language=en-US |work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/06/05/us/politics/donald-trump-republican-convention-speech.html |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20211228/https://www.nytimes.com/2021/06/05/us/politics/donald-trump-republican-convention-speech.html |url-status=live |archive-date=2021-12-28 |url-access=limited |access-date=June 5, 2021 |issn=0362-4331}}{{cbignore}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=June 2, 2021 |title=Arizona GOP election audit draws more Republican politicians |url=https://apnews.com/article/donald-trump-arizona-election-2020-elections-election-recounts-0f822ded24fb3cdbb9894c175dfffa91 |first=Jonathan J. |last=Cooper |access-date=June 5, 2021 |website=[[Associated Press]] |archive-date=June 5, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210605144508/https://apnews.com/article/donald-trump-arizona-election-2020-elections-election-recounts-0f822ded24fb3cdbb9894c175dfffa91 |url-status=live }}</ref> However, several Trump allies denied reports that Trump would be reinstated as president in August, including [[Lara Trump]], [[Jenna Ellis]], [[Jason Miller (communications strategist)|Jason Miller]], [[Corey Lewandowski]], and Marjorie Taylor Greene.<ref>Multiple sources:
* {{Cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jackbrewster/2021/06/03/lara-trump-dismisses-reports-trump-believes-he-will-be-reinstated-in-august/ |title=Lara Trump Dismisses Reports Trump Believes He Will Be Reinstated In August |last1=Brewster |first1=Jack |website=Forbes |date=June 3, 2021 |access-date=November 20, 2021 |archive-date=October 28, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211028171646/https://www.forbes.com/sites/jackbrewster/2021/06/03/lara-trump-dismisses-reports-trump-believes-he-will-be-reinstated-in-august/ |url-status=live }}
* {{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2021/jun/06/trump-lewandowski-election-reinstated-biden-north-carolina-fox-news |title=Trump adviser Lewandowski: he 'lost the election' and will not be reinstated |last1=Pengelly |first1=Martin |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=June 6, 2021 |access-date=November 20, 2021 |archive-date=October 27, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211027011541/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2021/jun/06/trump-lewandowski-election-reinstated-biden-north-carolina-fox-news |url-status=live }}
* {{Cite web |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/rep-marjorie-taylor-greene-admits-trump-will-not-be-reinstated-to-presidency |title=Rep. Marjorie Taylor Greene Admits Trump Will Not Be Reinstated to Presidency |last1=Montgomery |first1=Blake |newspaper=[[The Daily Beast]] |date=July 7, 2021 |access-date=November 20, 2021 |archive-date=October 27, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211027011540/https://www.thedailybeast.com/rep-marjorie-taylor-greene-admits-trump-will-not-be-reinstated-to-presidency |url-status=live }}
* {{Cite web |url=https://www.newsweek.com/trump-allies-reject-theory-trump-can-reinstated-president-1619343 |access-date=November 20, 2021 |title=Trump Allies Reject Theory Trump Can Be Reinstated as President |last1=Fink |first1=Jenna |website=[[Newsweek]] |date=August 13, 2021 |archive-date=October 27, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211027002701/https://www.newsweek.com/trump-allies-reject-theory-trump-can-reinstated-president-1619343 |url-status=live }}</ref>

''[[The Gateway Pundit]]'' published an August 2021 article reporting analysis conducted by Seth Keshel, a former Army intelligence officer, purporting to prove election fraud and that Trump actually won seven states carried by Biden. The analysis was false. Keshel was among a group of military-intelligence veterans including former Trump national security advisor [[Michael Flynn]] who played central roles in spreading false information about the election.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Swenson |first1=Ali |title=Report claiming 'excess' Biden votes doesn't show fraud |url=https://apnews.com/article/fact-checking-001029664507 |date=August 4, 2021 |work=[[Associated Press]] |access-date=June 13, 2022 |archive-date=December 16, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211216230809/https://apnews.com/article/fact-checking-001029664507 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Funke |first1=Daniel |title=Fact check: No evidence of 8 million 'excess' Biden votes from 2020 election |work=[[USA Today]] |date=August 10, 2021 |access-date=June 13, 2022 |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/factcheck/2021/08/10/fact-check-8-million-excess-biden-votes-werent-counted-2020/5512962001/ |archive-date=November 7, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211107215618/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/factcheck/2021/08/10/fact-check-8-million-excess-biden-votes-werent-counted-2020/5512962001/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="reuters.com">{{cite news |title=The military-intelligence veterans who helped lead Trump's campaign of disinformation |url=https://www.reuters.com/investigates/special-report/usa-election-military/ |work=[[Reuters]] |date=December 15, 2021 |first1=Ram |last1=Roston |first2=Brad |last2=Heath |first3=John |last3=Shiffman |first4=Peter |last4=Eisler |access-date=June 13, 2022 |archive-date=December 18, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211218203057/https://www.reuters.com/investigates/special-report/usa-election-military/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

== November 2020 ==
On at least one occasion in November 2020, Trump privately acknowledged that he lost the election. [[Alyssa Farah Griffin]], a White House aide to Trump, recalls him exclaiming "Can you believe I lost to this guy?" while watching Biden on television.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ex-Trump aide says Trump admitted privately that he lost the election |website=CNN Video |date=June 19, 2022 |url=https://www.cnn.com/videos/politics/2022/06/19/trump-admission-2024-election-sotu-vpx.cnn |access-date=June 20, 2022 |archive-date=June 21, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220621134007/https://www.cnn.com/videos/politics/2022/06/19/trump-admission-2024-election-sotu-vpx.cnn |url-status=live }}</ref> This, however, was not Trump's public position.

The [[Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency]] had a website called Rumor Control to combat disinformation,<ref name=":13">{{Cite web |last1=Winter |first1=Tom |last2=Collier |first2=Kevin |last3=Rohde |first3=David |date=April 9, 2025 |title=Trump orders probes of two former officials who defied him |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/national-security/trump-orders-probes-two-former-officials-defied-rcna200523 |access-date=April 9, 2025 |website=NBC News |language=en}}</ref> and on November 12, CISA Director [[Chris Krebs]] called the election "the most secure in American history". Trump fired Krebs,<ref name="60Min20201129">{{Cite episode |surname=Krebs |given=Christopher Cox |subject-link=Chris Krebs |editor-surname=Pelley |editor-given=Scott Cameron |editor-link=Scott Pelley |id=Securing the Election, The Last Slave Ship, James Corden |season=53 |number=13 |title=Fired director of U.S. cyber agency Chris Krebs explains why President Trump's claims of election interference are false |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/election-results-security-chris-krebs-60-minutes-2020-11-29/ |series=60 Minutes |series-link=60 Minutes |network=[[CBS]] |time=11:30 |date=November 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201202060053/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/election-results-security-chris-krebs-60-minutes-2020-11-29/ |access-date=June 13, 2022 |archive-date=December 2, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> and Trump attorney [[Joseph diGenova]] called for his [[Capital punishment|execution]].<ref name="taken out and shot" /><ref>{{Cite news |last1=Sanger |first1=David E. |last2=Perlroth |first2=Nicole |date=November 18, 2020 |title=Trump Fires Christopher Krebs, Official Who Disputed Election Fraud Claims |work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/11/17/us/politics/trump-fires-christopher-krebs.html |access-date=January 13, 2021 |issn=0362-4331 |archive-date=November 12, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211112002552/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/11/17/us/politics/trump-fires-christopher-krebs.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>Multiple sources:
* {{Cite web |last=Payne |first=Adam |date=December 1, 2020 |title=Trump lawyer Joe diGenova says election security chief fired by the president should be 'taken out at dawn and shot' |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/trump-lawyer-joe-digenova-chris-krebs-shot-drawn-and-quartered-2020-12 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201202063902/https://www.businessinsider.com/trump-lawyer-joe-digenova-chris-krebs-shot-drawn-and-quartered-2020-12 |archive-date=December 2, 2020 |access-date=December 3, 2020 |website=Business Insider}}
* {{Cite web |last1=Acosta |first1=Jim |last2=Tapper |first2=Jake |last3=Cohen |first3=Zachary |last4=Cole |first4=Devan |date=December 2, 2020 |title=Trump attorney issues call for violence against truth-telling former election cybersecurity official |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/11/30/politics/joe-digenova-attorney-trump-campaign-chris-krebs-violence/index.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201202005545/https://www.cnn.com/2020/11/30/politics/joe-digenova-attorney-trump-campaign-chris-krebs-violence/index.html |archive-date=December 2, 2020 |access-date=December 3, 2020 |work=[[CNN]]}}
* {{Cite news |last=Izadi |first=Elahe |date=December 3, 2020 |title=Joseph diGenova resigns from Gridiron Club after saying fired cybersecurity official should be shot |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/media/2020/12/02/joseph-digenova-gridiron-club/ |url-status=live |access-date=December 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201208200957/https://www.washingtonpost.com/media/2020/12/02/joseph-digenova-gridiron-club/ |archive-date=December 8, 2020}}</ref> (Years later, on April 9, 2025, Trump directed Attorney General Pam Bondi and Homeland Security Secretary Kristi Noem to investigate Krebs and revoke his security clearance.)<ref name=":13" />

[[Emily W. Murphy|Emily Murphy]], the administrator of the [[General Services Administration]], delayed the start of [[Presidential transition of Joe Biden|the presidential transition]] until sixteen days after most media outlets had projected Biden to be the winner.<ref name="StandsBetween">{{Cite news |last1=Shear |first1=Michael D. |last2=Haberman |first2=Maggie |last3=Crowley |first3=Michael |date=November 10, 2020 |title=Trump Appointee Stands Between Biden's Team and a Smooth Transition |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/11/09/us/politics/emily-murphy-trump-biden.html |url-status=live |access-date=November 10, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201110135518/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/11/09/us/politics/emily-murphy-trump-biden.html |archive-date=November 10, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=November 23, 2020 |title=Formal Joe Biden transition may begin, US agency concludes |url=https://www.12news.com/article/news/nation-world/emily-murphy-gsa-signs-off-biden-transition/507-7bd7213a-d31b-43e8-ace3-4a96a54f44aa |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201123232925/https://www.12news.com/article/news/nation-world/emily-murphy-gsa-signs-off-biden-transition/507-7bd7213a-d31b-43e8-ace3-4a96a54f44aa |agency=[[Associated Press]] |archive-date=November 23, 2020 |access-date=November 23, 2020 |website=12news.com}}</ref>

==="Fake" electors===
{{Main|Trump fake electors plot}}
On November 3, [[Gregory Jacob]] wrote to [[Marc Short]] that it would be undesirable for the public to perceive Vice President Pence as if he had prejudged "questions concerning disputed electoral votes".<ref>{{Cite web |author=U.S. House of Representatives |date=22 December 2022 |title=Final Report of the Select Committee to Investigate the January 6th Attack on the United States Capitol|url=https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/GPO-J6-REPORT/pdf/GPO-J6-REPORT.pdf |access-date=5 July 2023 |website=govinfo.gov |page=11 |archive-date=July 29, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230729165626/https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/GPO-J6-REPORT/pdf/GPO-J6-REPORT.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref>

On November 4, White House Chief of Staff Mark Meadows received a text message calling for an "aggressive strategy" of having the Republican-led legislatures of three uncalled states "just send their own electors to vote and have it go to the [Supreme Court]". This was reportedly sent by Trump's secretary of energy, [[Rick Perry]].<ref name="independentPerry">{{Cite web|last=Feinberg|first=Andrew|date=December 17, 2021|title=Rick Perry sent Meadows text on 'aggressive' strategy to toss election, report says|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/rick-perry-meadows-texts-capitol-b1978490.html|url-status=live|access-date=December 18, 2021|website=[[The Independent]]|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211218102307/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/rick-perry-meadows-texts-capitol-b1978490.html |archive-date=December 18, 2021 }}</ref>

On November 5, [[Donald Trump Jr.]] sent a text message to Meadows outlining paths to subvert the Electoral College process and ensure his father a second term. Excerpts from the message are:
<blockquote>It's very simple. We have multiple paths. We control them all. We have operational control. Total leverage. Moral high ground. POTUS must start second term now. Republicans control 28 states Democrats 22 states. Once again Trump wins. We either have a vote WE control and WE win OR it gets kicked to Congress 6 January 2021.</blockquote>
Biden had not yet been declared the winner at the time of the text.<ref>{{cite news |first1=Ryan |last1=Nobles |first2=Zachary |last2=Cohen |first3=Annie |last3=Grayer |date=April 8, 2022 |title=CNN Exclusive: 'We control them all': Donald Trump Jr. texted Meadows ideas for overturning 2020 election before it was called |work=[[CNN]] |url=https://www.cnn.com/2022/04/08/politics/donald-trump-jr-meadows-text/index.html |access-date=June 13, 2022 |archive-date=April 8, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220408205412/https://www.cnn.com/2022/04/08/politics/donald-trump-jr-meadows-text/index.html |url-status=live }}</ref> Trump Jr. testified to the House select committee on May 3, 2022, that he had not written the message and did not recall who had, but that the idea had "sounded plausible" and was "the most sophisticated" plan he'd heard, although it concerned "things I don't necessarily, you know, know too much about".<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Herb |first1=Jeremy |last2=Grayer |first2=Annie |last3=Maher |first3=Kit |last4=Polantz |first4=Katelyn |date=December 29, 2022 |title=Key findings from the latest Jan. 6 panel transcripts, including from Donald Trump Jr. and others |url=https://www.cnn.com/2022/12/29/politics/january-6-committee-transcripts/index.html |access-date=December 29, 2022 |website=[[CNN]] |language=en |archive-date=December 29, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221229190026/https://www.cnn.com/2022/12/29/politics/january-6-committee-transcripts/index.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

On November 9, Ginni Thomas, wife of Supreme Court Justice Clarence Thomas, emailed 29 Arizona lawmakers, including [[Russell Bowers]] and [[Shawnna Bolick]], encouraging them to pick "a clean slate of Electors" and telling them that the responsibility was "yours and yours alone".<ref name="Brown_6/10//2022">{{Cite news |last=Brown |first=Emma |date=June 10, 2022 |title=Ginni Thomas pressed 29 Ariz. lawmakers to help overturn Trump's defeat, emails show |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/investigations/2022/06/10/ginni-thomas-election-arizona-lawmakers/ |access-date=June 11, 2022 |archive-date=June 11, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220611164148/https://www.washingtonpost.com/investigations/2022/06/10/ginni-thomas-election-arizona-lawmakers/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

On November 18, [[Jim Troupis|James R. Troupis]], a lawyer for the Trump campaign in Wisconsin, received a memo from Boston attorney [[Kenneth Chesebro]] outlining a plan to create and submit alternate slates of electors in contested states.<ref name="NYT-20230808">{{cite news |last1=Haberman |first1=Maggie |last2=Savage |first2=Charlie |last3=Broadwater |first3=Luke |title=Previously Secret Memo Laid Out Strategy for Trump to Overturn Biden's Win - The House Jan. 6 committee's investigation did not uncover the memo, whose existence first came to light in last week's indictment. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2023/08/08/us/politics/trump-indictment-fake-electors-memo.html |date=August 8, 2023 |work=[[The New York Times]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20230809142035/https://www.nytimes.com/2023/08/08/us/politics/trump-indictment-fake-electors-memo.html |archive-date=August 9, 2023 |access-date=August 10, 2023}}</ref><ref>Bauer, Scott, ''[https://apnews.com/article/wisconsin-fake-electors-trump-2020-charges-77d00919fc8d8e07438076610090a9b1 Wisconsin attorney general files felony charges against attorneys, aide who worked for Trump in 2020] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240604173654/https://apnews.com/article/wisconsin-fake-electors-trump-2020-charges-77d00919fc8d8e07438076610090a9b1 |date=June 4, 2024 }}'', Associated Press, June 4, 2024</ref>

Another memo three weeks later went to Wisconsin and several other contested states. The memos are evidence that within weeks of the election, the Trump campaign was focusing on January 6, 2021, as the "hard deadline" for determining the outcome of the election.<ref name="NYT2222">{{cite news |first1=Alan |last1=Feuer |first2=Maggie |last2=Haberman |author-link2=Maggie Haberman |first3=Luke |last3=Broadwater |title=Memos Show Roots of Trump's Focus on Jan. 6 and Alternate Electors |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2022/02/02/us/politics/trump-jan-6-memos.html |access-date=February 3, 2022 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=February 2, 2022 |archive-date=August 10, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230810104924/https://www.nytimes.com/2022/02/02/us/politics/trump-jan-6-memos.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

The [[White House Counsel|White House Counsel's Office]] reportedly reviewed the plans to use alternate electors and deemed them not to be legally sound.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2022/04/25/cassidy-hutchinson-mark-meadows/ |title=The two significant new Jan. 6 disclosures from Mark Meadows's aide |first=Aaron |last=Blake |date=April 25, 2022 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=January 17, 2023 |archive-date=April 26, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220426010856/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2022/04/25/cassidy-hutchinson-mark-meadows/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

=== Lame duck firings and hirings ===
After vote counts showed a Biden victory, Trump engaged in what has been called a "post-election purge", firing or forcing out at least a dozen officials and replacing them with loyalists.<ref name=McEvoy/> Secretary of Defense [[Mark Esper]] was fired by tweet on November 9.<ref name="govnv">{{Cite web |last=Harper |first=Steven |url=https://billmoyers.com/story/insurrection-timeline-first-the-coup-and-then-the-cover-up-updated/ |date=March 7, 2021 |access-date=November 21, 2021 |title=Insurrection Timeline: First the Coup and Then the Cover-Up |work=BillMoyers.com |archive-date=February 27, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210227185627/https://billmoyers.com/story/insurrection-timeline-first-the-coup-and-then-the-cover-up-updated/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.defensenews.com/pentagon/2020/11/09/esper-fired-as-secretary-of-defense/ |title=Esper fired as defense secretary |first=Aaron |last=Mehta |date=November 10, 2020 |website=Defense News |access-date=November 22, 2020 |archive-date=November 10, 2020 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20201110000826/https://www.defensenews.com/pentagon/2020/11/09/esper-fired-as-secretary-of-defense/ |url-status=live}}</ref> Undersecretary for Defense [[Joseph D. Kernan]] and Acting Undersecretary for Policy [[James Anderson (defense official)|James H. Anderson]] resigned in protest or were forced out.<ref name=McEvoy/> The White House sought to learn the names of political appointees who had applauded Anderson upon his departure, so they could be fired.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-election-2020/white-house-department-of-defense-pentagon-jim-anderson-b1721307.html |first=Harriet |last=Alexander |title=White House 'requesting names of those who clapped out departing Pentagon official' |date=November 11, 2020 |website=[[The Independent]] |access-date=November 22, 2020 |archive-date=November 17, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201117223350/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-election-2020/white-house-department-of-defense-pentagon-jim-anderson-b1721307.html |url-status=live}}</ref> The DOD chief of staff, Jen Stewart, was replaced by a former staffer to Representative [[Devin Nunes]].<ref name=McEvoy/> On November 30, Christopher P. Maier, the head of the Pentagon's Defeat ISIS Task Force, was ousted and the task force was disbanded; a White House official told him that the United States had won the war against the Islamic State, so the task force was no longer needed.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/12/01/us/politics/pentagon-firing.html |title=Another Official Is Ousted From the Pentagon |last1=Schmitt |first1=Eric |last2=Goldman |first2=Adam |date=December 1, 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=December 1, 2020 |archive-date=December 1, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201201202404/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/12/01/us/politics/pentagon-firing.html |url-status=live}}</ref>

Trump's allegations of election fraud in battleground states were refuted by judges, state election officials, and his own administration's [[Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency]] (CISA).<ref name=conclusive>{{Cite news |last1=Woodward |first1=Calvin |title=AP Fact Check: Trump conclusively lost, denies the evidence |url=https://apnews.com/article/ap-fact-check-trump-conclusively-lost-bbb9d8c808021ed65d91aee003a7bc64 |access-date=November 17, 2020 |work=[[Associated Press]] |date=November 17, 2020 |archive-date=November 17, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201117000041/https://apnews.com/article/ap-fact-check-trump-conclusively-lost-bbb9d8c808021ed65d91aee003a7bc64 |url-status=live}}</ref> After CISA director [[Chris Krebs]] contradicted Trump's voting-fraud allegations, Trump fired him on November 17.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Sanger |first=David E. |date=November 18, 2020 |title=Trump fires Christopher Krebs, whose agency disputed president's false claims of election fraud |work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/live/2020/11/17/us/joe-biden-trump |access-date=November 18, 2020 |issn=0362-4331 |archive-date=November 18, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201118012220/https://www.nytimes.com/live/2020/11/17/us/joe-biden-trump/trump-fires-christopher-krebs-whose-agency-disputed-presidents-false-claims-of-election-fraud |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Trump fires election security official who contradicted him |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-54982360 |access-date=November 18, 2020 |work=[[BBC News]] |date=November 18, 2020 |archive-date=November 18, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201118013241/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-54982360 |url-status=live}}</ref> Three other Department of Homeland Security officials – CISA's deputy director [[Matthew Travis]], CISA's assistant director for cybersecurity, Bryan Ware, and the DHS's assistant secretary of international affairs Valerie Boyd{{snd}}were also forced out.<ref name=McEvoy>{{Cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jemimamcevoy/2020/11/18/trumps-post-election-purge-head-of-election-cybersecurity-11-other-top-officials-out/ |title=Trump's 'Post-Election Purge': Head Of Election Cybersecurity, 11 Other Top Officials Out |last=McEvoy |first=Jemima |date=November 18, 2020 |work=[[Forbes]]|access-date=November 24, 2020 |archive-date=May 26, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220526035447/https://www.forbes.com/sites/jemimamcevoy/2020/11/18/trumps-post-election-purge-head-of-election-cybersecurity-11-other-top-officials-out/ |url-status=live}}</ref>

[[Bonnie Glick]], the deputy administrator of the [[United States Agency for International Development]], was abruptly fired on November 6; she had prepared a transition manual for the next administration. She was due to become acting administrator of the department on November 7. Firing her left the position of acting administrator vacant, so that Trump loyalist [[John Barsa]] could become acting deputy administrator.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trump-white-house-purge/2020/11/13/2af12c94-25ca-11eb-8672-c281c7a2c96e_story.html |first1=Josh |last1=Dawsey |first2=Juliet |last2=Eilperin |first3=John |last3=Hudson |first4=Lisa |last4=Rein |title=In Trump's final days, a 30-year-old aide purges officials seen as insufficiently loyal |date=November 13, 2020 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=November 16, 2020 |archive-date=November 28, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201128090111/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trump-white-house-purge/2020/11/13/2af12c94-25ca-11eb-8672-c281c7a2c96e_story.html |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last1=Hansler |first1=Jennifer |first2=Kylie |last2=Atwood |date=November 7, 2020 |title=Second highest-ranking official at USAID ousted |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/11/06/politics/bonnie-glick-ousted-usaid/index.html |url-status=live |publisher=[[CNN]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201107010125/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/11/06/politics/bonnie-glick-ousted-usaid/index.html |archive-date=November 7, 2020 |access-date=November 8, 2020}}</ref>

Career climate scientist Michael Kuperberg, who for the past five years has produced the annual [[National Climate Assessment]] issued by [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]] (NOAA), was demoted on November 9 and returned to his previous position at the Department of Energy. Several media outlets reported that David Legates, a deputy assistant secretary at NOAA who claims that global warming is harmless, would be appointed to oversee the congressionally mandated report in place of Kuperberg, based on information obtained from "people close to the Administration", including [[Myron Ebell]], the head of President Trump's Environmental Protection Agency transition team and director of the Center for Energy and Environment at the [[Competitive Enterprise Institute]].<ref>Multiple sources:
* {{Cite journal |last1=Waldmann |first1=Scott |title=Trump to put climate change denier in charge of key U.S. report |journal=Science Magazine |date=November 10, 2020 |doi=10.1126/science.abf6536 |s2cid=228883906 |url=https://www.science.org/content/article/trump-put-climate-denier-charge-key-us-report |access-date=January 5, 2021 |archive-date=July 8, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220708090829/https://www.science.org/content/article/trump-put-climate-denier-charge-key-us-report |url-status=live |url-access=subscription }}
* {{Cite news |last1=Boyle |first1=Louise |title=Trump removes scientist who led sweeping climate change report and other officials |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/environment/trump-fires-climate-change-scientist-kuperberg-b1720426.html |access-date=January 5, 2021 |work=[[The Independent]] |date=November 10, 2020 |archive-date=January 9, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210109051909/https://www.independent.co.uk/environment/trump-fires-climate-change-scientist-kuperberg-b1720426.html |url-status=live }}
* {{Cite news |last1=Flavelle |first1=Christopher |last2=Friedman |first2=Lisa |last3=Davenport |first3=Coral |title=Trump Administration Removes Scientist in Charge of Assessing Climate Change |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/11/09/climate/michael-kuperberg-climate-assessment.html |access-date=January 5, 2021 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=November 9, 2020 |archive-date=January 5, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210105011441/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/11/09/climate/michael-kuperberg-climate-assessment.html |url-status=live }}
* {{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/weather/2020/11/09/trump-removes-climate-program-director/ |title=Trump administration removes head of federal climate program that oversees key reports |date=November 9, 2020 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=November 16, 2020 |archive-date=November 24, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201124073850/https://www.washingtonpost.com/weather/2020/11/09/trump-removes-climate-program-director/ |first1=Jason |last1=Samenow |first2=Andrew |last2=Freedman |first3=Juliet |last3=Eilperin |url-status=live }}</ref> As of May 18, 2021, the Biden administration reappointed Kuperberg as executive director of the U.S. Global Change Research Program.<ref name="Flavelle">{{Cite news |last1=Flavelle |first1=Christopher |title=Biden reappoints a top climate scientist who was removed by Trump. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/05/19/us/politics/climate-scientist-biden.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20211228/https://www.nytimes.com/2021/05/19/us/politics/climate-scientist-biden.html |archive-date=December 28, 2021 |url-access=limited |access-date=May 21, 2021 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=May 19, 2021}}{{cbignore}}</ref>

On November 5, [[Neil Chatterjee]] was removed from his post as chair of the [[Federal Energy Regulatory Commission]].<ref name=McEvoy/>

On November 11, [[Lisa Gordon-Hagerty]] resigned from her posts as [[Under Secretary of Energy for Nuclear Security]] and administrator of the quasi-independent [[National Nuclear Security Administration]], reportedly due to longstanding tensions and disagreements with [[Secretary of Energy]] [[Dan Brouillette]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Castronuovo |first=Celine |date=November 6, 2020 |title=Lisa Gordon-Hagerty resigns as chief of nuclear weapons agency |url=https://thehill.com/policy/defense/524865-lisa-e-gordon-hagerty-resigns-as-nnsa-administrator |access-date=November 7, 2020 |website=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |archive-date=November 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201127041005/https://thehill.com/policy/defense/524865-lisa-e-gordon-hagerty-resigns-as-nnsa-administrator |url-status=live}}</ref>

In October 2020, Trump signed an executive order that created a new category of federal employee, [[Schedule F appointment|Schedule F]], which included all career civil servants whose job includes "policymaking". Such employees would no longer be covered by [[United States federal civil service|civil service]] protections against arbitrary dismissal, but would be subject to the same rules as political appointees. The new description could be applied to thousands of nonpartisan experts, such as scientists who give advice to the political appointees who run their departments.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/trump-executive-order-civil-service-biden-election-schedule-f-b1255692.html |title=Trump just quietly passed an executive order that could destroy a future Biden administration |last=Feinberg |first=Andrew |date=October 30, 2020 |work=[[The Independent]] |access-date=December 1, 2020 |archive-date=November 21, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201121220931/https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/trump-executive-order-civil-service-biden-election-schedule-f-b1255692.html |url-status=live}}</ref> Heads of all federal agencies were ordered to report by January 19, 2021, a list of positions that could be reclassified as Schedule F. The [[Office of Management and Budget]] submitted a list in November that included 88 percent of the office's workforce.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.realclearpolitics.com/articles/2020/11/21/omb_lists_workers_stripped_of_job_protection_under_trump_order_144708.html |title=OMB Lists Positions Stripped of Job Protection Under Trump Order |last=Wegmann |first=Philip |date=November 21, 2020 |work=Real Clear Politics |access-date=December 1, 2020 |archive-date=November 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201127201134/https://www.realclearpolitics.com/articles/2020/11/21/omb_lists_workers_stripped_of_job_protection_under_trump_order_144708.html |url-status=live}}</ref> Federal employee organizations and Congressional Democrats sought to overturn the order via lawsuits or bills. House Democrats warned in a letter that "The executive order could precipitate a mass exodus from the federal government at the end of every presidential administration, leaving federal agencies without deep institutional knowledge, expertise, experience, and the ability to develop and implement long-term policy strategies".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://federalnewsnetwork.com/workforce/2020/11/congress-employee-groups-ramp-up-pressure-to-block-schedule-f-executive-order/ |title=Congress, employee groups ramp up pressure to block Schedule F executive order |last=Ogrysko |first=Nicole |date=November 24, 2020 |work=Federal News Network |access-date=December 1, 2020 |archive-date=November 30, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201130152647/https://federalnewsnetwork.com/workforce/2020/11/congress-employee-groups-ramp-up-pressure-to-block-schedule-f-executive-order/ |url-status=live}}</ref> Observers predicted that Trump could use the new rule to implement a "massive government purge on his way out the door".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/trump-lays-the-groundwork-for-a-massive-government-purge-on-his-way-out-the-door/2020/11/30/280519ac-333d-11eb-a997-1f4c53d2a747_story.html |title=Trump lays the groundwork for a massive government purge on his way out the door |last=Rampell |first=Catherine |date=November 30, 2020 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=December 1, 2020 |archive-date=December 2, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201202032635/https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/trump-lays-the-groundwork-for-a-massive-government-purge-on-his-way-out-the-door/2020/11/30/280519ac-333d-11eb-a997-1f4c53d2a747_story.html |url-status=live}}</ref>

Meanwhile, administration officials had ordered the Budget Office to begin work on a 2022 budget proposal that they would submit to Congress in February, ignoring the fact that Biden would have already taken over by that point.<ref>{{Cite news |first2=Erica |last2=Werner |first3=Josh |last3=Dawsey |first1=Jeff |last1=Stein |title=White House tells federal agencies to proceed with plans for Trump's February budget in latest sign of election defiance |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/us-policy/2020/11/10/trump-federal-budget-post-election/ |date=November 10, 2020 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=December 22, 2020 |archive-date=December 21, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201221185258/https://www.washingtonpost.com/us-policy/2020/11/10/trump-federal-budget-post-election/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

=== Lawsuits ===
[[File:2019 Rudolph Giuliani, Ex-Prefeito de Nova York - 48789790128 (cropped).jpg|thumb|[[Rudy Giuliani]], head of Trump's failed legal efforts, falsely asserted that the election had been subject to massive fraud.]]
{{main|Post-election lawsuits related to the 2020 United States presidential election}}
After the 2020 United States presidential election, the [[Donald Trump 2020 presidential campaign|campaign]] for incumbent president Donald Trump filed a number of lawsuits contesting election processes, vote-counting, and the vote-certification process in multiple states, including Arizona, Georgia, Michigan, Nevada, Pennsylvania, Texas, and Wisconsin.<ref name="bloomberg-law-davis-list">{{Cite web |last1=Davis |first1=Tina |title=Trump's Election Lawsuits: Where the Fights Are Playing Out |url=https://news.bloomberglaw.com/us-law-week/trumps-election-lawsuits-where-the-fights-are-playing-out |work=[[Bloomberg Law]] |access-date=November 10, 2020 |date=November 7, 2020 |archive-date=November 16, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201116052204/https://news.bloomberglaw.com/us-law-week/trumps-election-lawsuits-where-the-fights-are-playing-out |url-status=live}}</ref> Many such cases were quickly dismissed,<ref name="buzzfeed-tillman"/> and lawyers and other observers noted that the lawsuits were unlikely to have an effect on the outcome of the election.<ref name="econ-nov-7">{{Cite news |title=Courting failure: Donald Trump still hopes lawsuits will make up for his lack of votes |newspaper=[[The Economist]] |url=https://www.economist.com/united-states/2020/11/07/donald-trump-still-hopes-lawsuits-will-make-up-for-his-lack-of-votes |access-date=November 12, 2020 |date=November 7, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201116052231/https://www.economist.com/united-states/2020/11/07/donald-trump-still-hopes-lawsuits-will-make-up-for-his-lack-of-votes |archive-date=November 16, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="ft-shubber">{{Cite news |last1=Shubber |first1=Kadhim |title=Trump clings to courtroom hopes despite lawsuit losses |url=https://www.ft.com/content/4942e1b5-e445-476d-9d80-6b51777939a9 |work=[[Financial Times]] |access-date=November 12, 2020 |date=November 8, 2020 |archive-date=November 16, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201116052209/https://www.ft.com/content/4942e1b5-e445-476d-9d80-6b51777939a9 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="npr-parks-suits-nov-10">{{Cite news |last1=Parks |first1=Miles |title=Trump Election Lawsuits Have Mostly Failed. Here's What They Tried |work=[[NPR]] |url=https://www.npr.org/2020/11/10/933112418/the-trump-campaign-has-had-almost-no-legal-success-this-month-heres-what-they-ve |access-date=November 11, 2020 |date=November 10, 2020 |archive-date=November 16, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201116052241/https://www.npr.org/2020/11/10/933112418/the-trump-campaign-has-had-almost-no-legal-success-this-month-heres-what-they-ve |url-status=live}}</ref> By November 19, more than two dozen of the legal challenges filed since Election Day had failed.<ref name="2dozen">{{Cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/2020/11/19/936759911/despite-more-than-2-dozen-legal-losses-trumps-lawyers-press-on-with-election-fig |last=Fessler |first=Pam |date=November 19, 2020 |title=Despite More Than 2 Dozen Legal Losses, Trump's Lawyers Press On With Election Fights |work=[[NPR]] |access-date=November 21, 2020 |archive-date=November 21, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201121155644/https://www.npr.org/2020/11/19/936759911/despite-more-than-2-dozen-legal-losses-trumps-lawyers-press-on-with-election-fig |url-status=live}}</ref>

On November 21, U.S. District Court in Pennsylvania Judge [[Matthew Brann]], a Republican, dismissed the case before him [[Prejudice (legal term)|with prejudice]], ruling:
<blockquote> In this action, the Trump Campaign and the Individual Plaintiffs ... seek to discard millions of votes legally cast by Pennsylvanians from all corners{{snd}}from Greene County to Pike County, and everywhere in between. In other words, Plaintiffs ask this Court to disenfranchise almost seven million voters. This Court has been unable to find any case in which a plaintiff has sought such a drastic remedy in the contest of an election, in terms of the sheer volume of votes asked to be invalidated. One might expect that when seeking such a startling outcome, a plaintiff would come formidably armed with compelling legal arguments and factual proof of rampant corruption, such that this Court would have no option but to regrettably grant the proposed injunctive relief despite the impact it would have on such a large group of citizens.<br /><br />That has not happened. Instead, this Court has been presented with strained legal arguments without merit and speculative accusations, unpled in the operative complaint and unsupported by evidence. In the United States of America, this cannot justify the disenfranchisement of a single voter, let alone all the voters of its sixth most populated state. Our people, laws, and institutions demand more.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/election-us-2020-55030617 |title=US election: Trump camp's lawsuit struck down in Pennsylvania |work=[[BBC News]] |date=April 10, 2020 |access-date=November 22, 2020 |archive-date=November 21, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201121233146/https://www.bbc.com/news/election-us-2020-55030617 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://pacer-documents.s3.amazonaws.com/147/127057/15517440654.pdf |first=Matthew W. |last=Brann |author-link=Matthew W. Brann |title=MEMORANDUM OPINION |date=November 21, 2020 |website=[[PACER (law)|PACER]] |access-date=November 23, 2020 |archive-date=November 22, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201122081510/https://pacer-documents.s3.amazonaws.com/147/127057/15517440654.pdf |url-status=live}}</ref></blockquote>

=== Michigan officials pressured to not certify ===
Prior to November 17, the four-member board of canvassers of [[Wayne County, Michigan]], was deadlocked on election-result certification along party lines with the two Republican members refusing to certify, but on November 17 the board voted unanimously to certify its results.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Michigan county reverses course, votes unanimously to certify election results |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/526451-michigans-wayne-county-board-of-canvassers-unanimously-certifies-election |first=Tal |last=Axelrod |date=November 17, 2020 |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |access-date=November 21, 2020 |archive-date=November 19, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201119232855/https://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/526451-michigans-wayne-county-board-of-canvassers-unanimously-certifies-election |url-status=live}}</ref> Trump and [[Republican National Committee]] Chair [[Ronna McDaniel]] called the two Republican members of the board that day to pressure them to not sign the official statement of votes; the next day the two Republicans sought but failed to rescind their votes for certification, signing affidavits stating that they had voted for certification only because the two Democratic members had promised a full audit of the county's votes.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.freep.com/story/news/local/michigan/detroit/2020/11/19/trump-monica-palmer-wayne-canvassers-certification-election/3776190001/ |date=November 19, 2020 |title=Donald Trump called Monica Palmer after Wayne County Board of Canvassers meeting |first=Clara |last=Hendrickson |website=[[Detroit Free Press]] |access-date=November 22, 2020 |archive-date=November 22, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201122035705/https://www.freep.com/story/news/local/michigan/detroit/2020/11/19/trump-monica-palmer-wayne-canvassers-certification-election/3776190001/ |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Republicans in key Michigan county ask to rescind votes to certify election |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/state-watch/526652-republicans-in-key-michigan-county-try-to-rescind-votes-to-certify |first=John |last=Bowden |date=November 19, 2020 |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |access-date=November 21, 2020 |archive-date=November 20, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201120063506/https://thehill.com/homenews/state-watch/526652-republicans-in-key-michigan-county-try-to-rescind-votes-to-certify |url-status=live}}</ref> The two denied Trump's call had influenced their reversal.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.clickondetroit.com/decision-2020/2020/11/20/wayne-county-gop-canvassers-say-call-from-trump-did-not-influence-vote-decisions/ |title=Wayne County GOP canvassers say call from Trump did not influence vote decisions |first1=Rod |last1=Meloni |first2=Dane |last2=Kelly |date=November 20, 2020 |publisher=WDIV |access-date=November 22, 2020 |archive-date=November 20, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201120223525/https://www.clickondetroit.com/decision-2020/2020/11/20/wayne-county-gop-canvassers-say-call-from-trump-did-not-influence-vote-decisions/ |url-status=live}}</ref> A recording of the phone call surfaced in December 2023, on which McDaniel can be heard telling the two Republicans, "We will get you attorneys," to which Trump added, "We'll take care of that." Trump can also be heard to say, "We've got to fight for our country. We can't let these people take our country away from us."<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mauger |first1=Craig |title=Trump recorded pressuring Wayne County canvassers not to certify 2020 vote |url=https://www.detroitnews.com/story/news/politics/2023/12/21/donald-trump-recorded-pressuring-wayne-canvassers-not-to-certify-2020-vote-michigan/72004514007/ |work=The Detroit News |date=December 21, 2023 |access-date=December 22, 2023 |archive-date=December 22, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231222005137/https://www.detroitnews.com/story/news/politics/2023/12/21/donald-trump-recorded-pressuring-wayne-canvassers-not-to-certify-2020-vote-michigan/72004514007/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

Trump issued an invitation to Michigan lawmakers to travel to Washington.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/nation-world/nation-politics/wayne-county-republican-who-asked-to-rescind-her-vote-certifying-election-results-says-trump-called-her/ |title=Trump invites Michigan Republican leaders to meet him at White House as he attempts to overturn election results |work=[[The Seattle Times]] |access-date=November 22, 2020 |archive-date=November 21, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201121013554/https://www.seattletimes.com/nation-world/nation-politics/wayne-county-republican-who-asked-to-rescind-her-vote-certifying-election-results-says-trump-called-her/ |date=November 19, 2020 |first1=David A. |last1=Fahrenthold |first2=Tom |last2=Hamburger |first3=Josh |last3=Dawsey |first4=Kayla |last4=Ruble |url-status=live}}</ref> Michigan House Speaker [[Lee Chatfield]], State Senate Majority Leader [[Mike Shirkey]] and State Representative Jim Lilly were photographed in the lobby of the D.C. Trump Tower, where they were drinking $500-a-bottle champagne and were not wearing masks.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Falcon |first=Russell |url=https://wgntv.com/news/dom-perignon-trends-on-twitter-after-michigan-gop-leaders-seen-drinking-495-champagne-at-trump-hotel/ |title='Dom Perignon' trends on Twitter after Michigan GOP leaders seen drinking $495 champagne at Trump hotel |publisher=WGN-TV |date=April 14, 2016 |access-date=November 22, 2020 |archive-date=November 22, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201122225954/https://wgntv.com/news/dom-perignon-trends-on-twitter-after-michigan-gop-leaders-seen-drinking-495-champagne-at-trump-hotel/ |url-status=live}}</ref> After the meeting, Chatfield and Shirkey released a joint statement indicating that they would "follow the law" and would not attempt to have the legislature intervene in selecting electoral votes.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mlive.com/politics/2020/11/michigan-legislative-leaders-after-meeting-with-trump-we-will-follow-the-law.html |website=[[MLive.com]] |first=Emily |last=Lawler |title=Michigan legislative leaders after meeting with Trump: 'we will follow the law' |date=November 21, 2020 |access-date=January 6, 2023 |archive-date=May 16, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230516121717/https://www.mlive.com/politics/2020/11/michigan-legislative-leaders-after-meeting-with-trump-we-will-follow-the-law.html |url-status=live }}</ref> Chatfield later floated the possibility of a "constitutional crisis" in Michigan, while Shirkey suggested that certification be delayed; however, neither took any concrete action to invalidate Biden's victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.detroitnews.com/story/news/politics/2020/11/22/michigan-house-speaker-floats-possibility-constitutional-crisis/6381960002/ |title=Michigan House speaker floats possibility of 'constitutional crisis' |first=Craig |last=Mauger |date=November 22, 2020 |access-date=November 23, 2020 |archive-date=November 22, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201122205203/https://www.detroitnews.com/story/news/politics/2020/11/22/michigan-house-speaker-floats-possibility-constitutional-crisis/6381960002/ |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |website=[[MLive.com]] |first=Lauren |last=Gibbons |access-date=June 13, 2022 |url=https://www.mlive.com/public-interest/2020/12/michigans-top-gop-lawmakers-acknowledge-trumps-loss-wont-interfere-with-electoral-vote.html |title=Michigan's top GOP lawmakers acknowledge Trump's loss, won't interfere with electoral vote |date=December 14, 2020 |archive-date=April 8, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230408184215/https://www.mlive.com/public-interest/2020/12/michigans-top-gop-lawmakers-acknowledge-trumps-loss-wont-interfere-with-electoral-vote.html |url-status=live }}</ref> On November 21, Ronna McDaniel and [[Michigan Republican Party]] Chair [[Laura Cox (politician)|Laura Cox]] publicly called upon the Michigan State Board of Canvassers to not proceed with the planned certification of election results.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.wxyz.com/news/gop-leaders-ask-michigan-board-of-state-canvassers-to-delay-certification-of-results |title=GOP leaders ask Michigan Board of State Canvassers to delay certification of election results for 2 weeks |date=November 21, 2020 |work=[[WXYZ-TV]] |access-date=November 22, 2020 |archive-date=November 21, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201121192423/https://www.wxyz.com/news/gop-leaders-ask-michigan-board-of-state-canvassers-to-delay-certification-of-results |first=Fatima |last=Bangura |url-status=live}}</ref> On November 23, the State Board of Canvassers certified the election.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mlive.com/public-interest/2020/11/board-of-canvassers-certifies-michigans-election-results-in-3-1-vote.html |title=Board of Canvassers certifies Michigan's election results |date=November 23, 2020 |website=mlive |access-date=November 23, 2020 |archive-date=November 23, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201123214848/https://www.mlive.com/public-interest/2020/11/board-of-canvassers-certifies-michigans-election-results-in-3-1-vote.html |first=Zahra |last=Ahmad |url-status=live}}</ref>

===Attempt to seize voting machines in Michigan===
{{further information| Post-election lawsuits related to the 2020 United States presidential election from Michigan#Bailey v. Antrim County}}

Starting in November 2020, the Trump campaign attempted to get local law enforcement agencies to seize voting machines for the Trump operation to review. In one Michigan county, Trump advisors including Rudy Giuliani phoned the county prosecutor on or about November 20, 2020. They asked him to obtain the county's voting machines and turn them over to the Trump team. He refused, but a judge later ordered the machines to be made available to Trump representatives. They later produced a "forensic report" claiming evidence of fraud; election experts have said the conclusion was false and the report "critically flawed".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/investigations/2022/02/09/giuliani-antrim-prosecutor-voting-machines/ |title=Giuliani asked Michigan prosecutor to give voting machines to Trump team |last1=Swaine |first1=Jon |last2=Brown |first2=Emma |last3=Alemany |first3=Jacqueline |date=February 9, 2022 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=February 9, 2022 |archive-date=February 10, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220210030231/https://www.washingtonpost.com/investigations/2022/02/09/giuliani-antrim-prosecutor-voting-machines/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

At least one person was indicted for trying to illegally access voting machines after the election.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Oosting |first=Jonathan |date=July 27, 2023 |title='I have been indicted,' says suspect in Michigan vote machine tampering probe {{!}} Bridge Michigan |url=https://www.bridgemi.com/michigan-government/i-have-been-indicted-says-suspect-michigan-vote-machine-tampering-probe |access-date=2023-07-27 |website=[[Bridge Michigan]] |language=en |archive-date=July 27, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230727152241/https://www.bridgemi.com/michigan-government/i-have-been-indicted-says-suspect-michigan-vote-machine-tampering-probe |url-status=live }}</ref>

=== Georgia Secretary of State pressured to disqualify ballots ===
[[File:Lindsey Graham July 2015.jpg|thumb|140px|Sen. Lindsey Graham (R-SC) contacted the Georgia Secretary of State about invalidating ballots.]]
The [[2020 United States presidential election in Georgia]] produced an initial count wherein Biden defeated Trump by around 14,000 votes, triggering an automatic recount due to the small margin. On November 13, 2020, while the recount was ongoing, Senator [[Lindsey Graham]] of South Carolina privately called [[Georgia Secretary of State]] [[Brad Raffensperger]] to discuss Georgia's vote counting.<ref name="Gardner" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Evelyn |first1=Kenya |title=Lindsey Graham condemned for allegedly pressuring Georgia to toss out ballots |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/nov/17/lindsey-graham-georgia-ballot-tossing-pressure-condemned |access-date=24 October 2023 |work=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=Guardian News & Media Limited |date=17 November 2020 |archive-date=January 7, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220107155446/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/nov/17/lindsey-graham-georgia-ballot-tossing-pressure-condemned |url-status=live }}</ref> Raffensperger, a Republican, told ''[[The Washington Post]]'' that Graham had asked whether Raffensperger could disqualify all mail-in ballots in counties that had more signature errors.<ref name=Gardner>{{cite news |date=November 16, 2020 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/brad-raffensperger-georgia-vote/2020/11/16/6b6cb2f4-283e-11eb-8fa2-06e7cbb145c0_story.html |title=Ga. secretary of state says fellow Republicans are pressuring him to find ways to exclude ballots |last=Garder |first=Amy |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=November 17, 2020 |url-status=live |archive-date=November 17, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201117022415/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/brad-raffensperger-georgia-vote/2020/11/16/6b6cb2f4-283e-11eb-8fa2-06e7cbb145c0_story.html }}</ref> [[Gabriel Sterling]], a Republican election official and staffer to Raffensperger, was present for the call, and Sterling confirmed that Graham had asked that question.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gregorian |first1=Dareh |last2=Clark |first2=Dartunorro |title=Georgia officials spar with Sen. Lindsey Graham over alleged ballot tossing comments |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/georgia-secretary-state-raffensperger-says-sen-graham-asked-him-about-n1247968 |access-date=November 19, 2020 |work=[[NBC News]] |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=November 18, 2020 |url-status=live |archive-date=November 18, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201118193820/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/georgia-secretary-state-raffensperger-says-sen-graham-asked-him-about-n1247968}}</ref>

Raffensperger viewed Graham's question as a suggestion to throw out legally cast ballots, although Graham denied suggesting that. Graham acknowledged calling Raffensperger to find out how to "protect the integrity of mail-in voting" and "how does signature verification work?", but declared that if Raffensperger "feels threatened by that conversation, he's got a problem".<ref name=Gardner/> Graham stated that he was investigating in his own capacity as a senator, although he is the head of the Senate Judiciary Committee. Graham also claimed that he had spoken to the Secretaries of State in Arizona and Nevada. The Secretaries, however, denied this, and Graham then contradicted himself, stating that he had talked to the Governor of Arizona but no official in Nevada.<ref name=Kane>{{cite news |last1=Kane |first1=Paul |title=Lindsey Graham's one-man voting probe prompts confusion |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/powerpost/lindsey-graham-voting-inquiry/2020/11/17/bb67c33c-2917-11eb-9b14-ad872157ebc9_story.html |access-date=November 19, 2020 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=November 17, 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20201118001253/https://www.washingtonpost.com/powerpost/lindsey-graham-voting-inquiry/2020/11/17/bb67c33c-2917-11eb-9b14-ad872157ebc9_story.html |archive-date=November 18, 2020}}</ref>

=== Wisconsin recount-obstruction ===
{{further information| 2020 United States presidential election in Wisconsin#Aftermath}}
[[File:2020 Dane County recount (50997675059).jpg|thumb|[[Dane County, Wisconsin|Dane County]] recount being conducted at [[Monona Terrace]] in [[Madison, Wisconsin]]]]

On November 5, 2020, Andrew Iverson, head of Trump's Wisconsin campaign, told other campaign operatives in a strategy session: "Here's the deal: Comms is going to continue to fan the flame and get the word out about Democrats trying to steal this election. We'll do whatever they need. Just be on standby if there's any stunts we need to pull."{{efn|The audio was obtained by the Associated Press on February 2, 2023.}}<ref name="2023Feb3WashPost">{{Cite news |last=Bauer |first=Scott |date=February 3, 2023 |title=Trump campaign staff on 2020 election lies: 'fan the flame' |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230203023650/https://apnews.com/article/biden-politics-2022-midterm-elections-donald-trump-madison-166e3f52e42cc45cff8f28b75dd23cfc |archive-date=February 3, 2023 |newspaper=[[Associated Press]] |url=https://apnews.com/article/biden-politics-2022-midterm-elections-donald-trump-madison-166e3f52e42cc45cff8f28b75dd23cfc |url-status=live |access-date=February 3, 2023}}</ref>

The Trump campaign requested a recount in [[Milwaukee County, Wisconsin|Milwaukee]] and [[Dane County, Wisconsin|Dane]] counties, both Democratic strongholds. On November 20, 2020, Wisconsin election officials reported that Trump campaign observers were attempting to obstruct the recount. According to officials, observers were "constantly interrupting vote-counters with questions and comments". At one table, a Republican representative was objecting to every ballot that was pulled for recount. At other tables, there were two Republican observers when only one was allowed; it was also reported that some Republicans had been posing as independents.<ref name="aprecount">{{Cite web |first=Michael |last=Tarm |url=https://apnews.com/article/election-2020-joe-biden-donald-trump-wisconsin-elections-dcb7da95578fc7289122c6d372575a9b |title=Wisconsin officials: Trump observers obstructing recount |work=[[Associated Press]] |date=September 24, 2019 |access-date=November 22, 2020 |archive-date=November 21, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201121235446/https://apnews.com/article/election-2020-joe-biden-donald-trump-wisconsin-elections-dcb7da95578fc7289122c6d372575a9b |url-status=live}}</ref> Completed by November 29, the recounts ended up increasing Biden's lead by 87 votes.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.jsonline.com/story/news/politics/2020/11/29/dane-county-recount-show-biden-won-wisconsin-trump-prepares-lawsuit/6455880002/ |title=Biden gains 87 votes in Trump's $3 million Wisconsin recount as Dane County wraps up review. President plans lawsuit. |first=Patrick |last=Marley |website=Milwaukee Journal Sentinel |access-date=November 30, 2020 |archive-date=November 30, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201130002601/https://www.jsonline.com/story/news/politics/2020/11/29/dane-county-recount-show-biden-won-wisconsin-trump-prepares-lawsuit/6455880002/ |date=November 29, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>

=== Partisan hearings with Republican legislatures ===
On November 25, 2020, one day after Pennsylvania certified its election results, a Republican state senator requested a hearing of the State Senate Majority Policy Committee to discuss election issues. The event, described as an "informational meeting", was held at a hotel in Gettysburg and featured Rudy Giuliani asserting that the election had been subject to massive fraud. Trump also spoke to the group by speakerphone, repeating his false claim that he had actually won in Pennsylvania and other swing states, and saying "We have to turn the election over".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/trump-giuliani-gettysburg-pennsylvania-hearing-election-issues-alleged-irregularities-live-stream-today-2020-11-25/ |title=Trump phones in false claims at Pennsylvania Senate committee hearing on voting "irregularities" |date=November 25, 2020 |work=[[CBS News]] |access-date=November 26, 2020 |archive-date=November 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201126093524/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/trump-giuliani-gettysburg-pennsylvania-hearing-election-issues-alleged-irregularities-live-stream-today-2020-11-25/ |url-status=live}}</ref>

In Arizona, a state won by Biden, Republican members of the [[Arizona Senate]] promoted Trump's false claims of election fraud. In mid-December 2020, [[Eddie Farnsworth]], Chairman of the State Senate Judiciary Committee, claimed that "tampering" or "fraud" might have marred the election, despite the testimony given by election officials, attorneys, and the [[Arizona Attorney General]] Election Integrity Unit at a six-hour hearing, all of whom testified that there was no evidence for such claims.<ref>{{Cite news |first1=Jim |last1=Small |first2=Laura |last2=Gómez |url=https://www.azmirror.com/2020/12/14/arizona-senate-will-subpoena-maricopa-county-for-election-audit/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201215023208/https://www.azmirror.com/2020/12/14/arizona-senate-will-subpoena-maricopa-county-for-election-audit/ |access-date=June 13, 2022 |archive-date=December 15, 2020 |url-status=live |title=Arizona Senate will subpoena Maricopa County for election audit |newspaper=Arizona Mirror |date=December 14, 2020}}</ref> Hearings held in the [[Michigan Legislature]] similarly presented no evidence of any fraud or other wrongdoing.<ref>{{Cite news |first=Craig |last=Mauger |url=https://www.detroitnews.com/story/news/politics/2020/12/01/michigan-hearing-puts-spotlight-unproven-claims-election-fraud/6475762002/ |access-date=June 13, 2022 |title=Michigan Senate hearing puts new spotlight on unproven claims of election fraud |newspaper=[[The Detroit News]] |date=December 1, 2020 |archive-date=January 7, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107095208/https://www.detroitnews.com/story/news/politics/2020/12/01/michigan-hearing-puts-spotlight-unproven-claims-election-fraud/6475762002/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

=== Conspiracy allegations ===
Days before the 2020 presidential election, [[Dennis L. Montgomery|Dennis Montgomery]], a software designer with a history of making dubious claims, asserted that a program called Scorecard, running on a government [[supercomputer]] called Hammer, would be used to switch votes from Trump to Biden on voting machines. Trump legal team attorney [[Sidney Powell]] promoted the conspiracy theory on ''[[Lou Dobbs Tonight]]'' on November 6,<ref>{{Cite news |date=November 10, 2020 |title=Fact check: TV news clip does not show 'live computerized fraud' on Election Day 2020 |work=[[Reuters]] |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/uk-factcheck-cnn-not-evidence-vote-fraud-idUSKBN27P2TI |access-date=November 15, 2020 |archive-date=November 16, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201116100851/https://www.reuters.com/article/uk-factcheck-cnn-not-evidence-vote-fraud-idUSKBN27P2TI |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="auto"/> and again two days later on [[Maria Bartiromo]]'s [[Fox Business]] program, claiming to have "evidence that that is exactly what happened".<ref name="auto"/> She also asserted that the [[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]] ignored warnings about the software, and urged Trump to fire director [[Gina Haspel]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/11/20/us/politics/trump-lawsuits-election.html |title=Trump's Legal Team Sets a Precedent for Lowering the Bar |first=Mark |last=Leibovich |date=November 20, 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=November 30, 2020 |archive-date=November 25, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201125103925/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/11/20/us/politics/trump-lawsuits-election.html |url-status=live}}</ref> Christopher Krebs, director of the Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency (CISA), characterized the supercomputer claim as "nonsense" and a "hoax". CISA described the 2020 election as "the most secure in American history", with "no evidence that any voting system deleted or lost votes, changed votes or was in any way compromised".<ref name="auto">{{Cite web |url=https://www.factcheck.org/2020/11/bogus-theory-claims-supercomputer-switched-votes-in-election/ |title=Bogus Theory Claims Supercomputer Switched Votes in Election |first1=Angelo |last1=Fichera |first2=Saranac Hale |last2=Spencer |date=November 13, 2020 |website=FactCheck.org |access-date=November 15, 2020 |archive-date=November 15, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201115032246/https://www.factcheck.org/2020/11/bogus-theory-claims-supercomputer-switched-votes-in-election/ |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="auto2">{{Cite web |url=https://apnews.com/article/top-officials-elections-most-secure-66f9361084ccbc461e3bbf42861057a5 |title=Repudiating Trump, officials say election 'most secure' |date=November 13, 2020 |website=[[Associated Press]] |first1=Eric |last1=Tucker |first2=Frank |last2=Bajak |access-date=November 15, 2020 |archive-date=November 15, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201115030026/https://apnews.com/article/top-officials-elections-most-secure-66f9361084ccbc461e3bbf42861057a5 |url-status=live}}</ref> A few days later, Trump fired Krebs by tweet, claiming that Krebs' analysis was "highly inaccurate".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/11/17/politics/chris-krebs-fired-by-trump/index.html |title=Trump fires director of Homeland Security agency who had rejected President's election conspiracy theories |first1=Kaitlan |last1=Collins |first2=Paul |last2=LeBlanc |work=[[CNN]] |access-date=November 18, 2020 |archive-date=November 18, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201118003755/https://www.cnn.com/2020/11/17/politics/chris-krebs-fired-by-trump/index.html |date=November 18, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>

On November 13, 2020, the Trump campaign's deputy director of communications, Zach Parkinson, asked his staff to review the claims regarding the voting machines; the staff concluded these claims were baseless.<ref name="baseless"/>

During a November 19, 2020, press conference, Powell alleged without evidence that an international [[Communist]] plot had been engineered by Venezuela, Cuba, China, [[Hugo Chávez]] (who died in 2013), [[George Soros]], the [[Clinton Foundation]], and [[Antifa (United States)|antifa]] to rig the 2020 elections.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/article/who-is-sidney-powell.html |title=What We Know About Sidney Powell, the Lawyer Behind Wild Voting Conspiracy Theories |first1=Jeremy W. |last1=Peters |first2=Alan |last2=Feuer |date=December 8, 2020 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=March 30, 2021 |archive-date=June 29, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220629000714/https://www.nytimes.com/article/who-is-sidney-powell.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="craziest"/><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.politico.com/newsletters/playbook-pm/2020/11/19/rudy-490945 |title=POLITICO Playbook PM: Rudy. |first1=Jake |last1=Sherman |first2=Anna |last2=Palmer |first3=Garrett |last3=Ross |first4=Eli |last4=Okun |website=[[Politico]] |date=November 19, 2020 |access-date=November 19, 2020 |archive-date=November 20, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201120033527/https://www.politico.com/newsletters/playbook-pm/2020/11/19/rudy-490945 |url-status=live}}</ref> She also alleged that [[Dominion Voting Systems]] "can set and run an algorithm that probably ran all over the country to take a certain percentage of votes from President Trump and flip them to President Biden".<ref name="wild">{{Cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/11/19/politics/giuliani-trump-legal-team-press-briefing-fact-check/index.html |date=November 19, 2020 |title=Fact checking Giuliani and the Trump legal team's wild, fact-free press conference |first1=Tara |last1=Subramaniam |first2=Holmes |last2=Lybrand |work=[[CNN]] |access-date=November 20, 2020 |archive-date=November 20, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201120015606/https://www.cnn.com/2020/11/19/politics/giuliani-trump-legal-team-press-briefing-fact-check/index.html |url-status=live}}</ref> The source for many of these claims appeared to be the [[far-right]] news organization [[One America News Network]] (OANN). She also repeated a conspiracy theory<ref name="cnn_2020-11-17"/> spread by Texan Congressman [[Louis Gohmert|Louie Gohmert]], OANN and others:<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/11/20/technology/trump-allies-are-among-the-frequent-purveyors-of-election-misinformation.html |title=Trump allies are among the frequent purveyors of election misinformation. |first=Linda |last=Qiu |date=November 20, 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=November 30, 2020 |archive-date=November 30, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201130004015/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/11/20/technology/trump-allies-are-among-the-frequent-purveyors-of-election-misinformation.html |url-status=live}}</ref> that accurate voting results had been transmitted to the German office of the Spanish [[electronic voting]] firm [[Scytl]], where they were tabulated to reveal a landslide victory for Trump nationwide (which included implausible Trump victories in Democratic strongholds such as [[California]], [[Colorado]], [[Maine]] statewide, [[Minnesota]], and [[New Mexico]]), after which a company server was supposedly seized in a raid by the United States Army. The U.S. Army and Scytl refuted those claims:<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Joffe-Block |first1=Jude |url=https://apnews.com/article/fact-checking-afs:Content:9754011363 |title=False reports claim election servers were seized in Germany |date=November 14, 2020 |work=[[Associated Press]] |access-date=November 22, 2020 |archive-date=November 15, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201115091412/https://apnews.com/article/fact-checking-afs:Content:9754011363 |url-status=live}}</ref> Scytl has not had any offices in Germany since September 2019, and it does not tabulate any U.S. votes.<ref name="scytl-pr-13-nov">{{Cite web |title=Scytl strongly denies the false information related to the U.S. elections |url=https://www.scytl.com/fact-checking-regarding-us-elections-debunking-fake-news/ |website=Scytl |access-date=November 21, 2020 |date=November 13, 2020 |archive-date=November 20, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201120201610/https://www.scytl.com/en/fact-checking-regarding-us-elections-debunking-fake-news/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="nyt-scytl">{{Cite web |last1=Roose |first1=Kevin |title=No, the Army didn't seize a German server showing a Trump landslide |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/11/18/technology/scytl-trump.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=November 21, 2020 |date=November 18, 2020 |archive-date=November 21, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201121025922/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/11/18/technology/scytl-trump.html |url-status=live}}</ref> In a March 2021 report, the Justice and Homeland Security Departments flatly rejected accusations of voting fraud conducted by foreign nations.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/03/16/us/politics/election-interference-russia-2020-assessment.html |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20211228/https://www.nytimes.com/2021/03/16/us/politics/election-interference-russia-2020-assessment.html |url-status=live |access-date=June 13, 2022 |archive-date=December 28, 2021 |url-access=limited |title=Russian Interference in 2020 Included Influencing Trump Associates, Report Says |first=Julian E. |last=Barnes |date=March 16, 2021 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] }}{{cbignore}}</ref> Rudy Giuliani also spoke at this press conference. In a private text message, [[Rupert Murdoch]] described the Powell–Giuliani presentation as "really crazy stuff, and damaging".<ref>{{Cite web |last=Papenfuss |first=Mary |date=2023-02-18 |title=Even Rupert Murdoch Ripped Rudy Giuliani's 'Crazy' Election Press Conference: Court Filing |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/rupert-murdoch-rudy-giuliani-rigged-election-dominion_n_63f0527de4b0a209e827b92f |access-date=2023-02-18 |website=[[HuffPost]]|language=en |archive-date=February 18, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230218131048/https://www.huffpost.com/entry/rupert-murdoch-rudy-giuliani-rigged-election-dominion_n_63f0527de4b0a209e827b92f |url-status=live }}</ref>

In a subsequent interview with [[Newsmax]] on November 21, 2020,<ref>{{Cite web |date=November 22, 2020 |title=Trump lawyer Sidney Powell said that the Georgia election lawsuit "will be biblical," suggests GOP governor helped Biden |url=https://www.newsweek.com/trump-lawyer-sidney-powell-says-georgia-election-lawsuit-will-biblical-suggests-gop-governor-1549333 |first=Alexandra |last=Garrett |access-date=November 23, 2020 |website=[[Newsweek]] |archive-date=November 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201129180527/https://www.newsweek.com/trump-lawyer-sidney-powell-says-georgia-election-lawsuit-will-biblical-suggests-gop-governor-1549333 |url-status=live}}</ref> Powell accused [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia's]] Republican governor, [[Brian Kemp]], of being "in on the Dominion scam" and suggested financial impropriety.<ref>{{Cite web |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=November 23, 2020 |title=Trump campaign cuts ties with attorney Sidney Powell after bizarre election fraud claims |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/nov/23/trump-campaign-cuts-ties-with-attorney-sidney-powell-after-bizarre-election-claims |access-date=November 23, 2020 |website=[[The Guardian]] |archive-date=November 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201127113339/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/nov/23/trump-campaign-cuts-ties-with-attorney-sidney-powell-after-bizarre-election-claims |url-status=live}}</ref> Powell additionally alleged that fraud had prevented [[Doug Collins (politician)|Doug Collins]] from winning a top-two position in the November 2020 [[nonpartisan blanket primary]] against incumbent [[Kelly Loeffler]] in the [[2020–21 United States Senate special election in Georgia|Senate race in Georgia]].<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Haberman |first1=Maggie |last2=Feuer |first2=Alan |title=Trump Team Disavows Lawyer Who Peddled Conspiracy Theories on Voting |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/11/22/us/politics/sidney-powell-trump.html |access-date=November 26, 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=November 22, 2020 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20201123043554/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/11/22/us/politics/sidney-powell-trump.html |archive-date=November 23, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> She also claimed that the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] had used rigged Dominion machines to defeat [[Bernie Sanders]] in the 2016 primary and that Sanders had learned of this but had "sold out".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mediaite.com/election-2020/trump-lawyer-sidney-powell-accuses-georgia-gov-brian-kemp-and-bernie-sanders-of-complicity-in-bonkers-voting-machine-conspiracy/ |first=Josh |last=Feldman |title=Sidney Powell Goes After Brian Kemp Over Election Conspiracy |date=November 22, 2020 |publisher=Mediaite |access-date=November 22, 2020 |archive-date=November 22, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201122191809/https://www.mediaite.com/election-2020/trump-lawyer-sidney-powell-accuses-georgia-gov-brian-kemp-and-bernie-sanders-of-complicity-in-bonkers-voting-machine-conspiracy/ |url-status=live}}</ref> She stated that she would "blow up" Georgia with a "biblical" court filing.<ref>{{Cite news |date=November 23, 2020 |title=Sidney Powell: Trump team cuts ties with lawyer who peddled bizarre fraud claims |work=[[BBC News]] |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/election-us-2020-55040756 |access-date=November 24, 2020 |archive-date=November 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201127091302/https://www.bbc.com/news/election-us-2020-55040756 |url-status=live}}</ref> Powell suggested that candidates "paid to have the system rigged to work for them".<ref>{{Cite web |last=Vella |first=Lauren |date=November 19, 2020 |title=Ernst: Trump lawyer claim that candidates pay to rig elections 'absolutely outrageous' |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/senate/526798-ernst-trump-lawyer-claim-that-candidates-pay-to-rig-elections-absolutely |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201120033548/https://thehill.com/homenews/senate/526798-ernst-trump-lawyer-claim-that-candidates-pay-to-rig-elections-absolutely |archive-date=November 20, 2020 |access-date=November 20, 2020 |website=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] }}</ref> On the basis of these claims, Powell called for Republican-controlled [[State legislature (United States)|state legislatures]] in swing states to disregard the election results and appoint a [[Slate (elections)|slate]] of "loyal" [[United States Electoral College#Electors|electors]] who would vote to re-elect Trump,<ref>{{Cite web |last=Smith |first=David |date=November 21, 2020 |title=Trump makes futile last stand to overturn results as Georgia certifies Biden win |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/nov/20/trump-michigan-republicans-election |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201121060545/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/nov/20/trump-michigan-republicans-election |archive-date=November 21, 2020 |access-date=November 21, 2020 |website=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> based on authority supposedly resting in [[Article Two of the United States Constitution#Clause 2: Method of choosing electors|Article Two of the Constitution]].<ref>{{Cite tweet |user=JasonSCampbell |first=Jason |last=Campbell |number=1329549873516048387 |title=Sidney Powell: "The entire election, frankly, in all the swing states should be overturned and the legislatures should make sure that the electors are selected for Trump" |access-date=November 20, 2020 |archive-date=November 20, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201120033548/https://twitter.com/JasonSCampbell/status/1329549873516048387 |date=November 19, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> ''The Washington Post'' reported that on December 5 Trump asked Kemp to convene a special session of the Georgia legislature for that purpose, but Kemp declined.<ref name=KempLegis>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trump-kemp-call-georgia/2020/12/05/fd8d677c-3721-11eb-8d38-6aea1adb3839_story.html |title=Trump calls Georgia governor to pressure him for help overturning Biden's win in the state |first1=Amy |last1=Gardner |first2=Colby |last2=Itkowitz |first3=Josh |last3=Dawsey |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=December 5, 2020 |access-date=December 5, 2020 |archive-date=December 5, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201205192533/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trump-kemp-call-georgia/2020/12/05/fd8d677c-3721-11eb-8d38-6aea1adb3839_story.html |url-status=live}}</ref> Trump also pressured Pennsylvania Speaker of the House [[Bryan Cutler]] to overturn the result and use electors loyal to Trump, but Cutler declined, saying that the legislature had no power to overturn the state's chosen slate of electors.<ref name="trump asks"/>

Conservative television outlets amplified baseless allegations of voting machine fraud. Fox News host [[Lou Dobbs]] had been outspoken during his program supporting the allegations, but on December 18 his program aired a video segment debunking the allegations, although Dobbs himself did not comment. Fox News hosts [[Jeanine Pirro]] and [[Maria Bartiromo]] had also been outspoken in supporting the allegations, and both their programs aired the same video segment debunking the allegations over the following two days.<ref name=":2">{{Cite news |work=Mediaite |access-date=January 5, 2021 |url=https://www.mediaite.com/tv/lou-dobbs-airs-stunning-fact-check-of-his-own-election-conspiracies-after-company-threatens-legal-action/ |first=Josh |last=Feldman |title=Lou Dobbs Airs Stunning Fact-Check of His Own Election Claims |date=December 18, 2020 |archive-date=January 7, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107042912/https://www.mediaite.com/tv/lou-dobbs-airs-stunning-fact-check-of-his-own-election-conspiracies-after-company-threatens-legal-action/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

[[Smartmatic]], a company accused of conspiring with Dominion, demanded a retraction from Fox News. Smartmatic wanted corrections to be "published on multiple occasions" during prime time to "match the attention and audience targeted with the original defamatory publications". They also threatened legal action.<ref name=":2" /><ref>{{Cite web |access-date=June 13, 2022 |url=https://www.mediaite.com/tv/maria-bartiromo-airs-same-fact-check-of-election-conspiracies-as-fox-colleagues-adds-we-will-keep-investigating/ |work=Mediaite |first=Josh |last=Feldman |title=Maria Bartiromo Airs Fact-Check, Adds 'We Will Keep Investigating' |date=December 20, 2020 |archive-date=January 11, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210111033201/https://www.mediaite.com/tv/maria-bartiromo-airs-same-fact-check-of-election-conspiracies-as-fox-colleagues-adds-we-will-keep-investigating/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/media/2020/12/19/lou-dobbs-debunk-fact-check-smartmatic/ |access-date=June 13, 2022 |date=December 19, 2020 |title=Lou Dobbs debunks his own claims of election fraud – after a legal demand from Smartmatic |first=Jeremy |last=Barr |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |archive-date=January 11, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210111034649/https://www.washingtonpost.com/media/2020/12/19/lou-dobbs-debunk-fact-check-smartmatic/ |url-status=live }}</ref> On February 4, 2021, Smartmatic filed a lawsuit against Dobbs, Bartiromo, Pirro, and Fox News itself, as well as against Rudy Giuliani and Sidney Powell, seeking $2.7 billion in total damages.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Darcy |first=Oliver |date=February 4, 2021 |title=Voting technology company Smartmatic files $2.7 billion lawsuit against Fox News, Rudy Giuliani and Sidney Powell over 'disinformation campaign' |url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/02/04/media/smartmatic-fox-news-giuliani-powell-lawsuit/index.html |access-date=February 4, 2021 |website=[[CNN]] |archive-date=February 4, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210204230219/https://www.cnn.com/2021/02/04/media/smartmatic-fox-news-giuliani-powell-lawsuit/index.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

In December 2020, Dominion sent a similar letter to Sidney Powell, demanding that she retract her allegations and retain all relevant records; the Trump legal team later instructed dozens of staffers to preserve all documents for any future litigation.<ref>{{Cite news |access-date=June 13, 2022 |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/12/19/politics/trump-campaign-sidney-powell-dominion-voting-systems/index.html |date=December 19, 2020 |title=Trump campaign told to preserve all documents related to Sidney Powell and Dominion Voting Systems |first=Kaitlan |last=Collins |website=[[CNN]] |archive-date=December 21, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201221140236/https://www.cnn.com/2020/12/19/politics/trump-campaign-sidney-powell-dominion-voting-systems/index.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://lawandcrime.com/2020-election/days-after-smartmatics-legal-threat-dominion-voting-systems-follows-suit-with-demand-letter-to-sidney-powell/ |website=lawandcrime.com |first=Matt |last=Naham |access-date=January 5, 2021 |title=Days After Smartmatic's Legal Threat, Dominion Voting Systems Follows Suit with Demand Letter to Sidney Powell |date=December 17, 2020 |archive-date=January 7, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107044142/https://lawandcrime.com/2020-election/days-after-smartmatics-legal-threat-dominion-voting-systems-follows-suit-with-demand-letter-to-sidney-powell/ |url-status=live }}</ref> The company filed $1.3 billion defamation suits against Powell in January 2021.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://apnews.com/article/dominion-lawsuit-sidney-powell-0031ce89ba24bdeae0402861e20ede69 |date=January 8, 2021 |title=Dominion sues Trump lawyer Sidney Powell for defamation |work=[[Associated Press]] |access-date=March 30, 2021 |archive-date=January 14, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210114062256/https://apnews.com/article/dominion-lawsuit-sidney-powell-0031ce89ba24bdeae0402861e20ede69 |url-status=live }}</ref> While fighting the lawsuit in March 2021, Powell's attorneys claimed that her speech was protected because she was sharing her "opinion" and that, because she was serving as an attorney for the Trump campaign, it was her role to make accusations against Dominion. Dominion had complained that Powell's comments were "wild", "outlandish", and "impossible". Powell's attorneys seemed to concede that Powell had been obviously lying, saying that "reasonable people would not accept such statements as fact" and therefore that she had not defamed Dominion.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Polantz |first=Katelyn |date=March 23, 2021 |title=Sidney Powell argues in new court filing that no reasonable people would believe her election fraud claims |url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/03/22/politics/sidney-powell-dominion-lawsuit-election-fraud/index.html |access-date=March 23, 2021 |website=[[CNN]] |archive-date=March 23, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210323020540/https://www.cnn.com/2021/03/22/politics/sidney-powell-dominion-lawsuit-election-fraud/index.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

In internal Fox News communications, several prominent network hosts and senior executives—including chairman [[Rupert Murdoch]] and CEO [[Suzanne Scott]]—discussed their knowledge that the election fraud allegations they were reporting were false. The communications showed the network was concerned that not reporting the falsehoods would alienate viewers and cause them to switch to rival conservative networks, impacting corporate profitability.<ref>{{cite news |title=Fox Stars Privately Expressed Disbelief About Election Fraud Claims. 'Crazy Stuff.' |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2023/02/16/business/media/fox-dominion-lawsuit.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=February 16, 2023 |author1=Jeremy W. Peters |author2=Katie Robertson |access-date=February 18, 2023 |archive-date=April 19, 2023 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20230419071342/https://www.nytimes.com/2023/02/16/business/media/fox-dominion-lawsuit.html |url-status=live }} See also [https://int.nyt.com/data/documenttools/redacted-documents-in-dominion-fox-news-case/dca5e3880422426f/full.pdf the brief itself.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230405063319/https://int.nyt.com/data/documenttools/redacted-documents-in-dominion-fox-news-case/dca5e3880422426f/full.pdf |date=April 5, 2023 }}</ref> In a deposition in the Dominion Voting Systems lawsuit, Murdoch said: "I would have liked us to be stronger in denouncing it [the false allegations], in hindsight".<ref>{{Cite web |last=Darcy |first=Oliver |date=2023-02-27 |title=Rupert Murdoch acknowledged that Fox News hosts endorsed false stolen election claims |url=https://www.cnn.com/2023/02/27/media/dominion-fox-news/index.html |access-date=2023-02-28 |website=[[CNN Business]] |language=en |archive-date=February 28, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230228000358/https://www.cnn.com/2023/02/27/media/dominion-fox-news/index.html |url-status=live }}</ref> The communications and deposition were reported in February 2023.

=== Threats of violence by Trump supporters ===
After Biden won the election, angry Trump supporters threatened election officials, election officials' family members, and elections staff in at least eight states via emails, telephone calls and letters; some of the menacing and vitriolic communications included [[death threats]]. Officials terrorized by the threats included officials in the swing states of Wisconsin, Pennsylvania, Michigan, Nevada, and Arizona, as well as a few less competitive states.<ref name=Wines>{{Cite web |first=Michael |last=Wines |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/12/03/us/election-officials-threats-trump.html |title=Here Are the Threats Terrorizing Election Workers |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=December 3, 2020 |access-date=June 13, 2022 |archive-date=January 11, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210111163251/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/12/03/us/election-officials-threats-trump.html |url-status=live }}</ref> Some officials had to seek police protection<ref name=Wines/><ref name=PilkingtonLevine>{{Cite web |first1=Ed |last1=Pilkington |first2=Sam |last2=Levine |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/dec/09/trump-voter-fraud-threats-violence-militia |access-date=January 5, 2021 |title='It's surreal': the US officials facing violent threats as Trump claims voter fraud |date=December 9, 2020 |archive-date=January 5, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210105031615/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/dec/09/trump-voter-fraud-threats-violence-militia |url-status=live }}</ref> or move from their homes due to the threats.<ref name=Wines/> The director of the nonpartisan, nonprofit Center for Election Innovation & Research, described the threats as frightening and said, "These threats often go into areas related to race or sex or [[anti-Semitism]]. More than once they specifically refer to gun violence." Prominent Republicans ignored or said little about the threats of violence.<ref name=Wines/>

On November 15, the Georgia Secretary of State reported that he and his wife were receiving death threats.<ref name=Gardner/> On November 30, Trump attorney [[Joseph diGenova]] said the recently fired head of the Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency, [[Chris Krebs]], should be "taken out and shot" for disputing the president's claims about election fraud.<ref name="taken out and shot">{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/dec/01/trump-lawyer-joe-digenova-election-security-chief-chris-krebs-shot |title=Trump lawyer: ex-election security chief Krebs should be 'taken out and shot' |date=December 1, 2020 |website=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=December 3, 2020 |archive-date=December 2, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201202074438/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/dec/01/trump-lawyer-joe-digenova-election-security-chief-chris-krebs-shot |first=Martin |last=Pengelly |url-status=live}}</ref> On December 1, Republican Georgia elections official Gabriel Sterling publicly condemned Trump and Georgia Senators [[David Perdue|Perdue]] and Loeffler for making unsubstantiated claims and for failing to condemn the threats of violence against election workers, including those made against a young, low-level Dominion employee and his family.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/12/01/georgia-election-official-condemns-trump-441879 |title=Georgia election official condemns Trump after threat to worker |first=Zach |last=Montellaro |website=[[Politico]] |access-date=December 2, 2020 |archive-date=December 2, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201202004229/https://www.politico.com/news/2020/12/01/georgia-election-official-condemns-trump-441879 |date=December 1, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> After Democratic Georgia State Senator [[Elena Parent]] spoke out against the false claims of voter fraud, she was targeted by online vitriol, threatened with death and sexual violence, and had her home address widely circulated online. Parent attributed the onslaught to Trump, saying, "He has created a cult-like following and is exposing people like me across the country to danger because of his unfounded rhetoric on the election".<ref name=PilkingtonLevine/>

In early December, an "enemies list" circulated on the web falsely accusing various government officials and voting systems executives of rigging the election, providing their home addresses, and superimposing red targets on their photos.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/public-officials-threatened-covid-election/2020/12/13/680bd380-3be7-11eb-bc68-96af0daae728_story.html |date=December 13, 2020 |title='A dark, empty place:' Public officials face personal threats as tensions flare |first1=Hannah |last1=Knowles |first2=Annie |last2=Gowen |first3=Tom |last3=Hamburger |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=June 13, 2022 |archive-date=January 9, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210109163849/https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/public-officials-threatened-covid-election/2020/12/13/680bd380-3be7-11eb-bc68-96af0daae728_story.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

The [[Arizona Republican Party]] twice tweeted that supporters should be willing to "die for something" or "give my life for this fight". Ann Jacobs, chairwoman of the [[Wisconsin Elections Commission]], said she had received constant threats, including a message mentioning her children, and photos of her house had been posted on the web.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/12/08/us/politics/trump-election-challenges.html |title=As Trump Rails Against Loss, His Supporters Become More Threatening |first1=Nick |last1=Corasaniti |first2=Jim |last2=Rutenberg |first3=Kathleen |last3=Gray |date=December 9, 2020 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=June 13, 2022 |archive-date=January 11, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210111143941/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/12/08/us/politics/trump-election-challenges.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

On January 1, 2021, Vice President [[Mike Pence]] asked a federal judge to dismiss a suit naming him as the defendant; filed by Texas Republican congressman [[Louis Gohmert]] and others, the ultimately unsuccessful suit asserted that the vice president had the sole constitutional authority to conduct the congressional certification of Electoral College results without restriction.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://thehill.com/regulation/court-battles/532390-appeals-court-dismisses-gohmerts-election-suit-against-pence |title=Appeals court dismisses Gohmert's election suit against Pence |first=Lauren |last=Vella |date=January 2, 2021 |website=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |access-date=January 5, 2021 |archive-date=January 3, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210103015532/https://thehill.com/regulation/court-battles/532390-appeals-court-dismisses-gohmerts-election-suit-against-pence }}</ref> Attorney [[Lin Wood]], a conspiracy theorist and [[QAnon]] promoter who had worked with Trump attorney [[Sidney Powell]] to file baseless lawsuits alleging election fraud, tweeted that day that Pence and other prominent Republican officials should be arrested for treason and that Pence should "face execution by firing squad".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/trump-pence-wood-firing-squad-b1781554.html |first=Gustaf |last=Kilander |access-date=January 5, 2021 |title=Trump election lawyer Lin Wood calls for Pence to be 'executed by firing squad' |date=January 2, 2021 |website=[[The Independent]] |archive-date=January 5, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210105040449/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/trump-pence-wood-firing-squad-b1781554.html |url-status=live }}</ref> Two weeks earlier, Wood had tweeted that people should stock up on survival goods, including "2nd Amendment supplies". [[Emerald Robinson]], a White House correspondent for pro-Trump [[One America News]], tweeted "Folks, when [Lin Wood] tells people to prep, I listen".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-election-2020/donald-trump-lawyer-lin-wood-second-amendment-georgia-b1774253.html |first=James |last=Crump |title=Trump election lawyer calls on his supporters to stock up on '2nd Amendment supplies' |date=December 15, 2020 |website=[[The Independent]] |access-date=January 5, 2021 |archive-date=January 4, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210104234631/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-election-2020/donald-trump-lawyer-lin-wood-second-amendment-georgia-b1774253.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

After Trump urged his supporters to protest in Washington as Congress convened to certify the election results, some posters in far-right online forums interpreted it as a call to action, with one asserting, "We've got marching orders", while others made references to possible violence and to bringing firearms to the protest. In a discussion of how to evade police blockades and the District of Columbia's gun laws, one poster remarked, "We The People, Will not tolerate a Steal. No retreat, No Surrender. Restore to my President what you stole or reap the consequences!!!"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2021/01/05/parler-telegram-violence-dc-protests/ |access-date=June 13, 2022 |date=January 5, 2021 |title=Pro-Trump forums erupt with violent threats ahead of Wednesday's rally against the 2020 election |first1=Craig |last1=Timberg |first2=Drew |last2=Harwell |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |archive-date=January 7, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107115438/https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2021/01/05/parler-telegram-violence-dc-protests/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/tech/internet/violent-threats-ripple-through-far-right-internet-forums-ahead-protest-n1252923 |date=January 6, 2021 |first1=Brandy |last1=Zadrozny |first2=Ben |last2=Collins |title=Violent threats ripple through far-right internet forums ahead of protest |website=[[NBC News]] |access-date=June 13, 2022 |archive-date=January 10, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210110233442/https://www.nbcnews.com/tech/internet/violent-threats-ripple-through-far-right-internet-forums-ahead-protest-n1252923 |url-status=live }}</ref>

== December 2020 ==

On December 1, 2020, [[U.S. Attorney General]] [[William Barr]] said U.S. attorneys and [[FBI]] agents had investigated complaints and allegations of fraud, but found none of significance.<ref name="disputing trump" /><ref name="NYT-20210131" /><ref name="NYT-20210201mr">{{Cite news |last1=Rosenberg |first1=Matthew |last2=Rutenberg |first2=Jim |date=February 1, 2021 |title=Key Takeaways From Trump's Effort to Overturn the Election – A Times examination of the 77 days between election and inauguration shows how a lie the former president had been grooming for years overwhelmed the Republican Party and stoked the assault on the Capitol. |work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/02/01/us/politics/trump-election-results.html |url-access=limited |access-date=February 1, 2021 |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20211228/https://www.nytimes.com/2021/02/01/us/politics/trump-election-results.html |archive-date=2021-12-28 |url-status=live }}{{cbignore}}</ref><ref>Multiple sources:
* {{Cite web |last=Schouten |first=Fredreka |date=December 3, 2020 |title=Trump raises more than $207 million since Election Day as he pushes baseless election fraud claims |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/12/03/politics/trump-fundraising-election-day/index.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201208201016/https://www.cnn.com/2020/12/03/politics/trump-fundraising-election-day/index.html |archive-date=December 8, 2020 |access-date=December 4, 2020 |work=[[CNN]] }}
* {{Cite news |last1=Dawsey |first1=Josh |last2=Lee |first2=Michelle Ye Hee |title=Trump raises more than $150 million appealing to false election claims |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trump-raises-more-than-150-million-appealing-to-false-election-claims/2020/11/30/82e922e6-3347-11eb-afe6-e4dbee9689f8_story.html |url-status=live |access-date=December 1, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201201030712/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trump-raises-more-than-150-million-appealing-to-false-election-claims/2020/11/30/82e922e6-3347-11eb-afe6-e4dbee9689f8_story.html |date=December 1, 2020 |archive-date=December 1, 2020 }}
* {{Cite web |last1=Goldmacher |first1=Shane |last2=Haberman |first2=Maggie |date=December 1, 2020 |title=Trump Raises $170 Million as He Denies His Loss and Eyes the Future |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/11/30/us/politics/trump-campaign-donations.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201201203150/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/11/30/us/politics/trump-campaign-donations.html |archive-date=December 1, 2020 |access-date=December 1, 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] }}
* {{Cite news |last1=Renshaw |first1=Jarrett |last2=Tanfani |first2=Joseph |date=November 11, 2020 |title=Donations under $8K to Trump 'election defense' instead go to president, RNC |work=[[Reuters]] |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-election-trump-fundraising-insigh/donations-under-8k-to-trump-election-defense-instead-go-to-president-rnc-idUSKBN27R309 |access-date=June 15, 2022 |archive-date=April 9, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230409171913/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-election-trump-fundraising-insigh/donations-under-8k-to-trump-election-defense-instead-go-to-president-rnc-idUSKBN27R309 |url-status=live }}</ref> On December 3, 2020, [[Director of National Intelligence]] [[John Ratcliffe (American politician)|John Ratcliffe]] said no evidence had yet been found of [[Foreign electoral intervention|foreign interference]].<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Herridge |first1=Catherine |last2=Quinn |first2=Melissa |date=3 December 2020 |title=Ratcliffe says Biden getting "all of the same intelligence" as Trump, warns of China threat |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/dni-ratcliffe-biden-intelligence-china-threat/ |access-date=2022-06-13 |website=[[CBS News]] |language=en-US |archive-date=October 13, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211013200736/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/dni-ratcliffe-biden-intelligence-china-threat/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last1=Polantz |first1=Katelyn |last2=Cohen |first2=Zachary |last3=Perez |first3=Evan |date=August 6, 2021 |title=How a Trump environmental lawyer tried to weaponize the Justice Department to help the President |url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/08/06/politics/doj-clark-trump-election/index.html |website=[[CNN]] |access-date=June 15, 2022 |archive-date=November 26, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211126202014/https://www.cnn.com/2021/08/06/politics/doj-clark-trump-election/index.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

Former Trump [[National Security Advisor (United States)|National Security Advisor]] [[Michael Flynn]], who had received a presidential pardon shortly after the election, on December 1 publicly called on the president to [[Martial law in the United States|suspend the Constitution]], silence the press, and hold a new election under military supervision.<ref>Multiple sources:
* {{Cite web |last=Vallejo |first=Justin |date=December 3, 2020 |title=Michael Flynn calls for Trump to suspend the constitution and declare martial law to re-run election |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-election-2020/michael-flynn-suspend-constitution-martial-law-trump-reelection-b1765467.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201208201019/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-election-2020/michael-flynn-suspend-constitution-martial-law-trump-reelection-b1765467.html |archive-date=December 8, 2020 |access-date=December 4, 2020 |website=[[The Independent]]}}
* {{Cite web |last=Krawczyk |first=Kathryn |date=December 2, 2020 |title=Freshly pardoned Michael Flynn shares message telling Trump to 'suspend the Constitution' to hold a new presidential election |url=https://theweek.com/speedreads/952902/freshly-pardoned-michael-flynn-shares-message-telling-trump-suspend-constitution-hold-new-presidential-election |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201208201112/https://theweek.com/speedreads/952902/freshly-pardoned-michael-flynn-shares-message-telling-trump-suspend-constitution-hold-new-presidential-election |archive-date=December 8, 2020 |access-date=December 3, 2020 |website=The Week}}
* {{Cite web |last=Meyer |first=Ken |date=December 2, 2020 |title=Michael Flynn Calls for Trump to 'Suspend the Constitution,' Impose Martial Law |url=https://www.mediaite.com/politics/michael-flynn-newly-pardoned-calls-for-trump-to-temporarily-suspend-the-constitution-and-impose-martial-law-edited/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201208200941/https://www.mediaite.com/politics/michael-flynn-newly-pardoned-calls-for-trump-to-temporarily-suspend-the-constitution-and-impose-martial-law-edited/ |archive-date=December 8, 2020 |access-date=December 3, 2020 |work=[[Mediaite]]}}</ref>

=== Trump's attempt to pressure state officials ===
On December 5, Trump placed a call to Georgia governor [[Brian Kemp]] in which he urged the governor to call a special session of the state legislature to override the election results and appoint electors who would support Trump.<ref name=KempLegis /> He also called the Pennsylvania speaker of the house with similar objectives, and had earlier invited Michigan Republican state officials to the White House to discuss election results in that state.<ref name=KempLegis /><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2020/11/19/wayne-county-rescind-certifying-election/ |title=Trump invites Michigan Republican leaders to meet him at White House as he escalates attempts to overturn election results |first1=Tom |last1=Hamburger |first2=Kayla |last2=Ruble |first3=David A. |last3=Fahrenthold |first4=Josh |last4=Dawsey |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=December 8, 2020 |archive-date=December 2, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201202072754/https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2020/11/19/wayne-county-rescind-certifying-election/ |date=November 19, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> The Georgia and Pennsylvania contacts were made after Biden's victories had been certified in those states; Biden's Michigan victory was certified three days after the Trump White House meeting.<ref name=scolforo>{{Cite news |first=Mark |last=Scolforo |url=https://apnews.com/article/election-2020-joe-biden-donald-trump-pennsylvania-elections-8a61a1609d7a0d60c1db13fa8e7c3019 |title=Biden certified as winner of Pennsylvania presidential vote |date=November 24, 2020 |website=[[Associated Press]] |access-date=December 8, 2020 |archive-date=November 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201127172320/https://apnews.com/article/election-2020-joe-biden-donald-trump-pennsylvania-elections-8a61a1609d7a0d60c1db13fa8e7c3019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="georgia officials">{{Cite web |url=https://apnews.com/article/georgia-certify-election-joe-biden-ea8f867d740f3d7d42d0a55c1aef9e69 |first=Kate |last=Brumback |title=Georgia officials certify election results showing Biden win |date=November 20, 2020 |website=[[Associated Press]] |access-date=December 7, 2020 |archive-date=December 1, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201201174512/https://apnews.com/article/georgia-certify-election-joe-biden-ea8f867d740f3d7d42d0a55c1aef9e69 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/11/23/politics/michigan-certify-election-results-monday/index.html |date=November 23, 2020 |title=Michigan's state board certifies Biden's win |first1=Annie |last1=Grayer |first2=Jeremy |last2=Herb |first3=Chandelis |last3=Duster |work=[[CNN]] |access-date=December 8, 2020 |archive-date=December 1, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201201161817/https://www.cnn.com/2020/11/23/politics/michigan-certify-election-results-monday/index.html |url-status=live}}</ref>

After Georgia had twice recounted and twice certified its results, Republican secretary of state [[Brad Raffensperger]] received death threats. He was pressured to resign by others in his party, including the state's two senators.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/11/11/us/brad-raffensperger-georgia.html |access-date=March 30, 2021 |title=Georgia's Close Elections Sent Republicans After a Republican |first1=Richard |last1=Fausset |first2=Stephanie |last2=Saul |date=November 12, 2020 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |archive-date=May 16, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230516134115/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/11/11/us/brad-raffensperger-georgia.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mediaite.com/tv/brad-raffensperger-responds-to-death-threats-irrational-behavior-over-ga-election-results-its-unpatriotic/ |first=Ken |last=Meyer |website=Mediaite |access-date=January 5, 2021 |title=Brad Raffensperger Responds to Death Threats, 'Irrational' Behavior Over GA Election Results |date=December 6, 2020 |archive-date=December 14, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201214150321/https://www.mediaite.com/tv/brad-raffensperger-responds-to-death-threats-irrational-behavior-over-ga-election-results-its-unpatriotic/ |url-status=live }}</ref> On December 23, Trump called the investigations chief in the Georgia Secretary of State's office, who was then investigating allegations of mail ballot fraud, and urged the official to "find the fraud" (a misquote that was amended by ''The Washington Post'' in March 2021 to "[you would] find things that are gonna be unbelievable");<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/correction-trump-georgia-story/2021/03/15/734b4aac-85f0-11eb-be4a-24b89f616f2c_story.html |title=Correction: Trump-Georgia story |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |archive-url=https://archive.today/20210316051149/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/correction-trump-georgia-story/2021/03/15/734b4aac-85f0-11eb-be4a-24b89f616f2c_story.html |archive-date=March 16, 2021 |date=March 15, 2021 |access-date=March 16, 2021}}</ref> the investigation ultimately concluded that the allegations had no merit.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trump-call-georgia-investigator/2021/01/09/7a55c7fa-51cf-11eb-83e3-322644d82356_story.html |title='Find the fraud': Trump pressured a Georgia elections investigator in a separate call legal experts say could amount to obstruction 'Find the fraud': Trump pressured a Georgia elections investigator in a separate call legal experts say could amount to obstruction |last=Gardner |first=Amy |date=January 9, 2021 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=January 9, 2021 |archive-date=January 14, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210114194053/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trump-call-georgia-investigator/2021/01/09/7a55c7fa-51cf-11eb-83e3-322644d82356_story.html |url-status=live }}</ref> Texas attorney general [[Ken Paxton]] sued the state and three others, asking the U.S. Supreme Court to invalidate the states' voting results, alleging that they had violated the Constitution, citing a litany of complaints that had already been rejected by other courts.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/12/07/us/politics/georgia-recertify-election-results.html |title=Georgia Recertifies Election Results, Affirming Biden's Victory |first1=Richard |last1=Fausset |first2=Nick |last2=Corasaniti |date=December 7, 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=December 10, 2020 |archive-date=January 7, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107014507/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/12/07/us/politics/georgia-recertify-election-results.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://apnews.com/article/donald-trump-courts-election-results-e1297d874f45d2b14bc99c403abd0457 |first1=Colleen |last1=Long |first2=Ed |last2=White |title=Trump thought courts were key to winning. Judges disagreed. |date=December 8, 2020 |website=[[Associated Press]] |access-date=June 15, 2022 |archive-date=January 10, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210110023312/https://apnews.com/article/donald-trump-courts-election-results-e1297d874f45d2b14bc99c403abd0457 |url-status=live }}</ref> Trump and seventeen Republican state attorneys general filed motions to support the case, the merits of which were sharply criticized by legal experts and politicians.<ref name="auto3">{{Cite web |url=https://www.dallasnews.com/news/politics/2020/12/09/trump-says-hell-join-texas-lawsuit-asking-supreme-court-to-block-62-biden-electors-from-four-states/ |access-date=January 17, 2023 |first=Todd J. |last=Gillman |title=17 states, and Trump, join Texas request for Supreme Court to overturn Biden wins in four states |date=December 9, 2020 |website=Dallas News |archive-date=December 9, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201209212932/https://www.dallasnews.com/news/politics/2020/12/09/trump-says-hell-join-texas-lawsuit-asking-supreme-court-to-block-62-biden-electors-from-four-states/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="auto4">{{Cite web |access-date=January 17, 2023 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/12/08/us/politics/texas-files-an-audacious-suit-with-the-supreme-court-challenging-the-election-results.html |title=Texas files an audacious suit with the Supreme Court challenging the election results. |first=Adam |last=Liptak |date=December 8, 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |archive-date=December 9, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201209023641/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/12/08/us/politics/texas-files-an-audacious-suit-with-the-supreme-court-challenging-the-election-results.html |url-status=live }}</ref> The day the suit was filed, Trump warned Georgia attorney general [[Christopher M. Carr|Chris Carr]] to not rally other Republican officials in opposition to the suit.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ajc.com/politics/trump-warns-georgia-ag-not-to-rally-other-republicans-against-texas-lawsuit/37ASZD4PJNENHOLVIXZHRXCIJI/ |date=December 9, 2020 |title=Trump warns Georgia AG not to rally other Republicans against Texas lawsuit |first1=Greg |last1=Bluestein |newspaper=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201217022556/https://www.ajc.com/politics/trump-warns-georgia-ag-not-to-rally-other-republicans-against-texas-lawsuit/37ASZD4PJNENHOLVIXZHRXCIJI/ |archive-date=December 17, 2020 |url-status=live |access-date=January 17, 2023 }}</ref>

On December 4, 2020, 64 Republican members of the [[Pennsylvania General Assembly]] signed a letter urging the state's congressional delegation to reject Biden's electoral votes. [[Kim Ward]], the Republican majority leader of the Pennsylvania senate, said that Trump had called her to say there had been fraud in the election, but she had not seen the letter before it had been released. She stated that Republican leaders were expected to support Trump's claims and if she had announced opposition to the letter, "I'd get my house bombed tonight".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/12/09/us/politics/trump-pennsylvania-electoral-college.html |access-date=January 17, 2023 |title=Even in Defeat, Trump Tightens Grip on State G.O.P. Lawmakers |first=Trip |last=Gabriel |date=December 9, 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |archive-date=January 12, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210112114737/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/12/09/us/politics/trump-pennsylvania-electoral-college.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Levy |first=Marc |date=4 December 2020 |title=64 Pennsylvania Republican Lawmakers Ask Congress to Throw Out State's Electoral Votes |url=https://www.nbcphiladelphia.com/news/local/64-pa-gop-lawmakers-ask-congress-to-throw-out-states-electoral-votes/2621654/ |access-date=2022-06-07 |website=NBC10 Philadelphia |language=en-US |archive-date=January 7, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220107035428/https://www.nbcphiladelphia.com/news/local/64-pa-gop-lawmakers-ask-congress-to-throw-out-states-electoral-votes/2621654/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

On December 10, 2020, after several lawsuits had been dismissed, Trump tweeted, "This is going to escalate dramatically. This is a very dangerous moment in our history. ... The fact that our country is being stolen. A coup is taking place in front of our eyes, and the public can't take this anymore."<ref>{{Cite web|last=Idliby|first=Leia|date=December 10, 2020|title='This is Going to Escalate Dramatically': Trump Threatens a 'Dangerous Moment' Forthcoming in Twitter Spree Assailing Election|url=https://www.mediaite.com/trump/this-is-going-to-escalate-dramatically-trump-threatens-a-dangerous-moment-forthcoming-in-twitter-spree-assailing-election/|url-status=live|access-date=2021-12-20|website=Mediaite|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201210153632/https://www.mediaite.com/trump/this-is-going-to-escalate-dramatically-trump-threatens-a-dangerous-moment-forthcoming-in-twitter-spree-assailing-election/ |archive-date=December 10, 2020 }}</ref>

=== Supreme Court petitions ===
{{main|Texas v. Pennsylvania}}
Before and after the election, Trump said he expected the outcome would be decided by the [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]], where [[Conservatism in the United States|conservative]] justices held a 6–3 majority, with three of the justices having been appointed by Trump.<ref>Multiple sources:
* {{Cite web|last=Mascaro|first=Lisa|date=September 30, 2020|title=Trump thrusts Supreme Court pick into election turmoil|url=https://apnews.com/article/election-2020-virus-outbreak-joe-biden-donald-trump-voting-e7fa904df7e51320e154efd7c0d7fd2a|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201102053611/https://apnews.com/article/election-2020-virus-outbreak-joe-biden-donald-trump-voting-e7fa904df7e51320e154efd7c0d7fd2a|archive-date=November 2, 2020|access-date=December 4, 2020|website=[[Associated Press]]}}
* {{Cite web|last=Mason|first=Jeff|date=September 24, 2020|title=Trump hedges on transferring power, says election will end up at Supreme Court|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/usa-court-election-idUSKCN26F06C|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200927000615/https://www.reuters.com/article/usa-court-election-idUSKCN26F06C|archive-date=September 27, 2020|access-date=December 4, 2020|work=[[Reuters]]}}
* {{Cite web|last1=McCoy|first1=Kevin|last2=Wolf|first2=Richard|date=December 1, 2020|title=Lawsuit by Trump allies challenging Pennsylvania election results reaches Supreme Court|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2020/12/01/donald-trumps-allies-ask-supreme-court-block-pa-election-result/3785564001/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201208200940/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2020/12/01/donald-trumps-allies-ask-supreme-court-block-pa-election-result/3785564001/|archive-date=December 8, 2020|access-date=December 4, 2020|website=[[USA Today]]}}
* {{Cite web|last1=Gresko|first1=Jessica|last2=Sherman|first2=Mark|date=November 7, 2020|title=Trump faces tough road in getting Supreme Court to intervene|url=https://apnews.com/article/election-2020-donald-trump-elections-voting-fraud-and-irregularities-us-supreme-court-14eb73bc80dfd2aa637d097a3f41fca5|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201126043851/https://apnews.com/article/election-2020-donald-trump-elections-voting-fraud-and-irregularities-us-supreme-court-14eb73bc80dfd2aa637d097a3f41fca5|archive-date=November 26, 2020|access-date=December 4, 2020|website=[[Associated Press]]}}
</ref><ref name="doa" />

On November 21, a group of Republican legislators in Pennsylvania petitioned the [[Supreme Court of the United States|U.S. Supreme Court]] in appeal of a [[Pennsylvania Supreme Court]] decision against the legislators, who had asked to nullify mailed ballots after they had been cast, or to direct the legislature to select Pennsylvania's electors. The high court denied the request in a one-sentence, unsigned order on December 8. By the time of the high court's decision, the Pennsylvania election results had been certified in Biden's favor. Lawyers for Pennsylvania argued to the high court that the legislators' request was "an affront to constitutional democracy" and that "Petitioners ask this court to undertake one of the most dramatic, disruptive invocations of judicial power in the history of the Republic; no court has ever issued an order nullifying a governor's certification of presidential election results".<ref name="auto1" /><ref name="scolforo" />

On December 8, 2020, Texas attorney general [[Ken Paxton]] [[Texas v. Pennsylvania|sued the states of Georgia, Michigan, Wisconsin and Pennsylvania]], where certified results showed Joe Biden had won,<ref name="auto5">{{Cite news |access-date=January 17, 2023 |last=Liptak |first=Adam |date=December 11, 2020 |title=Supreme Court Rejects Texas Suit Seeking to Subvert Election |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/12/11/us/politics/supreme-court-election-texas.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |archive-date=December 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201211234955/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/12/11/us/politics/supreme-court-election-texas.html |url-status=live }}</ref> alleging a variety of unconstitutional actions in their presidential balloting, arguments that had [[Post-election lawsuits related to the 2020 United States presidential election|already been rejected in other courts]]. Paxton asked the U.S. Supreme Court to invalidate those states' 62 electoral votes, allowing Trump to be declared the winner of a second presidential term.<ref name="auto1"/> This case, ''Texas v. Pennsylvania'', was hailed by Trump as "the big one".<ref name=":5" /> Seventeen Republican state attorneys general filed amicus briefs to support the case and 126 Republican members of the House of Representatives signed onto it.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Solender |first=Andrew |title=126 House Republicans Now Support Lawsuit To Overturn Election In Updated Brief |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/andrewsolender/2020/12/11/126-house-republicans-now-support-lawsuit-to-overturn-election-in-updated-brief/ |date=December 11, 2020 |access-date=December 12, 2020 |website=[[Forbes]]|archive-date=December 12, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201212002916/https://www.forbes.com/sites/andrewsolender/2020/12/11/126-house-republicans-now-support-lawsuit-to-overturn-election-in-updated-brief/ |url-status=live }}</ref> On December 11, the Supreme Court said it would not hear the case. In denying the plaintiff's motion to invalidate those votes, it said that "the state of Texas' motion" had "lack of standing".<ref name="auto5"/><ref name="order">{{Cite web |title=Order in Pending Case |url=https://www.supremecourt.gov/orders/courtorders/121120zr_p860.pdf |access-date=January 17, 2023 |date=December 11, 2020 |publisher=[[Supreme Court of the United States]] |archive-date=December 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201211234004/https://www.supremecourt.gov/orders/courtorders/121120zr_p860.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="CNN-20201211">{{Cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=READ: Supreme Court order on Texas election case |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/12/11/politics/supreme-court-order-texas-election-case/index.html |date=December 11, 2020 |work=[[CNN News]] |access-date=December 11, 2020 |archive-date=December 12, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201212005606/https://www.cnn.com/2020/12/11/politics/supreme-court-order-texas-election-case/index.html |url-status=live }}</ref> Ted Cruz, who had previously argued nine cases before the Supreme Court, agreed to Trump's request to argue the Paxton suit should it come before the Court.<ref name="auto10">{{cite news |last1=Kranish |first1=Michael |title=Inside Ted Cruz's last-ditch battle to keep Trump in power |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2022/03/28/ted-cruz-john-eastman-jan6-committee/ |access-date=January 17, 2023 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=March 28, 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Farley |first1=Robert |title=Cruz's Record Before the Supreme Court |url=https://www.factcheck.org/2016/03/cruzs-record-before-the-supreme-court/ |publisher=FactCheck.org |date=March 3, 2016 |access-date=January 17, 2023 }}</ref>

In late December attorneys Chesebro and Troupis asked the Supreme Court to review whether competing slates of electors from seven contested states could be considered by Congress on January 6. The Supreme Court declined their request for an opinion.<ref name="NYT2222"/>

On December 31, lawyer Kenneth Chesebro emailed other members of Trump's legal team, saying that U.S. Supreme Court Justice Clarence Thomas was "key" and proposing that they "frame things so that Thomas could be the one to issue" an order to undermine Georgia's election results. Trump lawyer John Eastman responded in agreement.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Sneed |first1=Tierney |last2=Polantz |first2=Katelyn |last3=Murray |first3=Sara |date=2022-11-02 |title=Clarence Thomas was 'key' to a plan to delay certification of 2020 election, Trump lawyers said in emails {{!}} CNN Politics |url=https://www.cnn.com/2022/11/02/politics/clarence-thomas-trump-eastman-emails/index.html |access-date=2022-11-02 |website=[[CNN]]|language=en}}</ref>

=== Consideration of special counsel and martial law ===
After legal efforts by Trump and his proxies had failed in numerous state and federal courts, including the Supreme Court,<ref name=CitebundleSought/> some right-wing activists and Trump allies{{snd}}including [[Michael Flynn]], [[Sidney Powell]], and [[L. Lin Wood]]{{snd}}suggested that Trump could suspend the Constitution, declare [[Martial law in the United States|martial law]] and "rerun" the election.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://lawandcrime.com/2020-election/lawyers-condemn-michael-flynn-and-lin-woods-breathtakingly-morally-treasonous-call-for-trump-to-declare-martial-law-and-hold-new-election/ |first=Jerry |last=Lambe |title=Lawyers Condemn Michael Flynn and Lin Wood's 'Breathtakingly Morally Treasonous' Call for Trump to Declare Martial Law and Hold New Election |date=December 2, 2020 |publisher=Law and Crime |access-date=December 3, 2020 |archive-date=December 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201208200946/https://lawandcrime.com/2020-election/lawyers-condemn-michael-flynn-and-lin-woods-breathtakingly-morally-treasonous-call-for-trump-to-declare-martial-law-and-hold-new-election/ |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Sidney Powell shares post recommending military tribunals review election |url=https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2020/dec/1/sidney-powell-ex-trump-campaign-lawyer-shares-post/ |date=December 1, 2020 |first=Andrew |last=Blake |access-date=December 30, 2020 |website=The Washington Times}}</ref> Many retired military officers, attorneys, and other commentators expressed horror at such a notion.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/when-the-bombs-go-off-the-blood-is-on-mike-flynns-hands-retired-officers-blast-his-calls-for-martial-law |title='When the Bombs Go Off, the Blood Is on Mike Flynn's Hands': Retired Officers Blast His Calls for Martial Law |first1=Spencer |last1=Ackerman |first2=Kelly |last2=Weill |date=December 2, 2020 |work=[[The Daily Beast]] |access-date=December 3, 2020 |archive-date=December 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201208200947/https://www.thedailybeast.com/when-the-bombs-go-off-the-blood-is-on-mike-flynns-hands-retired-officers-blast-his-calls-for-martial-law |url-status=live}}</ref>{{efn|Trump's [[Assistant Secretary of Defense for International Security Affairs]] nominee [[Scott O'Grady]] and [[Virginia Senate|Virginia State Senator]] [[Amanda Chase]], a candidate in [[2021 Virginia gubernatorial election|Virginia's 2021 gubernatorial election]], promoted debunked conspiracy claims and called for Trump to institute martial law.<ref name="KFile-4Dec2020">{{Cite news |title=Trump Pentagon nominee spreads debunked conspiracies and tweets suggesting Trump declare martial law |first1=Nathan |last1=McDermott |first2=Andrew |last2=Kaczynski |first3=Em |last3=Steck |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/12/04/politics/trump-nominee-pentagon-martial-law/index.html |access-date=December 4, 2020 |work=[[CNN]] |date=December 4, 2020 |archive-date=December 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201208201017/https://www.cnn.com/2020/12/04/politics/trump-nominee-pentagon-martial-law/index.html |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://news.yahoo.com/us-hero-bosnia-war-named-031024079.html |agency=AFP |title=US hero of Bosnia war named to the Pentagon |publisher=[[Yahoo! News]] |date=November 18, 2020 |access-date=December 4, 2020 |archive-date=November 18, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201118140317/https://news.yahoo.com/us-hero-bosnia-war-named-031024079.html |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Ruiz |first=Michael |date=December 17, 2020 |title=Virginia gubernatorial candidate says 'Trump should declare martial law' |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/virginia-amanda-chase-trump-martial-law |access-date=December 30, 2020 |website=[[Fox News]]}}</ref> [[North Carolina State Senate|North Carolina State Senator]] [[Bob Steinburg]] similarly promoted false claims of a "stolen" election and suggested that Trump should declare a national emergency, invoke the [[Insurrection Act of 1807]], and suspend [[Civil liberties in the United States|civil liberties]] and [[habeas corpus]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=WRAL |date=December 15, 2020 |title=NC senator OK with suspending civil liberties in wake of Trump's defeat |url=https://www.wral.com/nc-senator-ok-with-suspending-civil-liberties-in-wake-of-trump-s-defeat/19431251/ |access-date=December 16, 2020 |website=WRAL.com}}</ref>}} Trump held an Oval Office meeting on December 18 with Rudy Giuliani, Chief of Staff Mark Meadows, [[White House Counsel]] [[Pat Cipollone]], Powell, and Flynn. At the meeting, Trump entertained the idea of naming Powell, who has promoted election conspiracy theories and falsehoods, as [[special counsel]] to investigate election matters, though most advisors in attendance strongly opposed the idea. Two executive orders were drafted to appoint a special counsel and confiscate voting machines, which Trump falsely claimed were rigged against him. One order called for the Pentagon to seize machines, while the other tasked the [[Department of Homeland Security]]. At Trump's direction, Giuliani called [[Ken Cuccinelli]], the second in command at DHS, on December 17 to ask if the department could seize the machines, but Cuccinelli said it did not have the authority. On Giuliani's advice, Trump had rejected a recommendation from Flynn and Powell to have the Pentagon seize the machines, and Bill Barr flatly rejected the president's suggestion that the Justice Department do it.<ref>{{cite news |title=Exclusive: Trump advisers drafted more than one executive order to seize voting machines, sources tell CNN |url=https://www.cnn.com/2022/01/31/politics/trump-executive-orders-seize-voting-machines/index.html |work=[[CNN]]|date=January 31, 2022 |first1=Zachary |last1=Cohen |first2=Paula |last2=Reid |access-date=January 17, 2023 }}</ref><ref name="Politico"/><ref>{{cite news |last1=Swan |first1=Jonathan |title=Giuliani asks DHS about seizing voting machines |url=https://www.axios.com/2020/12/19/giuliani-homeland-security-seize-voting-machines |work=[[Axios (website)|Axios]]|date=December 19, 2020 |access-date=January 6, 2023 }}</ref><ref name="trump had role">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2022/01/31/us/politics/donald-trump-election-results-fraud-voting-machines.html|title=Trump Had Role in Weighing Proposals to Seize Voting Machines |first1=Alan |last1=Feuer |first2=Maggie |last2=Haberman |first3=Michael S. |last3=Schmidt |first4=Luke |last4=Broadwater |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=February 1, 2022 |access-date=January 17, 2023 }}</ref> Flynn reportedly discussed his idea to declare martial law, although others also resisted that idea, and Trump's opinion on the matter was unclear. That same day, Flynn appeared on [[Newsmax TV]] to suggest that Trump had the power to deploy the military to "rerun" the election in the swing states that Trump had lost.<ref name=CitebundleSought>
* {{Cite web |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/12/19/sidney-powell-trump-special-counsel-448694 |first1=Kyle |last1=Cheney |first2=Josh |last2=Gerstein |date=December 19, 2020 |title=Trump sought to tap Sidney Powell as special counsel for election fraud |website=[[Politico]] |ref=none |access-date=January 17, 2023}}
* {{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/12/19/us/politics/trump-sidney-powell-voter-fraud.html |title=Trump Weighed Naming Election Conspiracy Theorist as Special Counsel |first1=Maggie |last1=Haberman |first2=Zolan |last2=Kanno-Youngs |date=December 19, 2020 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |ref=none}}
* {{Cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/12/19/politics/trump-oval-office-meeting-special-counsel-martial-law/index.html |title=Heated Oval Office meeting included talk of special counsel, martial law as Trump advisers clash |first1=Kevin |last1=Liptak |first2=Pamela |last2=Brown |date=December 21, 2020 |website=[[CNN]] |ref=none}}
* {{Cite web |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/fired-attorney-sidney-powell-back-advising-trump-chart/story?id=74823842 |date=December 20, 2020 |first1=Olivia |last1=Rubin |first2=Matthew |last2=Mosk |first3=John |last3=Santucci |first4=Katherine |last4=Faulders |title=Fired attorney Sidney Powell is back, advising Trump to chart a scorched-earth course |website=[[ABC News (United States)|ABC News]] |ref=none}}
* {{Cite web |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/news/530795-michael-flynn-trump-should-deploy-military-to-rerun-election |title=Michael Flynn: Trump could deploy military to 'rerun' election |first=Jordan |last=Williams |date=December 18, 2020 |website=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] }}</ref> Trump dismissed reports about a discussion of martial law as "fake news", but it remained unclear whether he had endorsed the notion.<ref name=Goodwin>{{Cite web |first=Jazmin |last=Goodwin |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/12/20/media/stelter-trump-martial-law/index.html |title=Trump's talk of martial law sends White House staffers rushing to the press |website=[[CNN]] |date=December 20, 2020 |access-date=January 3, 2021 |ref=none}}</ref>

An attempt by Trump to invoke martial law to invalidate the results of the election would be illegal and unconstitutional.<ref name="FinkelsteinPainter">{{Cite news |last1=Finkelstein |first1=Claire O. |last2=Painter |first2=Richard |date=December 22, 2020 |title=Invoking Martial Law to Reverse the 2020 Election Could be Criminal Sedition |url=https://www.justsecurity.org/73986/invoking-martial-law-to-reverse-the-2020-election-could-be-criminal-sedition/ |access-date=January 5, 2021 |work=[[Just Security]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |access-date=January 5, 2021 |first=Noah Y. |last=Kim |url=https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2020/dec/18/facebook-posts/president-united-states-cant-unilaterally-impose-m/ |title=No, a 2018 executive order doesn't allow Trump to unilaterally impose martial law |work=[[PolitiFact]] |date=December 18, 2020 |quote=PolitiFact spoke to six scholars of constitutional law and presidential power and asked them whether the executive order allows Trump to declare martial law. They were unanimous: It doesn't. ... Under the Constitution, the president does not have the power to unilaterally impose martial law.}}</ref> In late December 2020, legal scholars [[Claire Finkelstein|Claire O. Finkelstein]] and [[Richard Painter]] wrote that while it was very unlikely that Trump would actually "attempt to spark a military coup", Acting Attorney General [[Jeffrey A. Rosen]] should be prepared to direct federal law enforcement "to arrest anyone, including if necessary the president, who ... conspired to carry out this illegal plan". Likening a hypothetical invocation of martial law to overturn the election to the [[Battle of Fort Sumter|1861 firing on Fort Sumter]], Finkelstein and Painter wrote that any such plan would constitute [[seditious conspiracy]] and possibly other crimes, and that any military officers or enlisted personnel ordered to assist in such a plan would be required, under the [[Uniform Code of Military Justice]], to disregard such an [[illegal order]].<ref name=FinkelsteinPainter/>

On December 18, Army Secretary [[Ryan D. McCarthy|Ryan McCarthy]] and General [[James McConville]], the [[Chief of Staff of the United States Army|Army chief of staff]], issued a joint statement saying, "There is no role for the US military in determining the outcome of an American election".<ref name="Frum_12/20/2020">{{Cite web |last=Frum |first=David |title=How Long Can This Continue? |website=[[The Atlantic]] |date=December 20, 2020 |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2020/12/trumps-attempted-coup-dangerous/617447/ |access-date=December 20, 2020}}</ref> On January 3, all ten living former secretaries of defense{{snd}}[[Ashton Carter]], [[Dick Cheney]], [[William Cohen]], [[Mark Esper]], [[Robert Gates]], [[Chuck Hagel]], [[James Mattis]], [[Leon Panetta]], [[William J. Perry|William Perry]] and [[Donald Rumsfeld]]{{snd}}published an op-ed in ''The Washington Post'' calling for the [[peaceful transfer of power|orderly and peaceful transfer of power]], noting that "efforts to involve the US armed forces in resolving election disputes would take us into dangerous, unlawful and unconstitutional territory", and noting that "civilian and military officials who direct or carry out such measures would be accountable, including potentially facing criminal penalties, for the grave consequences of their actions on our republic". The former defense secretaries wrote that "acting defense secretary [[Christopher C. Miller]] and his subordinates{{snd}}political appointees, officers and civil servants{{snd}}are each bound by oath, law and precedent to facilitate the entry into office of the incoming administration, and to do so wholeheartedly. They must also refrain from any political actions that undermine the results of the election or hinder the success of the new team."<ref name=All10SECDEF>{{Cite news |first1=Ashton |last1=Carter |first2=Dick |last2=Cheney |first3=William |last3=Cohen |first4=Mark |last4=Esper |first5=Robert |last5=Gates |first6=Chuck |last6=Hagel |first7=James |last7=Mattis |first8=Leon |last8=Panetta |first9=William |last9=Perry |first10=Donald |last10=Rumsfeld |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/10-former-defense-secretaries-military-peaceful-transfer-of-power/2021/01/03/2a23d52e-4c4d-11eb-a9f4-0e668b9772ba_story.html |access-date=January 5, 2021 |title=All 10 living former defense secretaries: Involving the military in election disputes would cross into dangerous territory |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=January 3, 2021 |author-link=Ashton Carter |author-link2=Dick Cheney |author-link3=William Cohen |author-link4=Mark Esper |author-link5=Robert Gates |author-link6=Chuck Hagel |author-link7=James Mattis |author-link8=Leon Panetta |author-link9=William J. Perry |author-link10=Donald Rumsfeld}}</ref>

[[Elizabeth Neumann]], an adviser at [[Defending Democracy Together]] and a former assistant secretary of Homeland Security under Trump, stated that "In the conspiratorial conservative base supporting Trump, there are calls for using the Insurrection Act to declare martial law. When they hear that the president is actually considering this, there are violent extremist groups that look at this as a [[Dog whistle (politics)|dog whistle]], an excuse to go out and create ... violence."<ref name=Goodwin/>

===Planning for Congress to overturn the election on January 6===

On December 21, Congressman [[Mo Brooks]], who had been the first member of Congress to announce he would object to the January 6, 2021 [[2021 United States Electoral College vote count|certification]] of the Electoral College results,<ref name=":6">{{Cite news |date=January 6, 2021 |title=Mo Brooks: Today patriots start 'kicking ass' in fighting vote results |first=Paul |last=Gattis |url=https://www.al.com/news/2021/01/mo-brooks-today-patriots-start-kicking-ass-in-fighting-vote-results.html |access-date=January 7, 2021 |website=[[AL.com]] |language=en}}</ref><ref name=":8">{{Cite news|title=Here Are The Republicans Challenging Congress' Tally Of Election Results |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/congress-electoral-college-tally-live-updates/2021/01/06/953714213/here-are-the-republicans-challenging-congress-tally-of-election-results |access-date=January 7, 2021|newspaper=[[NPR]] |date=January 6, 2021|language=en|last1=Grisales|first1=Claudia}}</ref> organized three White House meetings between Trump, Republican lawmakers, and others. Attendees included Trump, Vice President Pence, representatives [[Jody Hice]] (R-Ga.), [[Jim Jordan]] (R-Ohio), and [[Andy Biggs]] (R-Ariz.), representative-elect Marjorie Taylor Greene (R-Ga.), and members of the Trump legal team. The purpose of the meetings was to strategize about how Congress could overturn the election results on January 6. Brooks confirmed after one such meeting that it had been "a back-and-forth concerning the planning and strategy for January the 6th.".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/12/21/trump-house-overturn-election-449787|title=House Republicans meet with Trump to discuss overturning election results|last=Zanona|first=Melanie|date=December 21, 2021|work=[[Politico]] |access-date=July 29, 2021}}</ref>

''[[Talking Points Memo]]'' reported in December 2022 that it had obtained the 2,319 text messages Meadows had provided to the [[January 6 committee]], including 450 showing Meadows communicating with 34 Republican members of Congress about plans to overturn the election.<ref>{{cite news |title=A Plot To Overturn An American Election |url=https://talkingpointsmemo.com/feature/a-plot-to-overturn-an-american-election |access-date=January 17, 2023 |work=[[Talking Points Memo]] |date=December 12, 2022 |first1=Hunter |last1=Walker }}</ref>

=== Pressure on Pence ===
{{See also|2021 United States Electoral College vote count#Pressure on Vice President Pence to obstruct the certification of electoral votes}}
In the run-up to election certification on January 6, attempts to uncover significant election fraud bore no fruit and related legal challenges were rejected by the courts. Hence, those seeking to overturn the election focused attention increasingly on then-vice-president Mike Pence. The [[Twelfth Amendment to the United States Constitution]] requires the President of the Senate, which was Pence for the January 6 certification of the presidential election, to supervise the counting of electoral ballots at a joint session of the Congress.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Congressional Research Service |title=Counting Electoral Votes: An Overview of Procedures at the Joint Session, Including Objections by Members of Congress |date=December 8, 2020 |url=https://sgp.fas.org/crs/misc/RL32717.pdf |access-date=February 12, 2020}}</ref> The Trump team developed multiple theories about how the Vice President might act on January 6 to aid the overturning of election results; and repeatedly encouraged him to act accordingly.{{citation needed|date=July 2023}}

==== "Pence card" theory ====
{{anchor|Pence Card}}
{{main|Eastman memos|Trump fake electors plot}}
Beginning in late December, false legal theories went viral on pro-Trump social media suggesting that Vice President Pence could invoke a "Pence Card", a supposed legal loophole that would enable him, in his capacity as [[President of the Senate#United States|president of the Senate]], to reject electoral votes for Biden from contested swing states on the grounds that they had been cast by fraudulently appointed electors.<ref name="NYT-20211002">{{cite news |author=The Editorial Board |title=Jan 6 Was Worse Than We Knew |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/10/02/opinion/jan-6-trump-eastman-election.html |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20211228/https://www.nytimes.com/2021/10/02/opinion/jan-6-trump-eastman-election.html |archive-date=2021-12-28 |url-access=limited |date=October 2, 2021 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=October 3, 2021}}{{cbignore}}</ref><ref name="SLN-20211008">{{cite news |last=Parton |first=Heather Digby |author-link=Digby (blogger) |title=Trump's coup plot was worse than anyone knew - Republicans are trying their best to make attempted coups now normal politics in America |url=https://www.salon.com/2021/10/08/coup-plot-was-worse-than-anyone-knew/ |date=October 8, 2021 |work=[[Salon.com|Salon]] |access-date=October 8, 2021 }}</ref> These theories originated from [[Ivan Raiklin]], an attorney and former [[United States Army Special Forces|Green Beret]] who was among a small group of military-intelligence veterans associated with Michael Flynn who were instrumental in spreading false information alleging the 2020 election had been stolen from Trump.<ref name="reuters.com"/><ref name="WP-20211023" /><ref>{{cite tweet |user=visionsurreal |number=1441893743507001346|title=Before it became the "Eastman memo," the plan to overthrow our democracy was known as Ivan Raiklin's "Pence Card." |date=26 September 2021 |access-date=January 14, 2022}}</ref> 

The theory stems from a misreading of sections 2 and 12 of [[Title 3 of the United States Code|title 3, United States Code]]; the first of these sections (now since-repealed) concerned a state's failure to make an electoral choice on the prescribed day and the latter directs the vice president to request electoral vote certificates from any state that has not yet sent these votes to the [[National Archives]] by the fourth Wednesday in December. Under the theory, Pence had unilateral authority to declare that state certificates from contested states had not in fact been received, and that new certificates (presumably supporting President Trump) should be issued, or that those states had a "failed election" for which new certificates (again, presumably supporting President Trump) should likewise be issued.<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Gabriel |first1=Trip |last2=Saul |first2=Stephanie |date=2025-03-24 |title=Could State Legislatures Pick Electors to Vote for Trump? Not Likely |url=https://www.nytimes.com/article/electors-vote.html |access-date=2025-03-24 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/can-veep-play-the-pence-card/ |first=Dan |last=Evon |date=December 23, 2020 |title=Can Veep Play the 'Pence Card' and Reject US Election Results? |access-date=January 17, 2023 |website=[[Snopes]] }}</ref> 

Trump retweeted a post of Raiklin's calling for the invocation of the Pence Card on December 23,<ref name="WP-20211023" /> the day specified in statute, but Pence took no action consistent with the theory. In late December, Pence called former vice president [[Dan Quayle]] for advice, and Quayle told him (according to reporters Bob Woodward and Robert Costa): "Mike, you have no flexibility on this. None. Zero. ... I do know the position you're in. I also know what the law is. ... You have no power."<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Gangel |first1=Jamie |last2=Herb |first2=Jeremy |last3=Stuart |first3=Elizabeth |date=14 September 2021 |title=Woodward/Costa book: Worried Trump could 'go rogue,' Milley took secret action to protect nuclear weapons |url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/09/14/politics/woodward-book-trump-nuclear/index.html |access-date=2022-06-20 |website=[[CNN]]}}</ref> Although the fourth Wednesday had passed, Trump still believed that Pence had the authority to reject electoral votes, and kept asking him to do so; however, over lunch on January 5, Pence informed Trump that he did not believe he had any such authority.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/01/05/politics/mike-pence-donald-trump-congress-election/index.html|title=Pence informed Trump that he can't block Biden's win |first1=Kaitlan |last1=Collins |first2=Jim |last2=Acosta |website=[[CNN]]|date=January 5, 2021 |access-date=June 13, 2022 }}</ref><ref name="nytsep142021" />

Attorney [[John C. Eastman|John Eastman]] incorrectly told Pence in a January 5 [[Oval Office]] meeting that Pence had the constitutional authority to block the certification, which Trump reportedly urged Pence to consider.<ref>{{Cite news|last1=Baker|first1=Peter|last2=Haberman|first2=Maggie|last3=Karni|first3=Annie|date=January 13, 2021|title=Pence Reached His Limit With Trump. It Wasn't Pretty.|language=en-US|work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/01/12/us/politics/mike-pence-trump.html|access-date=January 14, 2021|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name="cnn092021">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/09/20/politics/trump-pence-election-memo/index.html|title=Memo shows Trump lawyer's six-step plan for Pence to overturn the election |first1=Jamie |last1=Gangel |first2=Jeremy |last2=Herb |website=[[CNN]] |date=September 20, 2021|access-date=September 20, 2021}}</ref> Eastman also sent to Republican senator [[Mike Lee]] a six-point plan of action for Pence to set aside electors in seven states, which Lee rejected.<ref name="cnn092021" /> By January 5, Trump was continuing to assert that Pence had unilateral power to throw out states' official electoral certificates on grounds of fraud.<ref name="karni" /> During [[2021 United States Capitol attack|the Capitol attack]], numerous rioters chanted "Hang Mike Pence", and the phrase trended on [[Twitter]] until the website banned it.<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Pengelly |first1=Martin |title='Hang Mike Pence': Twitter stops phrase trending after Capitol riot |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2021/jan/10/hang-mike-pence-twitter-stops-phrase-trending-capitol-breach |access-date=January 12, 2021 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=January 10, 2021}}</ref> In March, when ABC News' [[Jonathan Karl]] asked Trump if he was worried about Pence while the crowd was chanting, Trump defended the crowd, saying they were "very angry" and that it was "common sense" that they would want to stop Congress from certifying the election result. Of Pence, Trump said, "I thought he was well protected and I had heard that he was in good shape".<ref>{{Cite web|last1=Stracqualursi|first1=Veronica|last2=Orr|first2=Gabby|date=November 12, 2021|title=Trump defends threats to Pence on January 6 in new audio|url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/11/12/politics/trump-pence-threats-january-6/index.html|url-status=live|access-date=November 12, 2021|website=[[CNN]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211112125410/https://www.cnn.com/2021/11/12/politics/trump-pence-threats-january-6/index.html |archive-date=November 12, 2021 }}</ref>{{Efn|The audio was released later in 2021.}}

Dozens of lawmakers from five key states wrote Pence on January 5 asking him to delay for ten days the final certification of electors scheduled for the following day, to allow them an opportunity to open special legislative sessions to decertify their electors and submit a new slate of electors. This came three days after Trump, Giuliani, and Eastman held a conference call with 300 legislators to present them purported evidence of election fraud.<ref name="WP-20211023"/> Ted Cruz, a decades-long friend of Eastman, proposed a complementary plan in the Senate, garnering the support of ten other senators.<ref name="auto10"/>

In January 2022, as Congress began debating whether to amend the 1887 Electoral Count Act to make it clearer that the vice-president has no power to overturn an election,<ref>{{Cite news |first=Laura |last=Litvan|date=2022-01-21|title=McConnell Backs Effort to Overhaul Electoral Vote Count Law |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2022-01-20/mcconnell-backs-effort-to-overhaul-electoral-vote-count-law |access-date=2022-01-31|website=[[Bloomberg News|Bloomberg]]|language=en-US}}</ref> Trump released a statement asserting, falsely, that Pence did have such power: "Unfortunately, he didn't exercise that power, he could have overturned the Election!" and "they now want to take that right away".<ref>{{Cite web |last=Trump |first=Donald |author-link=Donald Trump |date=2022-01-30 |title=Statement by Donald J. Trump, 45th President of the United States of America |url=https://www.donaldjtrump.com/news/news-hktthafwz61481 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20250310084638/https://web.archive.org/web/20220204214536/https://www.donaldjtrump.com/news/news-hktthafwz61481 |archive-date=March 10, 2025 |access-date=2025-03-10 |website=donaldjtrump.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-02-01 |title=Vice president doesn't have power to 'change the outcome' of elections |url=https://apnews.com/article/fact-checking-275776015398 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20250310084737/https://web.archive.org/web/20220202042946/https://apnews.com/article/fact-checking-275776015398 |archive-date=March 10, 2025 |access-date=2025-03-10 |website=[[Associated Press]] |language=en}}</ref> Pence responded several days later while addressing the [[Federalist Society]]: "President Trump is wrong. ... Under the Constitution, I had no right to change the outcome of our election."<ref name=":12">{{Cite web|last=Date|first=S.V.|date=2022-02-04|title=Mike Pence Rebuts Trump's Claim That VP Can Overturn Election: 'President Trump Is Wrong' |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/mike-pence-donald-trump-overturn-election_n_61fc7a08e4b0b69cfe8c743a |access-date=2022-02-05 |website=[[HuffPost]]|language=en}}</ref>

==== December timeline ====

John Eastman, author of the [[Eastman memos]], began working with the Trump team in November 2020.<ref name="LawyerBehind">{{cite news |last1=Schmidt |first1=M.S. |last2=Haberman |first2=M. |title=The Lawyer Behind the Memo on How Trump Could Stay in Office |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/10/02/us/politics/john-eastman-trump-memo.html |access-date=14 February 2022 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=October 2, 2021}}</ref> Trump adviser [[Peter Navarro]] claimed that the "[[Green Bay Sweep (politics)|Green Bay Sweep]]" plan was developed over weeks prior to January 6, 2021.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pagliery |first1=Jose |title=Trump Adviser Peter Navarro Lays Out How He and Bannon Planned to Overturn Biden's Electoral Win |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/trump-advisor-peter-navarro-lays-out-how-he-and-steve-bannon-planned-to-overturn-bidens-electoral-win |access-date=14 February 2022 |work=[[Daily Beast]] |date=December 28, 2021}}</ref>

On December 13, Trump allies in the House were developing a plan involving Pence "to use Congress's tallying of electoral results on Jan. 6 to tip the election to President Trump".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fandos |first1=N. |last2=Schmidt |first2=M.S. |title=Trump Allies Eye Long-Shot Election Reversal in Congress, Testing Pence |work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/12/13/us/politics/trump-allies-election-overturn-congress-pence.html |access-date=14 February 2022 |date=January 15, 2021}}</ref> Kenneth Chesebro emailed Rudy Giuliani and others pointing out that, if Pence were to recuse himself, Republican senator [[Chuck Grassley]] of Iowa would be in charge of certifying the election, and if Grassley were to delay doing so, this would give Trump more time for court battles. Chesebro's subject line called this the "'President of the Senate' strategy".<ref>{{Cite web |last=Polantz |first=Katelyn |date=2 June 2022 |title=House January 6 committee obtains email outlining early plan to try to overturn Trump's 2020 loss |url=https://www.cnn.com/2022/06/01/politics/january-6-email-plan-overturn-election-trump/index.html |access-date=2 June 2022 |website=[[CNN]]}}</ref>

On December 21, Trump's legal advisors, Pence, and multiple members of Congress at a White House meeting discussed ways to challenge the January 6 certification process and results.<ref>{{cite news |last1=McFall |first1=Caitlin |title=Trump, House Republicans held call to discuss Electoral College rejection: Brooks |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/gop-splits-electoral-college-certification |access-date=14 February 2022 |work=[[Fox News]] |date=January 2, 2021}}</ref>

On December 23, Trump re-tweeted the Ivan Raiklin "Operation Pence Card" memo while stating "America @VP @Mike_Pence MUST do this, tomorrow To defend our Constitution from our enemies ... Let him know!"<ref>{{cite tweet |first=John |last=Kruzel |title=Trump just RT'd a bizarre "memo" calling on VP Pence to reject certain Biden slates of electors on Dec. 6. Setting aside the kooky details here...big takeaway is that Trump is now publicly pressuring Pence to conspire in his bid to overturn the election |user=johnkruzel |number=1341908675984838657 |date=December 24, 2020 |access-date=14 February 2022}}</ref>

On December 24, a Trump aide contacted John Eastman to request documentation of his legal theories concerning the certification process including the role of the vice president, resulting in the [[Eastman memos]].<ref name="LawyerBehind"/>

On December 27, a lawsuit seeking to force action by Pence during the January 6 certification, ''[[Gohmert v. Pence]]'' (see below), was filed in a Texas court.

On December 31, then-White House Chief of Staff [[Mark Meadows]] e-mailed a memo prepared by [[Jenna Ellis]], a legal advisor to the Trump campaign, to one of Pence's top aides.<ref name="MemoFromTrumpAtty">{{cite news |last1=Cathey |first1=L. |title=Memo from Trump attorney outlined how Pence could overturn election, says new book. |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/memo-trump-attorney-outlined-pence-overturn-election-book/story?id=81134003 |access-date=14 February 2022 |work=[[ABC News (United States)|ABC News]] |date=November 14, 2021}}</ref> The memo claimed that the Vice President should not open electoral ballots from six states "that have electoral delegates in dispute", and should defer the eventual count of electoral delegates until January 15.<ref name="memorandum re"/>

=== Pressure on Justice Department ===
On December 14, two weeks after Barr stated there was no evidence of significant election fraud, Trump announced that Barr would be leaving as attorney general by Christmas.<ref name="disputing trump" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://apnews.com/article/william-barr-resigns-donald-trump-463cb19223f025345195d9d4f1666f3a |first=Michael |last=Balsamo |access-date=June 15, 2022 |title=Trump says Barr resigning, will leave before Christmas |date=December 14, 2020 |website=[[Associated Press]] }}</ref> Before Trump's announcement, he enlisted Chief of Staff Mark Meadows and other aides to pressure deputy attorney general [[Jeffrey A. Rosen|Jeffrey Rosen]], who would replace Barr on December 23, and other Justice Department officials to challenge the election results. Meadows and a top Trump aide emailed allegations of voting anomalies in three states to Rosen and other officials. Meadows also sought to have Rosen investigate [[Italygate|a&nbsp;conspiracy theory]], promoted by a Giuliani ally, that satellites and military technology had been used in Italy to remotely change votes from Trump to Biden. Trump also enlisted a private attorney, Kurt Olsen, to seek a meeting with Rosen to propose a legal challenge he had drafted; it was similar [[Texas v. Pennsylvania|to a challenge initiated by Texas attorney general]] [[Ken Paxton]] and supported by dozens of Republican members of Congress and state attorneys general, that attempted unsuccessfully to have the Supreme Court reject election results in four states. Trump also spoke to Rosen about Olsen's proposal. Rosen and his deputy [[Richard Donoghue]] resisted the efforts, exchanging emails mocking them, in one case, as "pure insanity".<ref name="auto6"/><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/06/15/us/politics/trump-justice-department-election.html |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20211228/https://www.nytimes.com/2021/06/15/us/politics/trump-justice-department-election.html |archive-date=2021-12-28 |url-access=limited|url-status=live |access-date=January 17, 2023 |title=Trump Pressed Official to Wield Justice Dept. to Back Election Claims |first=Katie |last=Benner |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=June 15, 2021}}{{cbignore}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2021/08/10/trump-asked-ag-overturn-election-503341 |date=August 10, 2021 |first1=Betsy Woodruff |last1=Swan |first2=Nicholas |last2=Wu |title=Trump asked his AG about legal strategy to overturn election, Rosen tells senators |access-date=January 6, 2023 |website=[[Politico]] }}</ref> Rosen later testified to Congress, "During my tenure, no special prosecutors were appointed, whether for election fraud or otherwise; no public statements were made questioning the election; no letters were sent to State officials seeking to overturn the election results; [and] no DOJ court actions or filings were submitted seeking to overturn election results".<ref name = Dawsey/>

In late December, Trump reportedly phoned Rosen "nearly every day" to tell him about claims of voter fraud or improper vote counts.<ref name = Dawsey>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/trump-rosen-election-calls/2021/07/28/43106ab6-efd6-11eb-bf80-e3877d9c5f06_story.html|title=As Trump pushed for probes of 2020 election, he called acting AG Rosen almost daily|last1=Dawsey|first1=Josh|last2=Barrett|first2=Devlin|date=July 28, 2021|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=July 30, 2021}}</ref> Donoghue took notes of a December 27, 2020, phone call between him, Rosen and Trump in which he characterized the president saying, "Just say that the election was corrupt + leave the rest to me and the R. Congressmen".<ref name="auto8"/><ref name="TG-20210803"/> The next day [[Jeffrey Clark]], acting assistant attorney general for the civil division, approached Rosen and Donoghue with a draft letter and requested them to sign it. The letter was addressed to officials in the state of Georgia, saying that the Justice Department had evidence that raised "significant concerns" about the outcome of the presidential election, contrary to what Barr had publicly announced weeks earlier, and suggesting that the Georgia legislature "call itself into special session for [t]he limited purpose of considering issues pertaining to the appointment of Presidential Electors". Both Rosen and Donoghue refused to sign the letter, and it was never sent.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2021/08/08/trump-doj-official-urged-acting-ag-pressure-georgia-election/5531371001/|title=Trump DOJ official Jeffrey Clark pushed acting AG to interfere in Georgia election: report|last=Brown|first=Matthew|date=August 8, 2021|work=[[USA Today]]|access-date=August 10, 2021}}</ref>

The Associated Press reported in December that Heidi Stirrup, an ally of Trump advisor [[Stephen Miller (political advisor)|Stephen Miller]], who months earlier had been quietly installed at the Justice Department as the White House's "eyes and ears", had in recent days been banned from the building after it was learned she pressured officials for sensitive information about potential election fraud and other matters she could relay to the White House. Stirrup had also circumvented Justice Department management to extend job offers to political allies for senior Department positions and interfered with the hiring of career officials.<ref>{{Cite news |first=Michael |last=Balsamo |access-date=January 17, 2023 |url=https://apnews.com/article/heidi-stirrup-banned-justice-department-7624560e990ec55383a2a3e421c3a52e |title=Trump aide banned from Justice after trying to get case info |date=December 3, 2020 |website=[[Associated Press]] }}</ref>

=== Pressure on Defense Department ===
According to ABC News reporter [[Jonathan Karl]], Michael Flynn called senior Trump intelligence official [[Ezra Cohen-Watnick|Ezra Cohen]] and told him to take extreme actions, including seizing ballots, to prevent the election results from favoring the Democrat. Cohen did not entertain Flynn's orders, responding, "Sir, the election is over. It's time to move on." Flynn replied, "You're a quitter! This is not over! Don't be a quitter!"<ref name=":0">{{Cite news |title=Trump allies pressed Defense Department to help overturn election, new book says |first=Will |last=Steakin |date=November 16, 2021 |url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/trump-allies-pressed-defense-department-overturn-election-book/story?id=81182008 |access-date=November 16, 2021 |website=[[ABC News (United States)|ABC News]] |language=en}}</ref><ref name=":4">{{Cite magazine|last=Bort|first=Ryan|date=November 16, 2021|title=Michael Flynn Pushed Defense Department to Seize Ballots, Overturn Trump's Loss: Report|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/politics-news/michael-flynn-sydney-powell-department-of-defense-election-1258421/|access-date=November 16, 2021|magazine=Rolling Stone|language=en-US}}</ref>

Trump attorney Sidney Powell called Cohen shortly thereafter and attempted to enlist his help with a far-fetched claim involving then-CIA Director [[Gina Haspel]]. According to Karl's book, Powell told Cohen that "Haspel has been hurt and taken into custody in Germany. You need to launch a special operations mission to get her." The claim, a conspiracy theory, had been circulating among Powell's QAnon following for some time.<ref name=":4" /> The conspiracy theory falsely claimed that Haspel had been injured while on a secret CIA operation to seize an election-related computer server that belonged to a company named Scytl. Powell alleged to Cohen that the server contained evidence of "hundreds of thousands, maybe millions, of votes had been switched using rigged voting machines". Powell was under the impression that Haspel had been engaged in this operation with the aim of destroying the nonexistent evidence on that nonexistent server. According to the book, Cohen thought Powell sounded "out of her mind" and he quickly reported the call to the acting defense secretary.<ref name=":0" />

A December 18, 2020, memo proposed that the Trump administration seek evidence that there had been foreign interference in favor of Biden. The memo laid out a plan for Acting Secretary of Defense [[Christopher C. Miller|Christopher Miller]] to use [[National Security Agency]] and [[United States Department of Defense|Defense Department]] powers to seize phone and email records. One of Trump's informal advisers, Michael Pillsbury, described this as "amateur hour" perpetrated by people with no existing connection to Trump who were raising topics that the government had already "said there was no evidence for".<ref name="memo circulated">{{Cite news|last1=Dawsey|first1=Josh|last2=Helderman|first2=Rosalind S.|last3=Brown|first3=Emma|last4=Swaine|first4=Jon|last5=Alemany|first5=Jacqueline|date=3 February 2022|title=Memo circulated among Trump allies advocated using NSA data in attempt to prove stolen election|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2022/02/03/trump-nsa-election/|access-date=3 February 2022}}</ref> In May 2021, Miller testified to the January 6 House committee that he had feared Trump might "invoke the Insurrection Act to politicize the military in an antidemocratic manner".<ref>{{Cite web |last=Date |first=S.V. |date=2022-12-23 |title=Trump's Eagerness To Use Military On June 2020 Protests Made Pentagon Coup-Wary |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/trump-coup-jan-6-committee_n_63a61a8ae4b0ae9de1b0a829 |access-date=2022-12-24 |website=[[HuffPost]]|language=en}}</ref>

=== Plan to seize voting machines ===
The then-President's team also developed plans to have federal authorities seize voting machines from states where the election had been closely contested but won by Biden. News reports indicate that, at various points in the planning, the Justice Department, the Department of Defense, Department of Homeland Security, and the National Guard were considered as entities that would conduct the seizures. Several versions of a draft Executive Order that would authorize the seizures were prepared. Then-President Trump was reported to have reviewed the draft Executive Order authorizing seizure by the National Guard but, based on advice by (among others) Patrick Cipollone and Rudy Giuliani, he did not sign and issue it.<ref name="trump had role"/><ref>{{Cite news|last=Lowell|first=Hugo|date=February 4, 2022|title=Revealed: Trump reviewed draft order that authorized voting machines to be seized|work=[[The Guardian]]|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2022/feb/04/trump-draft-order-voting-machines-white-house-meeting|access-date=February 8, 2022}}</ref>

In June 2022, an email dated November 21, 2020 surfaced, sent by British biopharmaceuticals executive Andrew Whitney, who in August 2020 pitched to Trump in the Oval Office the toxic botanical extract [[oleandrin]] as a cure for COVID-19. The email included a draft "authorizing letter" to be presented by the president allowing three armed private companies to seize all voting machines and related materials, with assistance from U.S. Marshals. The email was sent to Doug Logan, the president of [[Cyber Ninjas]], which later conducted the [[2021 Maricopa County presidential ballot audit]] that sought but failed to find election fraud in that county, and to cybersecurity expert Jim Penrose, who had worked with Sidney Powell, Michael Flynn and [[Patrick M. Byrne]], who were seeking access to voting machines in an attempt to find proof of election fraud.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wire |first1=Sarah D. |title=Trump allies explored sending armed private contractors to seize voting machines in 2020 election |access-date=January 17, 2023 |url=https://www.latimes.com/politics/story/2022-06-04/trump-allies-proposed-order-to-seize-voting-machines-gave-authority-to-armed-private-contractors |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=June 4, 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trump-struggled-summer-coronavirus/2020/08/08/e12ceace-d80a-11ea-aff6-220dd3a14741_story.html |access-date=January 17, 2023 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=August 8, 2020 |title=The lost days of summer: How Trump fell short in containing the virus |first1=Philip |last1=Rucker |first2=Yasmeen |last2=Abutaleb |first3=Josh |last3=Dawsey |first4=Robert |last4=Costa |quote=The president recently hosted Andrew Whitney, a biopharmaceuticals executive on the board of a company called Phoenix, who met in the Oval Office with Trump. Whitney, who has a limited health background, pitched Trump on a botanical extract called oleandrin as a treatment for the coronavirus, according to two senior administration officials with knowledge of the discussion. One official said Mike Lindell, a Trump booster and the chief executive of MyPillow – who stars as pitchman for his product in advertising on some of the Fox News shows Trump watches – helped arrange the meeting. Since then, Whitney has personally made overtures to senior leaders at the Food and Drug Administration, including its commissioner, Stephen Hahn, in an effort to get the agency to approve oleandrin as a treatment for the coronavirus.}}</ref>

===Ellis memos===
On New Year's Eve, Chief of Staff Mark Meadows sent a memo drafted by Trump attorney Jenna Ellis to a top Pence aide containing a detailed plan to overturn the election results. The plan entailed Pence returning the electoral results to six battleground states on January 6, with a deadline of January 15 for the states to return them. If any state did not return their electoral slate by that date, neither Trump nor Biden would hold a majority, so the election would be thrown to the House for a vote to determine the winner. Per the Constitution, in such a scenario the vote would be conducted on the basis of party control of state legislatures, with Republicans holding 26 of 50, presumably giving Trump the victory.<ref name="MemoFromTrumpAtty"/>

Ellis drafted a second memo dated January 5 which she shared with Trump personal attorney, [[Jay Sekulow]]. The memo argued that certain provisions of the Electoral Count Act that restricted Pence's authority to accept or reject selected electors were unconstitutional. She proposed that when Pence reached Arizona in the alphabetical order during the certification, he could declare the state's results as disputed and send all the electoral slates back to the states for "the final ascertainment of electors to be completed before continuing". Sekulow did not agree that Pence had such authority.<ref name="memorandum re">{{Cite news |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2021/12/10/trump-lawyer-pence-biden-524088|title=Trump campaign lawyer authored two memos claiming Pence could halt Biden's victory |work=[[Politico]] |date=December 10, 2021 |first1=Betsy Woodruff |last1=Swan |first2=Kyle |last2=Cheney |access-date=June 15, 2022 }}</ref>

===Plan to obtain National Security Agency data===
In February 2022, ''The Washington Post'' obtained a memo of unknown provenance dated December 18, 2020, that had circulated among Trump allies and was shared with some Republican senators. The memo called for Trump to direct acting defense secretary [[Christopher C. Miller|Christopher Miller]] to obtain "[[National Security Agency|NSA]] unprocessed raw signals data" in an effort to prove foreign interference in the election. The proposal called for Miller to direct three men named in the document to acquire the data. At least two Republican senators received the memo after a January 4 meeting at the Trump International Hotel attended by at least three senators and others, which had been arranged by Mike Lindell. The meeting centered around voting machines and alleged interference by China, Venezuela and other countries. The three men involved were not close to Trump and their names had not been previously reported in efforts to subvert the election. Miller said he was not aware of the memo and Trump did not act on it.<ref name="memo circulated"/>

== January 2021 ==

On New Year's Day, White House director of personnel [[John McEntee (political aide)|John McEntee]] sent a series of bullet points via text message to Pence's chief of staff to incorrectly assert that [[Thomas Jefferson]] "Used His Position as VP to Win" the 1801 election, which McEntee claimed "proves that the VP has, at a minimum, a substantial discretion to address issues with the electoral process". [[Jonathan Karl]], the ABC News chief White House correspondent for the duration of the Trump administration, wrote a November 2021 profile of McEntee, characterizing him as particularly powerful because "Trump knew he was the one person willing to do anything Trump wanted".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2021/11/trump-johnny-mcentee-january-6-betrayal/620646/ |access-date=November 21, 2021 |title=The Man Who Made January 6 Possible |first=Jonathan D. |last=Karl |date=November 9, 2021 |website=[[The Atlantic]] }}</ref><ref name="MemoFromTrumpAtty"/>

Trump reportedly reached out to [[Steve Bannon]] for advice on his quest to overturn the election results.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Jacobs |first=Jennifer |date=January 14, 2021 |title=Trump Reconciles With Ex-Strategist Steve Bannon in Talks on Election |work=[[Bloomberg L.P.]] |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2021-01-14/trump-reconciles-with-ex-strategist-bannon-in-talks-on-election |access-date=January 15, 2021}}</ref> In early January, Bannon, [[John C. Eastman|John Eastman]] and Rudy Giuliani were operating what they called a "war room" or "command center" at the [[Willard InterContinental Washington#January 6 "war room"|Willard Hotel]] near the White House with the goal of overturning the election results. [[Christina Bobb]] of the pro-Trump [[One America News]] was also a participant.<ref name="WP-20211023">{{cite news |last1=Alemany |first1=Jacqueline |last2=Brown |first2=Emma |last3=Hamburger |first3=Tom |last4=Swaine |first4=Jon |title=Ahead of Jan. 6, Willard hotel in downtown D.C. was a Trump team 'command center' for effort to deny Biden the presidency |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/investigations/willard-trump-eastman-giuliani-bannon/2021/10/23/c45bd2d4-3281-11ec-9241-aad8e48f01ff_story.html |date=October 23, 2021 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=October 23, 2021 }}</ref> Further related details of the effort to deny and overturn the election were also reported.<ref name="WP-20211029">{{cite news |last1=Dawsey |first1=Josh |last2=Alemany |first2=Jacqueline |last3=Swaine |first3=Jon |last4=Brown |first4=Emma |title=During Jan 6 riot, Trump attorney told Pence team the vice president's inaction caused attack on Capitol |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/investigations/eastman-pence-email-riot-trump/2021/10/29/59373016-38c1-11ec-91dc-551d44733e2d_story.html |date=October 29, 2021 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=October 30, 2021 }}</ref><ref name="CNN-20211030">{{cite news |last1=Kaczynski |first1=Andrew |last2=Steck |first2=Em |title=Trump lawyer John Eastman said 'courage and the spine' would help Pence send election to the House in comments before January 6 |url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/10/30/politics/kfile-john-eastman-said-pence-could-throw-election-to-house/index.html |date=October 30, 2021 |work=[[CNN]] |access-date=October 30, 2021 }}</ref><ref name="WP-20211030">{{cite news |last=Stracqualursi |first=Veronica |title=Washington Post: Trump lawyer John Eastman blamed Pence for January 6 violence by refusing to block 2020 election certification |url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/10/30/politics/mike-pence-january-6-john-eastman-trump/index.html |date=October 30, 2021 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=October 30, 2021 }}</ref><ref name="NYT-20211030lb">{{cite news |last=Broadwater |first=Luke |title=Trump Lawyer Blamed Pence for Violence as Rioters Stormed Capitol{{snd}}John Eastman, the author of a memo that some in both parties liken to a blueprint for a coup, sent a hostile email to the vice president's chief counsel as the mob attacked. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/10/30/us/politics/eastman-pence-capitol-riot.html |date=October 30, 2021 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=October 31, 2021 }}</ref>

Justice Department officials pressured Atlanta's top federal prosecutor, [[B. J. Pak]], to say there had been widespread voter fraud in Georgia, warning him that he would be fired if he did not.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Benner |first=Katie |date=August 11, 2021|title=Former U.S. attorney in Atlanta says Trump wanted to fire him for not backing election fraud claims.|newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/08/11/us/politics/byung-pak-trump-atlanta-election-fraud.html |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20211228/https://www.nytimes.com/2021/08/11/us/politics/byung-pak-trump-atlanta-election-fraud.html |archive-date=2021-12-28 |url-access=limited |url-status=live |access-date=November 21, 2021 }}{{cbignore}}</ref> The White House forced Pak to resign on January 4, 2021.<ref>{{Cite web |last3=McWhirter |first1=Aruna |last1=Viswanatha |first2=Sadie |last2=Gurman |first3=Cameron |date=January 9, 2021 |title=White House Forced Georgia U.S. Attorney to Resign |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/white-house-forced-georgia-u-s-attorney-to-resign-11610225840 |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |access-date=March 30, 2021 |archive-date=January 12, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210112020302/https://www.wsj.com/articles/white-house-forced-georgia-u-s-attorney-to-resign-11610225840 |url-status=live }}</ref>

On January 6, 2021, a joint session of Congress presided over by Vice President Pence and House Speaker [[Nancy Pelosi]] took place to [[Electoral Count Act|count the electoral votes]]. Normally a ceremonial formality, the session was interrupted by a mob that [[2021 United States Capitol attack|attacked the Capitol]].<ref name="Potter">{{Cite news |first=Trevor |last=Potter |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/outlook/2020/12/17/january-6-congress-count-trump/ |access-date=March 30, 2021 |title=No, Jan. 6 isn't another chance for Trump to reverse the election |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=December 17, 2020}}</ref><ref name="Berman">{{Cite news |first=Dan |last=Berman |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/12/31/politics/pence-gohmert-electoral-college-lawsuit/index.html |access-date=March 30, 2021 |title=Pence asks judge to reject Gohmert lawsuit asking the VP to interfere in the Electoral College count |work=[[CNN]] |date=January 1, 2021}}</ref> Trump had held a simultaneous rally on [[the Ellipse]] where he encouraged his supporters to march to the [[United States Capitol|Capitol building]].{{Citation needed|date=February 2024}}

Five lawyers who represented Trump resigned at the end of January 2021 after claiming he coerced them to repeat false claims of voter fraud.<ref>{{Cite web|last1=O'Connell|first1=Oliver|date=January 31, 2021 |title=Trump impeachment lawyers quit 10 days before Senate trial|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-election-2020/trump-impeachment-lawyers-quit-b1795451.html |access-date=June 13, 2022 |website=[[The Independent]] }}</ref>

=== ''Gohmert v. Pence'' ===
{{see also|Post-election lawsuits related to the 2020 United States presidential election#Gohmert et al. v. Pence}}

On December 27, 2020, Republican representative [[Louie Gohmert]] of Texas and the slate of Republican presidential electors for [[Arizona]] filed a lawsuit in the [[United States District Court for the Eastern District of Texas|US District Court for the Eastern District of Texas]] against Vice President [[Mike Pence]], seeking to force him to decide the election outcome.<ref name=Linton>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/louie-gohmert-trump-election-lawsuit-pence-dismissed-federal-judge/ |access-date=March 30, 2021 |work=[[CBS News]] |title=Judge dismisses Gohmert's attempt to force Pence to decide election results |first=Caroline |last=Linton |date=January 2, 2021}}</ref><ref name="gohmert dismissal">{{Cite web |url=https://www.courtlistener.com/recap/gov.uscourts.txed.203073/gov.uscourts.txed.203073.37.0.pdf |title=Order of Dismissal |work=Gohmert v. Pence |quote=6:20-cv-00660-JDK |date=January 1, 2021 |via=courtlistener.com |access-date=March 30, 2021}}</ref> Gohmert argued that the [[Electoral Count Act of 1887]] was unconstitutional, that the Constitution gave Vice President Pence the "sole" power to decide the election outcome, and that Pence had the power to "count elector votes certified by a state's executive", select "a competing slate of duly qualified electors", or "ignore all electors from a certain state".<ref name=Linton/><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/12/28/gohmert-suit-pence-overturn-trumps-defeat-451485 |date=December 28, 2020 |title=Gohmert suit may force Pence's hand in effort to overturn Trump's defeat |first=Kyle |last=Cheney |website=[[Politico]] |access-date=March 30, 2021}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/12/28/gohmert-other-republicans-sue-pence-in-last-ditch-effort-to-overturn-biden-win.html |access-date=March 30, 2021 |title=Congressman, other Republicans sue Vice President Pence in last-ditch effort to overturn Biden win |first=Kevin |last=Breuninger |date=December 28, 2020 |website=[[CNBC]]}}</ref> Pence, represented by the Justice Department, moved to dismiss the case, since Congress, and not the vice president, was a more suitable defendant. The Justice Department also argued that "the Vice President{{snd}}the only defendant in this case{{snd}}is ironically the very person whose power [plaintiffs] seek to promote. A suit to establish that the Vice President has discretion over the count, filed against the Vice President, is a walking legal contradiction."<ref name="WP-20201231">{{Cite news |last1=Helderman |first1=Rosalind S. |last2=Wagner |first2=John |title=Pence seeks rejection of lawsuit that aimed to expand his power to overturn the election |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/sasse-letter-electoral-college-ploy/2020/12/31/44da8dba-4b65-11eb-a9d9-1e3ec4a928b9_story.html |date=December 31, 2020 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=January 1, 2021}}</ref><ref name="WP-20210101"/> Lawyers for Congress also supported Pence's position.<ref name="WP-20210101" />

On January 1, 2021, U.S. District Judge [[Jeremy Kernodle]] dismissed the suit saying that due to the plaintiffs' [[Standing (law)|lack of standing]], the court lacked [[subject matter jurisdiction]] relating to the constitutional status of the Electoral Count Act.<ref name="gohmert dismissal"/><ref name="WP-20210101">{{Cite news |last=Barrett |first=Devlin |title=Judge dismisses Gohmert lawsuit seeking to stymie Biden electoral college count |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/gohmert-court-filing-claims-pence-is-not-a-glorified-envelope-opener/2021/01/01/eeb6b222-4c51-11eb-839a-cf4ba7b7c48c_story.html |date=January 1, 2021 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=January 2, 2021}}</ref><ref name="NYT-20210101">{{Cite news |last1=Edmondson |first1=Catie |last2=Haberman |first2=Maggie |title=Federal Judge Dismisses Election Lawsuit Against Pence |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/01/01/us/politics/mike-pence-louie-gohmert-lawsuit.html |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20211228/https://www.nytimes.com/2021/01/01/us/politics/mike-pence-louie-gohmert-lawsuit.html |archive-date=2021-12-28 |url-access=limited |url-status=live |date=January 1, 2021 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=January 2, 2021}}{{cbignore}}</ref> On appeal, the next day, the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit|US Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit]] dismissed Gohmert's appeal in a unanimous decision by a three-judge panel.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Federal appeals court tosses Gohmert suit aimed at overturning 2020 election results |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2021/01/01/louie-gohmert-lawsuit-pence-453387 |date=January 1, 2021 |first1=Josh |last1=Gerstein |first2=Kyle |last2=Cheney |access-date=January 3, 2021 |website=[[Politico]]}}</ref>

=== Calls with state officials ===
{{main|Trump–Raffensperger phone call}}

On January 2, 2021, Trump, Giuliani, Eastman and others held a conference call with 300 legislators of key states to provide them purported evidence of election fraud to justify calling special sessions of their legislatures in an attempt to decertify their electors. Three days later, dozens of lawmakers from five key states wrote Pence to ask he delay the January 6 final certification of electors for ten days to allow legislators the opportunity to reconsider their states' certifications.<ref name="WP-20211023"/>

That same day, Trump held a one-hour phone call with Georgia Secretary of State Brad Raffensperger.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Trump begs Georgia secretary of state to overturn election results in remarkable, hourlong phone call |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/trump-begs-georgia-secretary-state-overturn-election-results-remarkable-hourlong-n1252692 |date=January 3, 2021 |access-date=January 3, 2021 |website=[[NBC News]] |first1=Allan |last1=Smith |first2=Julia |last2=Jester |first3=Priscilla |last3=Thompson}}</ref><ref name="CNN-20210103">{{Cite news |last1=Duster |first1=Chandelis |last2=Cole |first2=Devan |title=In call, Trump demands Georgia officials 'find' votes to tilt election |url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/01/03/politics/donald-trump-brad-raffensperger-call-washington-post/index.html |date=January 3, 2021 |work=[[CNN News]] |access-date=January 3, 2021}}</ref> Trump was joined by Chief of Staff Mark Meadows, trade adviser [[Peter Navarro]], Justice Department official [[John Lott Jr.]], law professor [[John C. Eastman|John Eastman]], and attorneys Rudy Giuliani, [[Cleta Mitchell]] and Kurt Hilbert. Raffensperger was joined by his general counsel Ryan Germany.<ref name="full transcript"/> Raffensperger recorded the call, reportedly doing so while recalling his November 13 call with Trump ally and South Carolina Senator Lindsey Graham, after which Graham made public statements about the discussion that were at odds with Raffensperger's recollection.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Caputo |first=Marc |date=January 4, 2021 |title=POLITICO Playbook: The backstory of Trump's Georgia call |work=[[Politico]] |url=https://www.politico.com/newsletters/playbook/2021/01/04/the-backstory-of-trumps-georgia-call-491268 |access-date=February 8, 2022}}</ref>

In the call with Raffensperger, Trump repeatedly referred to disproven claims of election fraud and urged Raffensperger to overturn the election, saying, "I just want to find 11,780 votes".<ref name=":3" /> Raffensperger refused, noting that Georgia had certified its results after counting the votes three times,<ref name=AmySupervilleBrumback/> and said at one point in the conversation, "Well, Mr. President, the challenge you have is the data you have is wrong".<ref name=AmySupervilleBrumback>{{Cite web |first1=Jeff |last1=Amy |first2=Darlene |last2=Superville |first3=Kate |last3=Brumback |url=https://apnews.com/article/a7b4aa4d8ce3bf52301ddbe620c6bff6 |work=[[Associated Press]] |title=Trump, on tape, presses Ga. official to 'find' him votes |date=January 3, 2021 |access-date=March 30, 2021}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Bluestein |first=Greg |date=January 3, 2021 |title=Trump demands Georgia elections official overturn his defeat in hourlong call |url=https://www.ajc.com/politics/politics-blog/trump-demands-georgia-elections-official-overturn-his-defeat-in-hourlong-call/6MRGK445JNAGHBL2HXLZ3FIVZU/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210105153617/https://www.ajc.com/politics/politics-blog/trump-demands-georgia-elections-official-overturn-his-defeat-in-hourlong-call/6MRGK445JNAGHBL2HXLZ3FIVZU/ |archive-date=January 5, 2021 |access-date=January 3, 2021 |website=[[Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]}}</ref> Trump issued a vague threat suggesting that Raffensperger and his general counsel Ryan Germany might be subject to criminal liability.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Breland |first=Ali |title=Trump called the Georgia secretary of state and pressured him to find more nonexistent votes |url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2021/01/trump-called-the-georgia-secretary-of-state-and-pressured-him-to-find-more-nonexistent-votes/ |date=January 3, 2021 |access-date=January 3, 2021 |website=[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]] }}</ref> After the Georgia call, Trump and his team spoke on [[Zoom (software)|Zoom]] with officials in Arizona, Michigan, Pennsylvania and Wisconsin.<ref name="politico-jan3">{{Cite web |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2021/01/03/trump-georgia-election-454122 |title=Trump's pressure on Georgia election officials raises legal questions |first1=Allie |last1=Bice |first2=Kyle |last2=Cheney |author-link2=Kyle Cheney (journalist) |first3=Anita |last3=Kumar |website=[[Politico]] |date=January 3, 2021 |access-date=January 3, 2021}}</ref>

Raffensperger told his advisers that he did not wish a recording or a transcript to be made public unless Trump made false claims about the conversation or attacked Georgia officials. On the morning of January 3, Trump tweeted that Raffensperger "was unwilling, or unable, to answer questions" about various election-related conspiracy theories endorsed by Trump. Raffensperger replied by tweet, "Respectfully, President Trump: what you're saying is not true. The truth will come out."<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/01/03/us/politics/trump-raffensperger-call-georgia.html |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20211228/https://www.nytimes.com/2021/01/03/us/politics/trump-raffensperger-call-georgia.html |archive-date=2021-12-28 |url-access=limited |url-status=live |title=Trump, in Taped Call, Pressured Georgia Official to 'Find' Votes to Overturn Election |website=[[The New York Times]] |date=January 3, 2021 |access-date=January 3, 2021 |first1=Michael D. |last1=Shear |first2=Stephanie |last2=Saul}}{{cbignore}}</ref> Later that day, ''The Washington Post'' reported on the call and published the full audio and transcript<ref name="full transcript">{{Cite news |first1=Amy |last1=Gardner |first2=Paula |last2=Firozi |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trump-raffensperger-call-transcript-georgia-vote/2021/01/03/2768e0cc-4ddd-11eb-83e3-322644d82356_story.html |access-date=March 30, 2021 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=January 3, 2021 |title=Here's the full transcript and audio of the call between Trump and Raffensperger}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=January 3, 2021 |title='The truth's on tape.' Reactions to leaked Trump call seeking to overturn Georgia vote |url=https://www.charlotteobserver.com/news/nation-world/national/article248246235.html |access-date=January 3, 2021 |website=[[The Charlotte Observer]] |first1=Don |last1=Sweeney |first2=Bailey |last2=Aldridge}}</ref> (the Associated Press also obtained the recording that day).<ref name=AmySupervilleBrumback/>

Two months later, it was revealed that Trump had also called Raffensperger's chief investigator, Frances Watson, on December 23. He spoke to her for six minutes, during which he told her: "When the right answer comes out, you'll be praised".<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Morris |first1=Jason |last2=Murray |first2=Sara |date=March 11, 2021 |title=Wall Street Journal: Trump pressured Georgia investigator to find 'the right answer' in baseless fraud push |url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/03/10/politics/donald-trump-georgia-phone-call/index.html |access-date=March 11, 2021 |website=[[CNN]] }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Morris |first=Jason |date=March 15, 2021 |title=Officials located December recording of Trump call in a trash folder on Georgia investigator's device |url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/03/14/politics/trump-phone-call-georgia-investigator-trash-folder/index.html |access-date=March 15, 2021 |website=[[CNN]] }}</ref>

Legal experts stated that Trump's attempt to pressure Raffensperger could have violated election law,<ref name=AmySupervilleBrumback/> including federal and state laws against soliciting election fraud or interference in elections.<ref name="politico-jan3"/><ref>{{Cite web |first=Eric |last=Lipton |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/01/03/us/politics/trump-call-georgia.html |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20211228/https://www.nytimes.com/2021/01/03/us/politics/trump-call-georgia.html |url-status=live |access-date=January 17, 2023 |archive-date=2021-12-28 |url-access=limited |title=Trump Call to Georgia Official Might Violate State and Federal Law |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=January 3, 2021}}{{cbignore}}</ref> Election-law scholar [[Edward B. Foley]] called Trump's conduct "inappropriate and contemptible" while the executive director of [[Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington]] called Trump's attempt "to rig a presidential election ... a low point in American history and unquestionably impeachable conduct".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thenation.com/article/politics/trump-election-georgia-recording/ |title=Trump's Solicitation of Election Fraud Is His Highest Crime |work=[[The Nation]] |date=January 4, 2021 |first=John |last=Nichols |access-date=January 5, 2021}}</ref>

Democrats condemned Trump's conduct.<ref name=AmySupervilleBrumback/> Vice President-elect Harris, as well as Representative [[Adam Schiff]],<ref name="WP-20211008">{{cite news |last=Lozada |first=Carlos |title=Adam Schiff points to a second insurrection – by members of Congress themselves{{snd}}In his memoir [''"Midnight In Washington: How We Almost Lost Our Democracy and Still Could"''], the House Intelligence Committee chair argues America barely passed Trump's "stress test" of American democracy |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/outlook/2021/10/08/adam-schiff-midnight/ |date=October 8, 2021 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=October 9, 2021 }}</ref> (the [[House manager|chief prosecutor]] at [[First impeachment trial of Donald Trump|Trump's first impeachment trial]]) said that Trump's attempt to pressure Raffensperger was an [[abuse of power]].<ref name=AmySupervilleBrumback/><ref name=PengellyLuscombe>{{Cite web |first1=Martin |last1=Pengelly |first2=Richard |last2=Luscombe |title='I just want 11,780 votes': Trump pressed Georgia to overturn Biden victory |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2021/jan/03/trump-georgia-raffensperger-call-biden-washington-post |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=January 3, 2021 |access-date=March 30, 2021}}</ref> Senator [[Dick Durbin]] as well as Representatives [[Ted Lieu]] and [[Kathleen Rice]] requested a criminal investigation,<ref name="NBC-20210104">{{Cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Allan |last2=Moe |first2=Alex |title=Democrats ask FBI Director Wray to open criminal probe into Trump after leaked phone call |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/congress/democrats-ask-fbi-director-wray-open-criminal-probe-trump-after-n1252732 |date=January 4, 2021 |work=[[NBC News]] |access-date=January 4, 2021}}</ref> while others called Trump's conduct an impeachable offense.<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Falconer |first1=Rebecca |last2=Rummler |first2=Orion |date=January 3, 2021 |title="Impeachable offense": Democrats react to Trump's Georgia call |url=https://www.axios.com/trump-georgia-georgia-call-democrats-f400259f-9267-4d9a-bcf9-ea9fba890fb0.html |access-date=February 9, 2021 |work=[[Axios (website)|Axios]]}}</ref> More than 90 House Democrats supported a formal [[Censure in the United States|censure resolution]], introduced by Representative [[Hank Johnson]] of Georgia, to "censure and condemn" Trump for having "misused the power of his office by threatening an elected official with vague criminal consequences if he failed to pursue the president's false claims" and for attempting "to willfully deprive the citizens of Georgia of a fair and impartial election process in direct contravention" of state and federal law.<ref>{{Cite news |first=Christal |last=Hayes |title=90 House Dems support Trump censure after leaked GA election call |date=January 4, 2021 |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2021/01/04/live-politics-updates-monday-donald-trump-joe-biden/4124328001/ |work=[[USA Today]] |access-date=November 21, 2021 }}</ref><ref name="CNN-20210104">{{Cite news |last1=Raju |first1=Manu |last2=Herb |first2=Jeremy |title=House Republicans rush to Trump's defense over Georgia call as Democrats prep censure resolution |url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/01/04/politics/trump-call-republican-reaction-censure-resolution/index.html |date=January 4, 2021 |work=[[CNN News]] |access-date=January 4, 2021}}</ref>  In February 2021, [[Fulton County, Georgia|Fulton County]] District Attorney [[Fani Willis]] opened a criminal investigation into the phone call along with the phone call made by Lindsey Graham.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2021/02/10/966332808/georgia-district-attorney-is-investigating-trumps-call-to-overturn-election |access-date=November 21, 2021 |title=Georgia District Attorney Is Investigating Trump's Call To Overturn Election |first=Stephen |last=Fowler |date=February 10, 2021 |website=[[NPR]] }}</ref> In January 2022, a panel of Fulton County judges agreed to Willis's request to impanel a [[Grand juries in the United States#Special grand jury|special grand jury]] to compel testimony from individuals who had refused to cooperate.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hallerman |first1=Tamar |title=Fulton judges greenlight special grand jury for Trump probe |url=https://www.ajc.com/news/atlanta-news/breaking-fulton-judges-greenlight-special-grand-jury-for-trump-probe/DEBK3IQKLZHLBO6EYBGDXAHAU4/ |work=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230112092814/https://www.ajc.com/news/atlanta-news/breaking-fulton-judges-greenlight-special-grand-jury-for-trump-probe/DEBK3IQKLZHLBO6EYBGDXAHAU4/ |access-date=January 17, 2023 |date=January 24, 2022|archive-date=2023-01-12 }}</ref>

Several House and Senate Republicans also condemned Trump's conduct,<ref name=AmySupervilleBrumback/><ref name=LevineZanona>{{Cite news |date=January 4, 2021 |first1=Marianne |last1=Levine |first2=Melanie |last2=Zanona |title='A new low': Republicans chastise Trump over his Raffensperger call |work=[[Politico]] |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2021/01/04/republicans-trump-raffensperger-454636 |access-date=March 30, 2021}}</ref> although no Republican described the conduct as criminal or an impeachable offense as of January 4.<ref name=LevineZanona/>{{Update inline|date=February 2024|reason=More recent source that can speak to whether any Republicans after January 4th called that conduct impeachable or a criminal offense}} Republican senator [[Pat Toomey]], who was not seeking reelection in 2022, called it a "new low in this whole futile and sorry episode", and commended "Republican election officials across the country who have discharged their duties with integrity over the past two months while weathering relentless pressure, disinformation, and attacks from the president and his campaign".<ref name=LevineZanona/> Other congressional Republicans ignored or sought to defend Trump's Georgia call, including [[House Minority Leader]] [[Kevin McCarthy]]<ref name="CNN-20210104"/> and Georgia Senator [[David Perdue]], who told Fox News in an interview that he thought releasing the tape of the call was "disgusting".<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Hains |first1=Tim |title=David Perdue Says It is "Disgusting" Trump Call With Georgia Secretary Of State Was Leaked |url=https://www.realclearpolitics.com/video/2021/01/03/david_perdue_says_it_is_disgusting_trump_call_with_georgia_secretary_of_state_was_leaked.html |date=January 3, 2021 |website=Real Clear Politics |access-date=January 3, 2021 |format=Video}}</ref>

=== Justice Department pressured and efforts made to replace acting attorney general ===
The day after Attorney General [[William Barr]] said he intended to resign, Trump began to pressure his planned replacement, [[Jeffrey A. Rosen|Jeffrey Rosen]], to help him fight the election results. In particular, Trump asked Rosen to file legal briefs supporting lawsuits against the election results; to announce Justice Department investigations of alleged serious election fraud; and to appoint special prosecutors to investigate Trump's unfounded allegations of voter fraud and accusations against Dominion Voting Systems.<ref name=Benner/> Rosen refused, as did his deputy, [[Richard Donoghue]], as the Justice Department had already determined and announced that there was no evidence of widespread voter fraud.<ref name="disputing trump"/> However, Trump continued to pressure them.<ref name=Benner/>

Despite these disagreements, Rosen became acting U.S. Attorney General on December 24 as originally planned. Trump continued to pressure Rosen, asking him to go to the Supreme Court directly to invalidate the election results, but Rosen{{snd}}along with his predecessor Barr and former acting Solicitor General Jeffrey Wall{{snd}}said such a case would have no basis and refused to file it.<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Bravin |first1=Jess |last2=Gurman |first2=Sadie |date=January 24, 2021 |title= Trump Pressed Justice Department to Go Directly to Supreme Court to Overturn Election Results |work=[[Wall Street Journal]] |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-pressed-to-change-justice-department-leadership-to-boost-his-voter-fraud-claims-11611434369 |access-date=January 24, 2021 |issn=0099-9660}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Mena |first=Kelly |date=January 24, 2021 |title=The Wall Street Journal: Trump pressured DOJ to file case with Supreme Court to overturn election results |url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/01/23/politics/trump-department-of-justice-supreme-court-election-results/index.html |access-date=January 24, 2021 |website=[[CNN]] }}</ref>

Meanwhile, assistant attorney general [[Jeffrey Clark]], acting head of the [[United States Department of Justice Civil Division|Civil Division]], proposed himself as Rosen's replacement, suggesting to Trump that he would support the president's efforts to overturn the election results. Clark told Rosen and other top Justice Department officials that the Department should announce it was investigating serious election fraud issues. Clark drafted a letter to Georgia officials claiming the DOJ had "identified significant concerns that may have impacted the outcome of the election in multiple States" and urging the Georgia legislature to convene a special session for the "purpose of considering issues pertaining to the appointment of Presidential Electors".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Faulders |first1=Katherine |title=DOJ officials rejected colleague's request to intervene in Georgia's election certification: Emails |url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/doj-officials-rejected-colleagues-request-intervene-georgias-election/story?id=79243198 |work=[[ABC News (United States)|ABC News]] |date=August 3, 2021 |access-date=November 21, 2021}}</ref> Rosen and his deputy [[Richard Donoghue]] rejected the suggestion, as the Department had previously determined and announced that there was no significant fraud.<ref name="disputing trump" /> On January 3, Clark revealed to Rosen that Trump intended to appoint him in Rosen's place. Rosen, Donoghue, and head of the [[Office of Legal Counsel]] [[Steven Engel]] made a pact to resign if Rosen was removed. Confronted with the threat of mass resignations, the president backed away from the plan.<ref name="Benner">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/01/22/us/politics/jeffrey-clark-trump-justice-department-election.html |access-date=November 19, 2021 |title=Trump and Justice Dept. Lawyer Said to Have Plotted to Oust Acting Attorney General |first=Katie |last=Benner |date=January 23, 2021 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last1=Zapotosky |first1=Matt |last2=Barrett |first2=Devlin |last3=Leonnig |first3=Carol D. |title=Trump entertained plan to install an attorney general who would help him pursue baseless election fraud claims |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/trump-justice-department-overturn-election/2021/01/22/b7f0b9fa-5d1c-11eb-a976-bad6431e03e2_story.html |date=January 23, 2021 |access-date=January 23, 2021 |issn=0190-8286}}</ref> In early August 2021, Rosen and Donoghue told the [[United States Department of Justice Office of the Inspector General|Justice Department inspector general]] and members of the [[Senate Judiciary Committee]] that Clark attempted to help Trump subvert the election.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Brenner |first1=Katie |title=Former Acting Attorney General Testifies About Trump's Efforts to Subvert Election |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/08/07/us/politics/jeffrey-rosen-trump-election.html |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20211228/https://www.nytimes.com/2021/08/07/us/politics/jeffrey-rosen-trump-election.html |archive-date=2021-12-28 |url-access=limited |access-date=August 7, 2021 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=August 7, 2021 |url-status=live }}{{cbignore}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/08/07/politics/jeffrey-clark-richard-donoghue-jeffrey-rosen-justice-department-trump-election-results/index.html |access-date=November 19, 2021 |title=Interviews with former Justice Department officials provide new details on Trump efforts to undermine election results|first=Evan|last=Perez|website=[[CNN]] |date=August 7, 2021}}</ref> Rosen also told the Committee that Trump opened a January 3 Oval Office meeting with Rosen, Donoghue and Clark by saying, "One thing we know is you, Rosen, aren't going to do anything to overturn the election".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/senate-report-describes-trump-allies-efforts-doj-subvert/story?id=80456264 |title=Senate report describes Trump, allies' efforts to use DOJ to subvert 2020 election |first1=Luke |last1=Barr |first2=Alexander |last2=Mallin |work=[[ABC News (United States)|ABC News]] |date=October 7, 2021 |access-date=November 21, 2021 }}</ref>

During the closing weeks of the Trump presidency, White House chief of staff Mark Meadows sent multiple emails to Rosen, asking him to investigate conspiracy theories, including that [[Italygate conspiracy theory|satellites had been used from Italy]] to remotely switch votes from Trump to Biden. Rosen did not open the investigation.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Benner |first=Katie |date=June 5, 2021 |title=Meadows Pressed Justice Dept. to Investigate Election Fraud Claims |language=en-US |work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/06/05/us/politics/mark-meadows-justice-department-election.html |access-date=June 11, 2021 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>

=== Preparations by chief of staff ===
During the days leading up to January 6, Chief of Staff Mark Meadows sent messages in support of preparing alternate Republican electors to replace those in some states in which Biden might win. He also claimed in an email that the [[National Guard (United States)|National Guard]] would be ready to "protect pro Trump people".<ref>{{Cite web|last1=Cohen|first1=Zachary|last2=LeBlanc|first2=Paul|last3=McCullough|first3=Colin|date=2021-12-12|title=Meadows said National Guard would be ready to 'protect pro Trump people' before Capitol insurrection, House investigators say|url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/12/12/politics/mark-meadows-january-committee-contempt-of-congress-resolution/index.html|url-status=live|access-date=2021-12-13|website=[[CNN]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211213013045/https://www.cnn.com/2021/12/12/politics/mark-meadows-january-committee-contempt-of-congress-resolution/index.html |archive-date=December 13, 2021 }}</ref>

Additionally, a [[PowerPoint]] presentation on how the election could be overturned was sent by email to Meadows on January 5. The presentation, circulated by retired Army Colonel Phil Waldron<ref>{{Cite web|last=Benen|first=Steve|author-link=Steve Benen|date=17 December 2021|title=Contributor to conspiratorial PowerPoint slides gets Jan. 6 subpoena|url=https://www.msnbc.com/rachel-maddow-show/contributor-conspiratorial-powerpoint-slides-gets-jan-6-subpoena-n1286201|url-status=live|access-date=2021-12-17|website=MSNBC.com|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211217150731/https://www.msnbc.com/rachel-maddow-show/contributor-conspiratorial-powerpoint-slides-gets-jan-6-subpoena-n1286201 |archive-date=December 17, 2021 }}</ref> and apparently inspired by the ideas of [[Jovan Hutton Pulitzer]], alleged foreign interference in the election and recommended that the president declare a national emergency to delay the certification, that Pence provide alternate electors, and that the military count votes. When Meadows was subpoenaed in September 2021 by the [[United States House Select Committee on the January 6 Attack]], he provided the document to the Committee and stated that he had not acted on the plan it described.<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Broadwater |first1=Luke |last2=Feuer |first2=Alan |date=2021-12-10 |title=Jan. 6 Committee Examines PowerPoint Document Sent to Meadows |language=en-US|work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/12/10/us/politics/capitol-attack-meadows-powerpoint.html |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20211228/https://www.nytimes.com/2021/12/10/us/politics/capitol-attack-meadows-powerpoint.html |archive-date=2021-12-28 |url-access=limited |access-date=2021-12-13 |issn=0362-4331 |url-status=live }}{{cbignore}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last1=Brown |first1=Emma |last2=Swaine |first2=Jon |last3=Alemany |first3=Jacqueline |last4=Dawsey |first4=Josh |last5=Hamburger |first5=Tom |date=December 11, 2021 |title=Phil Waldron, backer of Jan. 6 PowerPoint, says he met with Mark Meadows, briefed lawmakers |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/investigations/phil-waldron-mark-meadows-powerpoint/2021/12/11/4ea67938-59df-11ec-9a18-a506cf3aa31d_story.html |url-access=limited |access-date=2021-12-13}}</ref> Of the broader context, U.S. Representative [[Ro Khanna]] said on December 15: "There were 20, 30 people who knew about it and were close to going through with it".<ref>{{Cite AV media |last=Hayes |first=Chris |author-link=Chris Hayes |date=15 December 2021 |title=Jan. 6 probe witnesses speak out |time=49:55 |url=https://all-in-with-chris-hayes.simplecast.com/episodes/jan-6-probe-witnesses-speak-out |transcript=Transcript: All In with Chris Hayes, 12/15/21 |transcript-url=https://www.msnbc.com/transcripts/transcript-all-chris-hayes-12-15-21-n1286521 |url-status=live |access-date=2021-12-17 |work=[[All In with Chris Hayes]] |publisher=[[MSNBC]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220116215816/https://www.msnbc.com/transcripts/transcript-all-chris-hayes-12-15-21-n1286521 |archive-date=January 16, 2022 }}</ref>

=== More pressure on Pence ===
In early January 2021, Trump and his supporters continued to pressure Pence into aiding their attempts to overturn election results during the January 6 certification. In early January, Trump criticized Pence for being "too honest" and warned him that people would "hate" him and believe he was "stupid".<ref>{{Cite web |last=Olander |first=Olivia |date=9 November 2022 |title='People are gonna think you're stupid': Trump warned Pence not to 'wimp out' before Jan. 6, Pence writes |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2022/11/09/donald-trump-mike-pence-book-jan-6-00066041 |access-date=2022-11-12 |website=[[Politico]] |language=en}}</ref>

On '''January 1''', Trump aide John McEntee sent a memo to Pence's chief of staff, Marc Short, titled "Jefferson used his position as VP to win", suggesting that Pence could emulate [[Thomas Jefferson]] by taking the actions encouraged by Trump and his supporters.<ref name="MemoFromTrumpAtty" />

On '''January 2''' in an appearance on Fox News, Trump aide Peter Navarro claimed that Pence had authority to delay election certification and to require an audit of the states' election results.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Politi |first1=Daniel |title=Peter Navarro Falsely Claims in TV Interview Biden Inauguration Could Be Delayed |url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2021/01/video-peter-navarro-false-biden-inauguration-delayed.html |access-date=14 February 2022 |work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] |date=January 3, 2021}}</ref> Navarro, a promoter of the [[Green Bay Sweep (politics)|Green Bay Sweep]], was intimately involved with the election-overturn effort. His remarks elicited a public response from the Vice President's office.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lucey |first1=C. |last2=Leary |first2=A. |title=Pence Faces Dilemma Over Biden Election Confirmation, as Trump Digs In |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/pence-faces-dilemma-over-biden-election-confirmation-as-trump-digs-in-11609858039 |access-date=14 February 2022 |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |date=January 5, 2021}}</ref>

On '''January 3''', [[Eastman memos]] author John Eastman briefed Marc Short and vice-presidential counsel [[Gregory Jacob|Greg Jacob]] on the arguments he had been presenting to Trump about the Vice President's certification role.<ref name="LawyerBehind" />

On '''January 4''', Trump tweeted, "the vice president has the power to reject fraudulently chosen electors".<ref name="Niedzwiadek">{{cite news |last1=Niedzwiadek |first1=Nick |last2=Cheney |first2=Kyle |title=Trump pressures Pence to throw out election results – even though he can't |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2021/01/05/trump-pressures-pence-election-results-455069 |access-date=14 February 2022 |work=[[Politico]] |date=January 5, 2021}}</ref>

Later that day, Trump told an audience of thousands at a '''January 4''' rally in Georgia, "I hope Mike Pence comes through for us ... Of course, if he doesn't come through, I won't like him quite as much".<ref name="Niedzwiadek" />

On '''January 4 and 5''', Trump met with Pence at the White House several times, attempting to persuade Pence to act as recommended by the [[Eastman memos]]; Eastman was present for at least one of the meetings.<ref name="PaperworkCoup">{{cite news |last1=Graham |first1=David |title=The Paperwork Coup |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2021/12/trumps-coup-before-january-6/620998/ |access-date=14 February 2022 |work=[[The Atlantic]] |date=December 15, 2021}}</ref><ref name="nytsep142021">{{cite news |last1=Haberman |first1=M. |last2=Karni |first2=A. |title=Pence Said to Have Told Trump He Lacks Power to Change Election Result |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/01/05/us/politics/pence-trump-election-results.html |access-date=14 February 2022 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=September 14, 2021}}</ref>

Also, on '''January 5{{snd}}'''following a January 2 call between Trump, Giuliani, Eastman, and about 300 state legislators{{snd}}several dozen of those legislators from five key states wrote to Pence and requested a 10-day delay of certification to allow reconsideration of the electoral results previously certified by those state legislatures.<ref name="WP-20211023"/>

Also on '''January 5''', Eastman communicated with Jacob.<ref name="LawyerBehind" /> That day, Jacob wrote a memo to Pence stating that Eastman's plan would violate multiple provisions of the Electoral Count Act and would assuredly be blocked in court, or if not considered by a court, would create an unprecedented political crisis and "the vice president would likely find himself in an isolated standoff against both houses of Congress...with no neutral arbiter available to break the impasse".<ref>{{cite news |title=Pence-world's final takedown of Trump's Jan. 6 bid to remain in power revealed in his lawyer's memo |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2022/06/11/pence-trump-jan-6-lawyer-memo-00038996 |access-date=January 17, 2023 |work=[[Politico]] |date=June 11, 2022 |first1=Betsy Woodruff |last1=Swan |first2=Kyle |last2=Cheney }}</ref>

On '''January 5 or the early morning of January 6''', after hearing from Pence and that he did not agree that the Vice President's power extended to actions that would change election results, Trump issued a statement falsely claiming that Pence was "in total agreement" with his contention that "the vice president has the power to act".<ref name="nytsep142021" />

On '''January 6''' in the morning, Trump called Pence and again attempted to secure his cooperation. Trump reportedly told Pence, "You can either go down in history as a patriot or you can go down in history as a pussy".<ref name="PaperworkCoup" />

On '''January 6''' at the rally preceding the [[2021 United States Capitol attack]], Trump said, "If Mike Pence does the right thing, we win the election", "Mike Pence is going to have to come through for us, and if he doesn't, that will be a sad day for our country", and "All Vice President Pence has to do is send it back to the states to recertify and we become president ...".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jacoby |first1=J. |title=This is what Trump told supporters before many stormed Capitol Hill |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/trump-told-supporters-stormed-capitol-hill/story?id=75110558 |access-date=14 February 2022 |publisher=[[ABC News (United States)|ABC News]] |date=January 7, 2021}}</ref>

Other speakers at the '''January 6''' rally, notably Giuliani and Eastman, also highlighted the actions being requested of Pence.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Giuliani |first1=R. |last2=Eastman |first2=J. |title=Rudy Giuliani Speech Transcript at Trump's Washington, D.C. Rally: Wants 'Trial by Combat' |url=https://www.rev.com/blog/transcripts/rudy-giuliani-speech-transcript-at-trumps-washington-d-c-rally-wants-trial-by-combat |website=Rev.com |date=January 6, 2021 |access-date=14 February 2022}}</ref> After the rally, during the [[2021 United States Capitol attack]], rioters chanted "Hang Mike Pence" and displayed gallows complete with a hanging noose.

During the Capitol attack on '''January 6''', Eastman emailed Jacob, who was with Pence in the Capitol, saying that the siege was occurring "because YOU and your boss did not do what was necessary".<ref name="WP-20211029"/>

Also, during the '''January 6''' Capitol attack and resulting interruption of the certification process, Trump tweeted, "Mike Pence didn't have the courage to do what should have been done to protect our Country and our Constitution".<ref name="PaperworkCoup" />

The certification process was [[Timeline of the 2021 United States Capitol attack|interrupted for about 5 hours and 53 minutes (from 2:13 p.m. to 8:06 p.m.)]].

In a meeting arranged by Senior presidential advisor [[Jared Kushner]], Trump and Pence met each other on '''January 11''' for the purpose of reconciliation.<ref name="auto11">{{Cite news |last=Baker |first=Peter |date=2022-06-08 |title=How Jared Kushner Washed His Hands of Donald Trump Before Jan. 6 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2022/06/08/us/politics/jared-kushner-trump-jan-6.html |access-date=2022-06-09 |work=[[The New York Times]] |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>

=== January 6 joint session ===
{{main|2021 United States Electoral College vote count}}

==== Senate efforts ====
In December 2020, several Republican members of the House, led by Representative [[Mo Brooks]] of Alabama,<ref name="AtLeast140" /><ref name="Fandos">{{Cite news |first=Nicholas |last=Fandos |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/12/15/us/politics/mcconnell-congratulates-biden.html |access-date=November 21, 2021 |title=Defying Trump, McConnell Seeks to Squelch Bid to Overturn the Election |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=December 15, 2020}}</ref> as well as Republican senator [[Josh Hawley]] of Missouri,<ref name="WP-20210105">{{Cite news |last=Brockell |first=Gillian |title=The senators who were expelled after refusing to accept Lincoln's election |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/history/2021/01/05/senators-expelled-lincoln-election-trump |date=January 5, 2021 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=January 5, 2021}}</ref> declared that they would formally object to the counting of the electoral votes of five swing states won by Biden during the January 6, 2021, joint session.<ref name="AtLeast140" /><ref name="Potter" /><ref name="Fandos" /> The objections would then trigger votes from both houses.<ref name="Potter" /> At least 140 House Republicans reportedly planned to vote against the counting of electoral votes, despite the lack of any credible allegation of an irregularity that would have impacted the election, and the allegations' rejections by courts, election officials, the Electoral College and others,<ref name="AtLeast140" /> and despite the fact that almost all of the Republican objectors had "just won elections in the very same balloting they are now claiming was fraudulently administered".<ref name="BroadwaterFutileBid">{{Cite news |last=Broadwater |first=Luke |title=Pence Welcomes Bid to Overturn Biden's Election as Republican Senators Join |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/01/02/us/politics/gop-senators-josh-hawley-election.html |date=January 2, 2021 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=January 2, 2021}}</ref>

Senate Majority Leader [[Mitch McConnell]], who on December 15 had acknowledged Biden's victory the day after the Electoral College vote, privately urged his Republican Senate colleagues not to join efforts by some House Republicans to challenge the vote count,<ref name=AtLeast140/> but he was unable to persuade Hawley not to lodge an objection.<ref name=EverettLambaste>{{Cite news |first=Burgess |last=Everett |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2021/01/01/republicans-hawley-election-challenge-453362 |title='Exercise in futility': Republicans lambaste Hawley's push to challenge election |work=[[Politico]] |date=January 1, 2021 |access-date=March 30, 2021}}</ref> Hawley used his objection stance in fundraising emails.<ref>{{Cite news |first=Tal |last=Axelrod |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/house/532242-outgoing-gop-congressman-criticizes-hawley-for-fundraising-of-electoral |access-date=March 30, 2021 |title=Outgoing GOP congressman criticizes Hawley for fundraising off Electoral College challenge |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |date=December 31, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/12/31/hawley-senate-republicans-453204 |first=Alex |last=Isenstadt |title=Hawley faces heat from Senate Republicans over Electoral College plans |work=[[Politico]] |date=December 21, 2020 |access-date=March 30, 2021}}</ref> Eleven Republican senators and senators-elect [[Ted Cruz]], [[Ron Johnson]], [[James Lankford]], [[Steve Daines]], [[John Kennedy (Louisiana politician)|John Kennedy]], [[Marsha Blackburn]], [[Mike Braun]], [[Cynthia Lummis]], [[Roger Marshall]], [[Bill Hagerty]], and [[Tommy Tuberville]]{{snd}}one-quarter of Senate Republicans{{snd}}announced that they would join Hawley's challenge. However, many senators acknowledged that it would not succeed. On January 2, 2021, Vice President Pence had expressed support for the attempt to overturn Biden's victory. Neither Pence nor the 11 senators planning to object made any specific allegation of fraud; rather, they vaguely suggested that some wrongdoing might have taken place.<ref name=BroadwaterFutileBid/> Other Senate Republicans were noncommittal or opposed to the attempt by the 11 Republican senators to subvert the election results.<ref name=EverettLambaste/>

Objections to the electoral votes had virtually no chance of success, as Democrats had a majority in the House of Representatives<ref name=AtLeast140/> and, although the Senate had a Republican majority, there was no majority for overturning the election results.<ref name=EverettLambaste/> [[Trevor Potter]], a Republican former chairman of the [[Federal Election Commission]] and the president of the [[Campaign Legal Center]], wrote that the counting joint session "gives Trump's die-hard supporters in Congress an opportunity to again provide more disinformation about the election on national television".<ref name=Potter/> After Senator [[John Thune]], the second highest-ranking Senate Republican, said that the challenge to the election results would fail "like a shot dog" in the Senate, Trump attacked him on Twitter.<ref name=BroadwaterFutileBid/><ref>{{Cite news |first=Joe |last=Sneve |url=https://www.argusleader.com/story/news/2021/01/01/south-dakota-gov-noem-again-passes-president-trumps-calls-her-challenge-sen-thune/4109569001/ |title=Trump again attacks Thune via Twitter, Noem repeats she won't challenge for Senate seat |work=[[Argus Leader|Sioux Falls Argus Leader]] |date=January 1, 2021 |access-date=January 5, 2021}}</ref>

In early January, Trump began to pressure Pence to take action to overturn the election. As vice president, Pence presides over the Congressional session to count the electoral votes{{snd}}normally a non-controversial, ceremonial event. For days beforehand, Trump demanded both in public and in private that Pence use that position to overturn the election results in swing states and declare Trump–Pence the winners of the election.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/01/05/us/politics/pence-trump-election.html |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20211228/https://www.nytimes.com/2021/01/05/us/politics/pence-trump-election.html |url-status=live |archive-date=2021-12-28 |url-access=limited |title=Trump Says Pence Can Overturn His Loss in Congress. That's Not How It Works. |last=Schmidt |first=Michael S. |date=January 5, 2021 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=January 6, 2021}}{{cbignore}}</ref> Pence demurred that the law does not give him that power, but Trump insisted that "The vice president and I are in total agreement that the vice president has the power to act".<ref name="nytsep142021"/> Pence ultimately released a statement stating: "It is my considered judgment that my oath to support and defend the Constitution constrains me from claiming unilateral authority to determine which electoral votes should be counted and which should not".<ref>{{Cite news |title=Pence Says He Doesn't Have Power To Reject Electoral Votes |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/congress-electoral-college-tally-live-updates/2021/01/06/953995808/pence-says-he-doesnt-have-power-to-reject-electoral-votes |first=Alana |last=Wise |date=January 6, 2021 |access-date=January 7, 2021 |newspaper=[[NPR]] }}</ref>

An hour before the joint session was set to start, the president's lawyer Rudy Giuliani tried to call freshman senator [[Tommy Tuberville]] but accidentally left a message in the voicemail of another senator, which was subsequently leaked to ''[[The Dispatch]]'', stating that "we need you, our Republican friends, to try to just slow it down&nbsp;... So if you could object to every state and, along with a congressman, get a hearing for every state, I know we would delay you a lot, but it would give us the opportunity to get the legislators who are very, very close to pulling their vote&nbsp;... they have written letters asking that you guys adjourn and send them back the questionable ones and they'll fix them up".<ref>{{Cite web |last=Hayes |first=Steve |title=Giuliani to Senator: 'Try to Just Slow it Down' |url=https://thedispatch.com/p/giuliani-to-senator-try-to-just-slow |date=January 6, 2021 |access-date=January 7, 2021 |website=[[The Dispatch]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last1=Serfaty |first1=Sunlen |last2=Cole |first2=Devan |last3=Rogers |first3=Alex |date=January 9, 2021 |title=As riot raged at Capitol, Trump tried to call senators to overturn election |url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/01/08/politics/mike-lee-tommy-tuberville-trump-misdialed-capitol-riot/index.html |access-date=January 9, 2021 |website=[[CNN]] }}</ref>

==== House votes ====
At the January 6 session, after Republican senators had raised objections to Biden's electoral victory, the House debated and voted. A majority of Republicans, totaling 139 and including Republican leader Kevin McCarthy and his deputy [[Steve Scalise]], voted to support at least one objection.<ref>{{Cite news |first1=Harry |last1=Stevens |first2=Daniela |last2=Santamariña |first3=Kate |last3=Rabinowitz |first4=Kevin |last4=Uhrmacher |first5=John |last5=Muyskens |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/2021/politics/congress-electoral-college-count-tracker/ |title=How members of Congress voted on counting the electoral college vote |date=January 7, 2021 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=January 13, 2021}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2021/jan/07/list-republicans-voted-to-reject-election-results |title=The long list of Republicans who voted to reject election results |date=January 7, 2021 |first=Alvin |last=Chang |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=January 13, 2021}}</ref>

==== Report by Rep. Zoe Lofgren ====
At the end of February 2021, Democratic Rep. [[Zoe Lofgren]], chair of the House Administration Committee, released a nearly 2,000-page report that examined the social media posts between election night and January 6 of Republican leaders who had voted against certifying the election results, writing "Many of former President Trump's false statements were made in very public settings. Had Members made similar public statements in the weeks and months before the January 6th attack? Statements which are readily available in the public arena may be part of any consideration of Congress' constitutional prerogatives and responsibilities."<ref>{{Cite web |last=Fox |first=Lauren |date=February 5, 2021 |title=Democratic Rep. Zoe Lofgren quietly releases massive social media report on GOP colleagues who voted to overturn the election |url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/03/05/politics/lofgren-social-media-report-gop-lawmakers/index.html |access-date=March 8, 2021 |website=[[CNN]] }}</ref>

=== Capitol attack ===
{{main|January 6 United States Capitol attack}}
[[File:70.East.USCapitol.WDC.6January2021 (50823235308).jpg|thumb|Protesters on Capitol grounds, January 6, 2021]]
[[File:DC Capitol Storming IMG 7940.jpg|thumb|Rioters attacking the Capitol]]
<section begin=Capitol attack/>Starting in December, Trump repeatedly encouraged his supporters to protest in Washington, D.C., on January 6 in support of his campaign to overturn the election results,<ref name="Lang" /> telling his supporters to "Be there, will be wild!"<ref>{{Cite news |first=Adam |last=Shaw |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/trump-wild-protest-washington-dc-jan-6 |title=Trump promises 'wild' protest in Washington DC on Jan 6, claims it's 'impossible' he lost |work=[[Fox News]] |date=December 19, 2020 |access-date=January 5, 2021}}</ref> ''The Washington Post'' editorial board criticized Trump for urging street protests, referring to previous violence by some Trump supporters at two rallies and his statement during a presidential debate telling the [[Proud Boys]] to "stand back and stand by".<ref>{{Cite news |author=Editorial Board |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/trump-is-inciting-chaos-on-jan-6-both-in-and-outside-the-capitol/2020/12/30/7c4196b0-4ad2-11eb-839a-cf4ba7b7c48c_story.html |title=Trump is inciting chaos on Jan. 6, both in and outside the Capitol |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=December 30, 2020 |access-date=January 5, 2021}}</ref> Multiple groups of die-hard Trump supporters staged rallies in Washington on that day: Women for America First; the Eighty Percent Coalition (also at Freedom Plaza) (the group's name refers to the belief that approximately 80% of Trump voters do not accept the legitimacy of Biden's win); and "The Silent Majority" (a group organized by a South Carolina conservative activist).<ref name="Lang">{{Cite news |first=Marissa J. |last=Lang |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trump-january6-dc-protest/2020/12/30/1773b19c-4acc-11eb-839a-cf4ba7b7c48c_story.html |title=Jan. 6 protests multiply as Trump continues to call supporters to Washington |access-date=November 21, 2021 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=December 30, 2020}}</ref><ref name="JacksonBrown">{{Cite news |first1=David |last1=Jackson |first2=Matthew |last2=Brown |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/12/31/elections-protest-dc-police-brace-donald-trump-demonstrators/4097472001/ |access-date=November 21, 2021 |title='Wild' protests: Police brace for pro-Trump rallies when Congress meets Jan 6 to certify Biden's win |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |date=January 2, 2021}}</ref> [[George Papadopoulos]] and [[Roger Stone]], ardent allies of Trump, headlined some of the events. In addition to the formally organized events, the Proud Boys, other [[far-right]] groups, and [[white supremacists]] vowed to descend on Washington on January 6, with some threatening violence and pledging to carry weapons.<ref name="Lang" /> Proud Boys leader [[Enrique Tarrio]] said that his followers would "be incognito" and would "spread across downtown DC in smaller teams".<ref name="JacksonBrown" /><noinclude> On January 4, Tarrio was arrested by District police on misdemeanor and felony charges.<ref name="WP-20210104ph">{{Cite news |last1=Hermann |first1=Peter |last2=Weil |first2=Martin |title=Proud Boys leader arrested in the burning of Black Lives Matter banner, D.C. police say |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/public-safety/proud-boys-enrique-tarrio-arrest/2021/01/04/8642a76a-4edf-11eb-b96e-0e54447b23a1_story.html |date=January 4, 2021 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=January 4, 2021}}</ref></noinclude>

As the certification process was underway, Trump gave a speech encouraging his supporters to march to the Capitol. Many of them did, whereupon they joined other protesters already gathered in the area and violently breached and stormed the Capitol, eventually entering the Senate chamber as well as numerous offices. The Congressional proceedings were suspended, the legislators were taken to secure locations, and [[Nancy Pelosi]] was evacuated.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mediaite.com/news/breaking-trump-supporters-waving-confederate-flags-breach-the-capitol-vp-pence-evacuated-senate-in-lockdown/ |first=Josh |last=Feldman |access-date=January 7, 2021 |work=Mediaite |title=Trump Supporters Breach Capitol Building as Violent Clashes Continue |date=January 6, 2021}}</ref><section end=Capitol attack/> Protestors penetrated the Senate chamber.<ref>{{Cite tweet |user=jamiedupree |first=Jamie |last=Dupree |number=1346909466386579457 |access-date=November 21, 2021 |title=A protester sitting in the chair of the Senate chamber pic.twitter.com/4FZ5Rziqd9 |date=January 6, 2021}}</ref> One unarmed woman was shot and killed by [[United States Capitol Police|Capitol Police]] inside the Capitol building after she attempted to climb through a broken door into the Speaker's Lobby, leading to the House chamber; the officer who shot her was placed on administrative leave pending an investigation, and was ultimately cleared of any wrongdoing.<ref name="Smith_Gibson_Arkin_Williams_1/6/2021">{{Cite web |last1=Smith |first1=Allan |last2=Gibson |first2=Ginger |last3=Arkin |first3=Daniel |last4=Williams |first4=Pete |title=Senate evacuated, National Guard activated after pro-Trump protesters storm Capitol |work=[[NBC News]] |date=January 6, 2021 |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/we-will-never-concede-trump-baselessly-asserts-voter-fraud-speech-n1253011 |access-date=January 6, 2021}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last1=Wild|first1=Whitney|last2=Duster|first2=Chandelis|date=23 August 2021|title=US Capitol Police says shooting of January 6 rioter Ashli Babbitt was 'lawful'|url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/08/23/politics/ashli-babbitt-capitol-police-officer/index.html|url-status=live|access-date=2021-08-23|website=[[CNN]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210823173150/https://www.cnn.com/2021/08/23/politics/ashli-babbitt-capitol-police-officer/index.html |archive-date=August 23, 2021 }}</ref> Another rioter died of a drug overdose, and three succumbed to natural causes.<ref name="YsUXQ">{{Cite news |access-date=January 17, 2023 |last=Evelyn |first=Kenya |date=January 9, 2021 |title=Capitol attack: the five people who died |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2021/jan/08/capitol-attack-police-officer-five-deaths |website=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> A Capitol Police officer died from a stroke the next day.<ref name="MedExaminer">{{Cite news |date=April 19, 2021 |title=Capitol Police officer Brian Sicknick, who engaged rioters, suffered two strokes and died of natural causes, officials say |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/public-safety/brian-sicknick-death-strokes/2021/04/19/36d2d310-617e-11eb-afbe-9a11a127d146_story.html |access-date=April 19, 2021 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |first1=Peter |last1=Hermann |first2=Spencer S. |last2=Hsu }}</ref>

As the attack progressed, Pence was evacuated from the Senate chamber to a basement room, as Trump tweeted, "Mike Pence didn't have the courage to do what should have been done to protect our Country and our Constitution". The Secret Service prepared to evacuate Pence to [[Andrews Air Force Base]]. [[Carol Leonnig]] and [[Philip Rucker]] reported in their book ''[[I Alone Can Fix It]]'' that Pence was brought to his armored limousine but told his security chief Tim Giebels, "I'm not leaving the Capitol...If I get in that vehicle, you guys are taking off. I'm not getting in the car." Pence remained at the Capitol and certified the election results late that night.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/10/21/politics/secret-service-testimony-jan-6-pence/index.html |access-date=January 17, 2023 |title=DOJ plans for Secret Service testimony about Pence at first scheduled Capitol riot trial |first=Katelyn |last=Polantz |work=[[CNN]] |date=October 21, 2021}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/administration/563513-pence-refused-to-leave-capitol-during-riot-book|title=Pence refused to leave Capitol during riot: book|first=Celine|last=Castronuovo|date=July 16, 2021|work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |access-date=January 17, 2023 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |access-date=January 17, 2023 |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2021/01/06/electoral-vote-update-congress-resumes-counting-after-pro-trump-rioters-invade-capitol.html |title=Congress confirms Biden election as president, morning after Trump-fueled mob invades Capitol |first1=Dan |last1=Mangan |first2=Jacob |last2=Pramuk |first3=Kevin |last3=Breuninger |date=January 7, 2021 |work=[[CNBC]]}}</ref>

On January 3, 2022, ''[[Newsweek]]'' reported, for the first time, the deployment of undercover commandos at the Capitol on January 6, 2021, to manage the "most extreme possibilities", including an attack on President Donald Trump or Vice President Mike Pence.<ref name="NSW-202209103">{{cite news |last=Arkin |first=William M. |title=Exclusive: Secret Commandos with Shoot-to-Kill Authority Were at the Capitol |url=https://www.newsweek.com/exclusive-secret-commandos-shoot-kill-authority-were-capitol-1661330 |date=January 3, 2022 |work=[[Newsweek]] |access-date=January 3, 2022 }}</ref>{{citation needed|reason=''[[Newsweek]]'' *may* not be reliable post-2013, per [[WP:RSP]]|date=January 2022}}

According to a January 3, 2022, [[CNN News]] report, the United States House Select Committee on the January 6 Attack has learned that Trump did nothing to stop the attack as it was unfolding. Leaders of the committee [[Bennie Thompson]] (D-[[Mississippi|MS]]) and [[Liz Cheney]] (R-[[Wyoming|WY]]) have characterized his failure to intervene, despite being asked to do so, as "dereliction of duty".<ref name="CNN-20220103">{{cite news |last=Gangel |first=Jamie |title=January 6 committee has 'firsthand' knowledge of Trump's behavior during the riot from multiple sources |url=https://www.cnn.com/2022/01/03/politics/january-6-committee-firsthand-knowledge-trump-actions/index.html |date=January 3, 2022 |work=[[CNN News]] |access-date=January 3, 2022 }}</ref> In April 2022, Cheney stated:<blockquote>It's absolutely clear that what President Trump was doing, what a number of people around him were doing, that they knew it was unlawful ... I think what we have seen is a massive and well-organized and well-planned effort that used multiple tools to try to overturn an election.<ref name="POL-20220410">{{cite news |last=Ward |first=Myah |date=April 10, 2022 |title=Cheney says Jan. 6 committee has enough evidence for a criminal referral for Trump{{snd}}Her statement followed a New York Times report that said the panel is divided on whether to move forward. |work=[[Politico]] |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2022/04/10/cheney-evidence-trump-criminal-referral-00024290 |access-date=April 11, 2022}}</ref><ref name="Schmidt_Broadwater_4/10/2022">{{cite news |title=Jan. 6 Panel Has Evidence for Criminal Referral of Trump, but Splits on Sending |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2022/04/10/us/politics/jan-6-trump-criminal-referral.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=April 10, 2022 |first1=Michael S. |last1=Schmidt |first2=Luke |last2=Broadwater |access-date=January 17, 2023 }}</ref></blockquote>

=== Trump operatives breach Coffee County, Georgia election system ===
{{Main|Prosecution of Donald Trump in Georgia#Coffee County election equipment breach}}
On January 1, 2021, lawyers on Trump's team asked a Georgia tech firm to assist them in looking into voting systems in Coffee County, Georgia.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cohen |first1=Zachary |date=April 21, 2023 |title=Exclusive: Text messages reveal Trump operatives considered using breached voting data to decertify Georgia's Senate runoff in 2021 |publisher=[[CNN]]|url=https://www.cnn.com/2023/04/21/politics/trump-georgia-senate-breached-voting-data/index.html}}</ref> On January 7, one of the fake electors in Georgia escorted two Trump operatives into the county's election office, and the Trump team copied data from the office.<ref name=":112">{{Cite web |last1=Cohen |first1=Zachary |last2=Morris |first2=Jason |date=6 September 2022 |title=Newly obtained surveillance video shows fake Trump elector escorted operatives into Georgia county's elections office before voting machine breach |url=https://www.cnn.com/2022/09/06/politics/surveillance-video-voting-machine-breach-coffee-county-georgia/index.html |access-date=2022-09-06 |website=[[CNN]]}}</ref>

[[Fani Willis]] examined this incident as part of the [[2020 Georgia election investigation]]. On August 14, 2023, Trump and 18 co-defendants were [[Prosecution of Donald Trump in Georgia|indicted in the Georgia case]], and four of the 19 defendants—[[Sidney Powell]], Misty Hampton, Cathleen Latham, and Scott G. Hall—were charged in the Coffee County breach.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Cohen |first=Zachary |date=August 15, 2023 |title=Indictment zeroes in on Trump supporters who breached voting system in Coffee County, Georgia |language=en |publisher=[[CNN]]|url=https://www.cnn.com/politics/live-news/trump-fulton-county-georgia-08-14-23/h_82eb60f2052019a1aaba10ed9ac52b21 |access-date=August 15, 2023}}</ref>

=== Lindell memo ===
{{Main|Mike Lindell#Attempts to overturn 2020 presidential election}}
On January&nbsp;15, Trump ally and [[My Pillow|My&nbsp;Pillow]] CEO [[Mike Lindell]] visited the White House, where he was photographed carrying notes that appeared to suggest an additional attempt to overturn the election.<ref name="frankcolon">{{Cite web |url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2021/01/frank-colon-who-mike-lindell-wants-for-a-coup-is-confused.html |access-date=November 21, 2021 |title=Even the Guy the MyPillow CEO Wanted to Enlist for a Coup Is Confused |first=Ben |last=Jacobs |date=January 16, 2021 |website=[[New York (magazine)|New York Intelligencer]]}}</ref> The document bore a heading containing the words "taken immediately to save&nbsp;... Constitution"<ref>{{Cite magazine |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/politics-news/trump-meets-my-pillow-ceo-mark-lindell-martial-law-1115519/ |access-date=November 21, 2021 |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |title=Trump Calls in Pillow Salesman to Discuss Possibility of Instituting Martial Law |first1=Ryan |last1=Bort |date=January 16, 2021}}</ref> and called for [[780th Military Intelligence Brigade (United States)|780th Military Intelligence Brigade (Cyber)]] civilian lawyer<ref name="frankcolon"/> "Frank Colon NOW as Acting National Security [''illegible'']", and mentioned the "Insurrection Act" and "martial law".<ref name="frankcolon"/> It further recommended "[m]ov[ing] [[Kash Patel]] to CIA Acting"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2021/01/15/pillow-salesman-apparently-has-some-ideas-about-declaring-martial-law/ |title=A pillow salesman apparently has some ideas about declaring martial law |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=January 16, 2021 |first=Philip |last=Bump |access-date=February 10, 2021}}</ref> and made reference to Trump loyalist [[Sidney Powell]].<!--, [[Bill Olsen]], and [[Kurt Olsen]]--><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://talkingpointsmemo.com/news/mypillow-ceo-spotted-bringing-notes-to-wh-that-appear-to-reference-martial-law-installing-new-cia-director |title=MyPillow CEO Spotted Bringing Notes To WH That Appear To Reference 'Martial Law,' Installing New CIA Director |first=Kate |last=Riga |date=January 15, 2021 |website=[[Talking Points Memo]]|access-date=November 21, 2021 }}</ref>

== Later developments ==

=== Taxpayer costs ===
According to a ''Washington Post'' assessment published February 6, 2021, Trump's falsehoods about fraud had cost taxpayers more than half a billion dollars in spending to enhance security, resolve legal disputes and repair property, among other things.<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Olorunnipa |first1=Toluse |last2=Ye Hee Lee |first2=Michelle |date=February 6, 2021 |title=Trump's lie that the election was stolen has cost $519 million (and counting) as taxpayers fund enhanced security, legal fees, property repairs and more |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/interactive/2021/cost-trump-election-fraud/ |access-date=November 21, 2021 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |author-link2=Michelle Ye Hee Lee}}</ref>

=== Security concerns over March 4, 2021 ===
{{Main|Aftermath of the January 6 United States Capitol attack#Security concerns over March 4, 2021|l1 = Concerns over March 4, 2021}}
Security was bolstered in Washington, D.C., in preparation for March 4, which QAnon adherents, adopting a false belief from [[Sovereign citizen movement|sovereign citizen]] ideology, believed would be the day Trump was re-inaugurated as president.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Collins|first1=Ben|last2=Zadrozny|first2=Brandy|author-link2=Brandy Zadrozny|date=March 2, 2021|title=D.C. police, FBI on alert ahead of QAnon's 'true Inauguration Day'|publisher=[[NBC News]]|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/tech/internet/dc-police-fbi-alert-ahead-qanons-true-inauguration-day-rcna331|access-date=March 2, 2021}}</ref> The House prematurely ended its work for the week following an announcement by the Capitol Police of intelligence on a "possible plot" by an identified militia group to breach the Capitol building on that day.<ref>{{cite news|last=Balsamo|first=Michael|date=March 3, 2021|title=Police uncover 'possible plot' by militia to breach Capitol|publisher=[[Associated Press|AP News]]|url=https://apnews.com/article/police-uncover-possible-plot-militia-breach-capitol-c470dc642d9b568238f80b5822787159|access-date=March 3, 2021|archive-date=March 4, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210304053856/https://apnews.com/article/police-uncover-possible-plot-militia-breach-capitol-c470dc642d9b568238f80b5822787159|url-status=live}}</ref> Ultimately, March 4 passed without any serious incidents being reported.

===Election audits===
Alleging fraud, during 2021 Republicans initiated or proposed audits in several states, in addition to the [[election audit]]s done normally in some states, which do not always include the presidency.

An [[2021 Maricopa County presidential ballot audit|audit in Maricopa County, Arizona]] that began in April inspired Republicans in other states to pursue similar efforts, with some calling for audits in all fifty states.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/not-just-arizona-republicans-push-more-partisan-election-audits-n1268644 |access-date=November 21, 2021 |title=Not just Arizona: Republicans push more partisan election inquiries |first=Allan |last=Smith |date=June 4, 2021 |website=[[NBC News]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.mlive.com/public-interest/2021/10/3-michigan-republicans-join-national-call-for-forensic-audit-of-2020-election.html |first=Samuel J. |last=Robinson |access-date=November 21, 2021 |title=3 Michigan Republicans join national call for 'forensic audit' of 2020 election|date=October 6, 2021|website=[[Booth Newspapers|MLive.com]]}}</ref> More than a year after the election, Trump supporters continued to pressure state election officials to investigate or decertify the outcome, even in states where Trump won by a large margin.<ref>{{cite news |title=Inside the nonstop pressure campaign by Trump allies to get election officials to revisit the 2020 vote |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trump-election-officials-pressure-campaign/2021/12/22/8a0b0788-5d26-11ec-ae5b-5002292337c7_story.html |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=December 22, 2021 |first1=Amy |last1=Gardner |first2=Emma |last2=Brown |first3=Josh |last3=Dawsey |access-date=June 14, 2022 }}</ref>

An Associated Press analysis published in December 2021 examined every potential case of voter fraud in the six battleground states that Trump had challenged. The analysis found 473 potential incidents. Even if all the incidents involved votes for Biden, which they did not, and involved ballots that were actually counted, which they did not, the number was far smaller than would have been necessary to change the election outcome. The analysis found no evidence of organized fraud but rather in virtually every case it involved an individual acting alone.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/article/voter-fraud-election-2020-joe-biden-donald-trump-7fcb6f134e528fee8237c7601db3328f |access-date=June 14, 2022 |title=Far too little vote fraud to tip election to Trump, AP finds|date=December 14, 2021 |work=[[Associated Press]] |first=Christina A. |last=Cassidy }}</ref>

==== Arizona ====
{{Main|2020 United States presidential election in Arizona#Audits and Recounts by Election Officials|2021 Maricopa County presidential ballot audit}}

On March 31, 2021, the [[Arizona Senate]] Republican caucus hired four firms to perform an [[2020 United States presidential election in Arizona#Audit ordered by Arizona Senate Republicans|audit of the presidential ballots]] in [[Maricopa County, Arizona|Maricopa County]], with a [[Florida]]-based company called Cyber Ninjas being the lead firm.<ref name="AP May 10">{{Cite news |title=Inside Arizona's election audit, GOP fraud fantasies live on |url=https://apnews.com/article/arizona-election-recount-b38a9205c306796f914d62bbad601587 |access-date=November 21, 2021 |date=May 10, 2021 |work=[[Associated Press]] |first1=Jonathan J. |last1=Cooper |first2=Bob |last2=Christie}}</ref> There was no stated purpose of overturning the election, and there is no mechanism under the [[United States Constitution|Constitution]] by which the Congressional certification of the result could be reversed. Arizona Senate President [[Karen Fann]] said that the audit was not intended to overturn the state's election results, including at a July 15 hearing.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://ktar.com/story/4570920/arizona-sen-karen-fann-at-audit-hearing-this-is-not-about-trump/ |access-date=November 21, 2021 |title=Arizona Sen. Karen Fann at audit hearing: 'This is not about Trump' |last1=Stone |first1=Kevin |date=July 15, 2021 |website=[[KTAR-FM]] }}</ref> Nevertheless, Trump and some of his supporters expressed the hope that the Arizona result would be changed and that there might be a "domino effect" in which other states changed their results.<ref>Multiple sources:
* {{Cite web |url=https://www.newsweek.com/trump-suggests-arizona-recount-will-first-domino-fall-lets-see-what-they-find-1588060 |title=Trump Suggests Arizona Recount Will Be First Domino to Fall: 'Let's See What They Find' |last=Colarossi |first=Natalie |date=May 1, 2021 |work=[[Newsweek]] |access-date=May 18, 2021}}
* {{Cite web |url=https://welovetrump.com/2021/04/22/maricopa-county-are-moving-machines-to-be-audited/ |title=Maricopa County Are Moving Machines To Be Audited |last=T |first=Anthony |date=April 22, 2021 |website=welovetrump.com |access-date=May 18, 2021}}
* {{Cite web |url=https://welovetrump.com/2021/05/03/az-gop-chair-kelli-ward-arizona-is-the-first-domino-that-will-fall/ |first=Vince |last=Quill |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210508200728/https://welovetrump.com/2021/05/03/az-gop-chair-kelli-ward-arizona-is-the-first-domino-that-will-fall/ |archive-date=May 8, 2021 |title=AZ GOP Chair Kelli Ward: Arizona Is The First Domino That Will Fall |date=May 3, 2021 |url-status=live |website=welovetrump.com |access-date=May 18, 2021}}
* {{Cite web |url=https://www.havasunews.com/opinion/bruce-warner-how-2020-election-could-be-overturned/article_0aaefcda-b22a-11eb-8996-83f78b4291c6.html |title=Bruce Warner: How 2020 election could be overturned |last=Warner |first=Bruce |date=May 11, 2021 |website=havasunews.com |access-date=May 18, 2021}}</ref>

The auditors released a report on September 24, 2021, finding no proof of fraud and that their ballot recount increased Biden's margin of victory by 360 votes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/09/24/politics/arizona-election-review-results/index.html |date=September 24, 2021 |title=Final report from partisan Arizona review confirms Biden defeated Trump in Maricopa County last November|first1=Eric |last1=Bradner |first2=Anna-Maja |last2=Rappard |website=[[CNN]] |access-date=September 25, 2021|archive-date=September 24, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210924111709/https://www.cnn.com/2021/09/24/politics/arizona-election-review-results/index.html|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last1=Healy|first1=Jack|last2=Wines|first2=Michael|last3=Corasaniti|first3=Nick|date=September 24, 2021|title=Republican Review of Arizona Vote Fails to Show Stolen Election|language=en-US|work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/09/24/us/arizona-election-review-trump-biden.html|access-date=September 24, 2021|issn=0362-4331|archive-date=September 24, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210924101013/https://www.nytimes.com/2021/09/24/us/arizona-election-review-trump-biden.html|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=":1">{{Cite news|last=Leary|first=Alex|date=September 24, 2021|title=Arizona GOP's Election Audit Confirms Biden Win in Draft Report|language=en-US|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/arizona-gops-election-audit-confirms-biden-win-in-draft-report-11632467822|access-date=September 24, 2021|issn=0099-9660|archive-date=September 24, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210924125130/https://www.wsj.com/articles/arizona-gops-election-audit-confirms-biden-win-in-draft-report-11632467822|url-status=live}}</ref> Following the audit, [[Governor of Arizona|Arizona Governor]] [[Doug Ducey]] rejected calls for the state's election to be decertified or overturned.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/trump-election-2020-doug-ducey-b1926988.html |first=Sheila |last=Flynn |access-date=November 21, 2021 |title=Arizona governor says state won't decertify 2020 election results, 'outcome stands'|date=September 25, 2021|website=[[The Independent]] }}</ref>

In January 2022, Maricopa County election officials released a final report finding nearly every claim the auditors made was false or misleading.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Correcting the Record: Maricopa County's In-Depth Analysis of the Senate Inquiry |url=https://elections.maricopa.gov/asset/jcr:a9e03750-0a8f-4162-859f-1d46ac54b485/Correcting%20The%20Record%20-%20January%202022%20Report.pdf |access-date=August 30, 2023 |date=January 2022 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220615171352/https://elections.maricopa.gov/asset/jcr:a9e03750-0a8f-4162-859f-1d46ac54b485/Correcting%20The%20Record%20-%20January%202022%20Report.pdf |archive-date=2022-06-15 |publisher=[[Maricopa County, Arizona]] |work=Maricopa County Elections Department & Office of the Recorder }}</ref> The next day, Cyber Ninjas announced it was shutting down, as a Maricopa County judge imposed a $50,000 contempt fine on the company for every day it refused to hand over documents as it had been ordered to do months earlier.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/politics-news/cyber-ninjas-company-led-arizona-gop-election-audit-shutting-down-n1287145 |access-date=June 14, 2022 |title=Cyber Ninjas, company that led Arizona GOP election 'audit,' is shutting down |work=[[NBC News]] |first=Dartunorro |last=Clark|date=January 6, 2022}}</ref>

After a six-month investigation into alleged fraud by Maricopa County election officials in the 2020 presidential election, Arizona attorney general [[Mark Brnovich]] said in April 2022 that he found no proof of fraud.<ref>{{cite news |author1=Jonathan J. Cooper |author2=Bob Christie |date=April 7, 2022 |title=Arizona AG letter offers no proof of 2020 election fraud |publisher=[[Associated Press|AP News]] |url=https://apnews.com/article/2022-midterm-elections-donald-trump-phoenix-congress-elections-b53523ff5a568bcef9dca78c3d120698}}</ref> He released an interim report claiming that "serious vulnerabilities" had been identified, omitting his investigators' findings to the contrary and withholding the more complete report. Brnovich was succeeded by [[Kris Mayes]]. When Brnovich left office in January 2023, Mayes released the more complete report that had been written during Brnovich's tenure showing that none of the allegations against the Maricopa County election board had merit.<ref>{{cite news |author1=Yvonne Wingett Sanchez |author2=Isaac Stanley-Becker |date=February 22, 2023 |title=Arizona's top prosecutor concealed records debunking election fraud claims |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2023/02/22/arizona-election-fraud-claims-mark-brnovich/ |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]}}</ref>

On April 23, 2024, Arizona [[Arizona prosecution of fake electors|indicted]] 11 fake electors and seven Trump allies and described five unindicted coconspirators.

====Georgia====
{{Main|2020 United States presidential election in Georgia#Statewide audit and recount}}
A group called VoterGA filed a lawsuit requesting to examine by microscope 150,000 [[Fulton County, Georgia|Fulton County]] ballots that it asserted might be counterfeit. The suit arose after four Republican auditors involved with the [[2020 United States presidential election in Georgia#Statewide audit and recount|November 2020 statewide audit and manual recount]] claimed to see what they asserted were "pristine" absentee ballots which they suspected might have been computer-generated, though an October 2021 investigation by the Georgia secretary of state's office found that there were no counterfeit ballots in the batches named by the complainants.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Niesse |first1=Mark |title=No counterfeit ballots found by Georgia election investigators |url=https://www.ajc.com/politics/no-counterfeit-ballots-found-by-georgia-election-investigators/OFRHJDGKOJH7BMKCH77VMR63NM/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220604073218/https://www.ajc.com/politics/no-counterfeit-ballots-found-by-georgia-election-investigators/OFRHJDGKOJH7BMKCH77VMR63NM/ |archive-date=June 4, 2022 |url-status=live |work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution |date=October 12, 2021 |access-date=June 14, 2022 }}</ref> After an initial ruling in favor of the suit by a superior court judge in May 2021, it was ultimately dismissed in October because the plaintiffs "failed to allege a particularized injury". The dismissal of the suit marked the end of the last remaining lawsuit challenging the Georgia election results until another suit making largely the same argument was subsequently filed. In December 2021, that suit was joined by [[David Perdue]], who had announced his candidacy for Georgia governor days earlier. Perdue lost his bid to be reelected as a United States senator in 2020 and asserted that he, like Trump, had been cheated.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/05/21/politics/georgia-ballot-audit-fulton-county/index.html |date=May 24, 2021 |title=Another ballot audit set to move ahead in Fulton County, Georgia, as judge rules absentee ballots can be unsealed |first1=Sara |last1=Murray |first2=Jason |last2=Morris |first3=Dianne |last3=Gallagher |first4=Fredreka |last4=Schouten |website=[[CNN]] |access-date=November 21, 2021 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |access-date=June 14, 2022 |url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/06/25/politics/fulton-county-ballots-lawsuit/index.html |date=June 25, 2021 |title=Georgia judge dismisses most of lawsuit seeking inspection of Fulton County ballots |first=Jason |last=Morris |website=[[CNN]] }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/10/13/politics/judge-dismisses-ballot-review-case-georgia/index.html |access-date=November 21, 2021 |date=October 13, 2021 |title=Judge dismisses Fulton County ballot review case in Georgia |first1=Sara |last1=Murray |first2=Rachel |last2=Janfaza |website=[[CNN]] }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |first=Jeff |last=Amy |url=https://apnews.com/article/lawsuits-donald-trump-georgia-presidential-elections-elections-5b520fef3ba06833fe8b216952f74a87 |title=Georgia's Perdue sues over 2020 election, pushes fraud claim|date=December 10, 2021|website=[[Associated Press]] |access-date=June 13, 2022 }}</ref>

Trump had claimed that about 5,000 dead people had voted in Georgia, but an examination by the State Election Board released in December 2021 found that four absentee ballots of dead people had been mailed in by relatives.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Niesse |first1=Mark |title=Alleged 'dead' Georgia voters found alive and well after 2020 election |url=https://www.ajc.com/politics/alleged-dead-georgia-voters-found-alive-and-well-after-2020-election/DAL3VY7NFNHL5OREMHD7QECOCA/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220610171807/https://www.ajc.com/politics/alleged-dead-georgia-voters-found-alive-and-well-after-2020-election/DAL3VY7NFNHL5OREMHD7QECOCA/ |archive-date=June 10, 2022 |url-status=live |work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution |date=December 27, 2021 |access-date=June 14, 2022 }}</ref>

====Idaho====
In September 2021, [[Bonner County, Idaho]] announced it would perform a recount of ballots cast in the election, in response to an allegation by election conspiracy theorist [[Mike Lindell]] that all 44 Idaho counties had been digitally hacked. Lindell provided a detailed list of IP addresses he asserted had been compromised. County Clerk Mike Rosedale stated that all county voting machines were fully [[Air gap (networking)|airgapped]] from the Internet, also noting that seven Idaho counties don't use voting machines. Lindell alleged that a specific formula had been applied by hackers to flip votes from Trump to Biden. Rosedale said Lindell had not contacted his office before presenting his allegations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.krem.com/article/news/local/mypillow-founder-allegations-bonner-county-presidential-vote-recount/293-22e7d328-6ed2-4843-a30c-7b3e3eeb5b32|title=Allegations made by MyPillow founder spur Bonner County vote recount|website=krem.com|date=September 30, 2021|first=Annisa|last=Keith|access-date=October 8, 2021}}</ref> The Bonner audit, and audits of two other counties that don't use voting machines, affirmed the accuracy of the ballot count. Chief Deputy Secretary of State Chad Houck said Lindell would be sent a bill for the audits.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/state-watch/575933-idaho-gop-official-says-he-is-sending-mike-lindell-bill-for-election |access-date=November 21, 2021 |title=Idaho GOP official says he is sending Mike Lindell bill for election audit|first=Lexi|last=Lonas|date=October 8, 2021|website=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Norimine |first1=Hayat |title=Idaho wants MyPillow CEO to pay for costs to refute his false election fraud claim |url=https://www.idahostatesman.com/news/politics-government/state-politics/article254838702.html |work=Idaho Statesman |date=October 7, 2021}}</ref>{{Importance inline|reason=Needs more notable sources or discussion of its impact and significance to keep from moving to another article|date=February 2024}}

====Pennsylvania====
{{Main|2020 United States presidential election in Pennsylvania#Official audits and recounts}}
The Republican Commissioners agreed to a ballot audit in Fulton County, PA due to a subpoena threat from State Senator [[Doug Mastriano#Efforts to overturn 2020 presidential election results and positive COVID-19 diagnosis|Doug Mastriano]].<ref name="Helderman">{{cite news |last1=Helderman |first1=Rosalind S. |title='It was like This Rogue Thing': How the Push by Trump Allies to Undermine the 2020 Results Through Ballot Reviews Started Quietly in Pennsylvania |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/pennsylvania-2020-ballot-audits/2021/06/06/4e456952-bfe0-11eb-b26e-53663e6be6ff_story.html |access-date=14 September 2023 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=6 June 2021}}</ref><ref name="Unprecedented">{{cite news |last1=Parish |first1=Marley |date=31 October 2021 |title='An unprecedented situation': Loose ends remain in Fulton County election review |url=https://www.penncapital-star.com/government-politics/an-unprecedented-situation-loose-ends-remain-in-fulton-county-election-review/ |access-date=6 October 2023 |work=Pennsylvania Capital-Star}}</ref> Fulton County's audit was funded by Defending The Republic an organization founded by Trump's lawyer [[Sidney Powell]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Duda |first1=Jeremy |title=Group led by 'kraken' lawyer Sidney Powell hired the firm recounting AZ's election to probe a PA election |url=https://www.azmirror.com/2021/05/24/group-led-by-kraken-lawyer-sidney-powell-hired-the-firm-recounting-azs-election-to-probe-a-pa-election/ |access-date=6 October 2023 |work=Arizona Mirror |date=24 May 2021}}</ref> Defying a directive from the State's Board of Elections, the County allowed Wake Technology Services, Inc. to access voting machines. The company had originally performed the hand recount in [[2021 Maricopa County presidential ballot audit|Maricopa County's ballot audit]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Duda |first1=Jeremy |title=Wake Technology Services Audited a Pennsylvania Election as Part of the #StopTheSteal Movement |url=https://www.azmirror.com/2021/05/21/wake-technology-services-audited-a-pennsylvania-election-as-part-of-the-stopthesteal-movement/ |access-date=14 September 2023 |work=Arizona Mirror |date=21 May 2021 |ref=Wake TSI}}</ref> The original draft of its audit report concluded that Fulton's "election was well run [and] followed all Commonwealth and Federal guidelines."<ref name="Helderman" /> At a state Senate hearing, the Republican chairman of Fulton County's Board of Commissioners testified that his county's audit found nothing wrong.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mimms |first1=Sarah |title=Pennsylvania Republicans' Attempts At A 2020 Election "Audit" Are Off To An Awkward Start |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/sarahmimms/pennsylvania-2020-election-audit-hearing |access-date=6 October 2023 |work=[[BuzzFeed News]] |date=9 September 2021}}</ref>

By August 2021, Pennsylvania Republican lawmakers were preparing to hold formal hearings on the election and conduct a "full forensic investigation". Prior to the investigation, [[President pro tempore of the Pennsylvania Senate|Senate President pro tempore]] [[Jake Corman]] made a statement asserting that the investigation is not meant to overturn the results of Pennsylvania's election and that the legislature does not have the authority to do so.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pittsburgh.cbslocal.com/2021/08/25/jake-corman-renews-investigation-of-2020-election-pennsylvania-donald-trump-joe-biden/ |access-date=November 21, 2021 |work=[[KDKA-TV|CBS Pittsburgh]] |first=Jon |last=Delano |title=State Senate President Jake Corman Renews Investigation Of 2020 Election, But Claims Trump Is Not Directing The Show|date=August 25, 2021}}</ref> The next month, Republicans approved subpoenas for a wide range of personal information on millions of voters who cast votes in the May primary and November general election. Republicans intended to hire private firms to manage the data.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Viebeck |first1=Elise |title=In latest bow to Trump, GOP lawmakers in Pennsylvania plan to launch hearings on 2020 vote |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/pennsylvania-election-review-trump/2021/08/24/e2515ee0-04ef-11ec-8c3f-3526f81b233b_story.html |access-date=June 14, 2022 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=August 24, 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Pennsylvania GOP lawmakers approve wide-ranging subpoenas for personal information of 2020 voters |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2021/09/15/pennsylvania-gop-election-probe-subpoena-trump/ |access-date=June 14, 2022 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=September 15, 2021 |first1=Elise |last1=Viebeck |first2=Rosalind S. |last2=Helderman |author-link2=Rosalind S. Helderman }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.inquirer.com/politics/pennsylvania/pennsylvania-election-audit-2021-updates-results-20210922.html |access-date=June 14, 2022 |title=What to know about Pennsylvania Republicans' investigation of the 2020 election |first1=Andrew |last1=Seidman |first2=Jonathan |last2=Lai |work=The Philadelphia Inquirer|date=September 29, 2021}}</ref> On September 23, 2021, [[Pennsylvania Attorney General]] [[Josh Shapiro]] filed a lawsuit seeking to block the subpoenas from being issued.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://apnews.com/article/donald-trump-pennsylvania-lawsuits-presidential-elections-state-elections-30f7077c5607906c932c7ab98235d3ba |work=[[Associated Press]] |date=September 23, 2021 |title=Pennsylvania prosecutor sues to block GOP election subpoena |access-date=June 13, 2022 |first=Marc |last=Levy }}</ref> On October 7, 2021, Corman said that he accepted the results of the election but also reaffirmed his support for the investigation.<ref>{{Cite news |first1=Kevin |last1=Gavin |first2=Marylee |last2=Williams |first3=Laura |last3=Tsutsui |first4=Rebecca |last4=Reese |url=https://www.wesa.fm/show/the-confluence/2021-10-07/senator-jake-corman-says-he-accepts-november-election-results-but-wants-audit-for-oversight-of-department-of-state |date=October 7, 2021 |title=Senator Jake Corman says he accepts November election results, but wants audit for oversight of Department of State |website=[[WESA (FM)|WESA]] |access-date=November 21, 2021 }}</ref>{{Update inline|date=February 2024}}

====Texas====
The Texas attorney general's office, led by ardent Trump ally [[Ken Paxton]], spent more than 22,000 staff hours investigating potential voting fraud in 2020. The investigation identified and prosecuted sixteen cases of false addresses on voter registration forms, among nearly 17 million registered voters in the state. This was half as many cases as two years earlier. A 2021 investigation found only three prosecutable cases among all elections in the state.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Goldenstein |first1=Taylor |title=Ken Paxton's beefed-up 2020 voter fraud unit closed 16 minor cases, all in Harris County |url=https://www.houstonchronicle.com/politics/texas/article/Ken-Paxton-s-beefed-up-2020-voter-fraud-unit-15820210.php |access-date=January 17, 2023 |work=Houston Chronicle |date=December 21, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Goldstein |first1=Taylor |title=Texas AG Paxton's $2.2M voter fraud unit closed three cases in 2021. GOP lawmakers still boosted its budget. |url=https://www.houstonchronicle.com/politics/texas/article/Texas-AG-Paxton-s-2-2M-voter-fraud-unit-closed-16708051.php |work=Houston Chronicle |date=December 17, 2021 |access-date=June 14, 2022 }}</ref>

In September 2021, hours after Trump wrote to Texas governor [[Greg Abbott]] demanding an audit of the state's election results, the [[Secretary of State of Texas|Texas secretary of state's office]] announced that audits had begun in four major counties. County officials and others in the secretary of state's office initially said they were unaware of any audit underway.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/09/24/politics/texas-audit-county-officials/index.html |date=September 25, 2021 |title=County officials in Texas say they are in the dark following 'audit' announcement |first=Sara |last=Murray |access-date=November 21, 2021 |website=[[CNN]] }}</ref>

The audits were conducted by secretary of state [[John B. Scott (Texas politician)|John Scott]], whom Abbott appointed in October 2021. Scott is a former state litigator who briefly joined Trump's legal team in 2020 to challenge the election results. He released preliminary findings of the audits in December 2021 that found few issues, including 17 votes cast by deceased voters and 60 cross-state duplicate votes among 3.9 million ballots cast. The duplicate votes remained under investigation.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Heinz |first1=Frank |title=Preliminary Findings of 2020 Election Audit Finds Little Trouble in Big Texas Counties |url=https://www.nbcdfw.com/news/local/texas-news/preliminary-findings-of-2020-election-audit-finds-little-trouble-in-big-texas-counties/2849506/ |work=[[KXAS-TV]] |date=December 31, 2021 |access-date=June 14, 2022 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Weber |first1=Paul J. |title=Gov. Abbott Appoints New Secretary of State; Elections Chief Joined Trump's Challenge in 2020 |url=https://www.nbcdfw.com/news/local/texas-news/gov-abbott-appoints-new-secretary-of-state-new-elections-chief-joined-trumps-challenge-in-2020/2779705/ |work=[[KXAS-TV]] |date=October 21, 2021 |access-date=June 14, 2022 }}</ref>{{Update inline|date=February 2024}}

====Wisconsin====
{{Main|2020 United States presidential election in Wisconsin#Aftermath}}
By May 2021, state election officials had identified 27 potential cases of voting fraud among 3.3 million ballots cast. Sixteen of those cases involved people using a [[UPS Store]] rather than their residence for their mailing address.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bauer |first1=Scott |title=27 possible voter fraud cases in 3 million Wisconsin ballots |url=https://apnews.com/article/donald-trump-wisconsin-election-2020-government-and-politics-daa3ac227c936d7fc038996af6e27cbe |work=[[Associated Press]] |access-date=June 13, 2022 |date=May 21, 2021}}</ref>

Trump and his allies filed multiple lawsuits challenging Wisconsin election results but lost all of them, including a series of decisions by the state Supreme Court. State Republicans initiated multiple types of investigations beginning in February 2021. That month, the Republican majority legislature voted to direct the nonpartisan Legislative Audit Bureau to conduct an examination of some election procedures.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jsonline.com/story/news/politics/2021/02/11/wisconsin-republicans-order-audit-2020-elections/6722833002/ |access-date=November 21, 2021 |title=Republican lawmakers order an audit of Wisconsin's elections|first=Patrick|last=Marley|work=Milwaukee Journal Sentinel|date=February 11, 2021}}</ref>

In May 2021, [[Robin Vos]], the Republican [[Speaker of the Wisconsin State Assembly|speaker]] of the [[Wisconsin State Assembly|Wisconsin state assembly]], hired three retired police officers and an attorney to examine reported tips of potential election irregularities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jsonline.com/story/news/politics/elections/2021/05/26/wisconsin-republican-robin-vos-hires-ex-cops-investigate-election/7455034002/ |access-date=November 21, 2021 |title=Top Wisconsin Republican Robin Vos hires former cops to investigate November election|first=Patrick|last=Marley|work=Milwaukee Journal Sentinel|date=May 26, 2021}}</ref>

[[Janel Brandtjen]], who chairs the Assembly elections committee, opened a "forensic audit" modeled after the [[2021 Maricopa County presidential ballot audit|Maricopa County, Arizona audit]]. She had traveled to Arizona to review that audit. Brandtjen issued subpoenas to two major counties for ballots and voting machines, but they were rejected because Vos had not signed them, as required by law. Vos indicated he did not intend to sign the subpoenas, which requested information that doesn't exist or doesn't apply to Wisconsin elections. Milwaukee County Clerk George Christenson asserted the subpoena he received was "clearly a cut and paste job" from similar election-related legal moves by Republicans in other states.<ref name="auto9">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wpr.org/whats-status-gop-backed-election-investigations-wisconsin |access-date=November 21, 2021 |title=What's The Status Of GOP-Backed Election Investigations In Wisconsin?|first=Laurel|last=White|date=September 22, 2021|website=Wisconsin Public Radio}}</ref>

In June 2021, Vos selected Republican former Wisconsin Supreme Court justice [[Michael Gableman]] to conduct an investigation of the election.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jsonline.com/story/news/politics/elections/2021/06/26/former-wisconsin-supreme-court-justice-michael-gableman-will-oversee-robin-vos-2020-election-review/5357319001/|title=A former Wisconsin Supreme Court justice will oversee the latest election review sought by the state's GOP leaders|first=Molly|last=Beck|work=Milwaukee Journal Sentinel|date=June 26, 2021}}</ref> Gableman had been considered for a position in the Trump administration in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jsonline.com/story/news/2017/09/13/wisconsin-supreme-court-justice-michael-gableman-being-vetted-trump-job/662233001/|title=Wisconsin Supreme Court Justice Michael Gableman being vetted for Trump job|first=Patrick|last=Marley|work=Milwaukee Journal Sentinel|date=September 13, 2017}}</ref> Soon after the election, Gableman had voiced conspiracy theories about the outcome and had attended an August conference hosted by election conspiracy theorist [[Mike Lindell]]. He also consulted [[Shiva Ayyadurai]], a conspiracy theorist whose work on the Arizona audit was discredited. Gableman issued subpoenas, later withdrawn, some of which contained errors and requested information that was already public. He later stated, "Most people, myself included, do not have a comprehensive understanding or even any understanding of how elections work". Gableman sent emails to election officials across the state asking them to retain information, but they came from a [[Gmail]] account associated with a different name and in some cases were blocked as a security concern or spam. Gableman compared a newspaper's coverage of his investigation to [[Propaganda in Nazi Germany|Nazi propaganda]]. In October, the office of Wisconsin attorney general [[Josh Kaul]] sent Gableman a nine-page letter characterizing the investigation as unlawful and called for it to be closed.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Elise |first1=Viebeck |title=Calls intensify to end Wisconsin's election review amid blunders by ex-judge in charge |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2021/10/14/wisconsin-election-review-gableman-errors/ |access-date=November 21, 2021 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=October 14, 2021}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/10/18/politics/wisconsin-republican-2020-election-review/index.html|title=Calls to end Wisconsin Republicans' review of 2020 election grow amid investigator's blunders |first=Eric |last=Bradner |website=[[CNN]] |date=October 18, 2021 }}</ref><ref name="auto9"/>

On October 22, 2021, the nonpartisan Legislative Audit Bureau released their findings of an audit ordered by Republicans in February 2021. The findings reported that there was no evidence of widespread voter fraud, and that [[Wisconsin Senate|State Senator]] [[Robert Cowles]] said that the election was "safe and secure". State Senator [[Kathy Bernier]] said that the audit found no evidence of any "attempt at vote fraud".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/wireStory/wisconsin-audit-finds-elections-safe-secure-80729558 |first=Scott |last=Bauer |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=October 23, 2021 |access-date=November 21, 2021 |title=Wisconsin audit finds elections are 'safe and secure'|website=[[ABC News (United States)|ABC News]] }}</ref>

A ten-month review by the conservative [[Wisconsin Institute for Law and Liberty]] found in December 2021 that certain election procedures weren't adequately followed, but there was "little direct evidence of fraud, and for the most part, an analysis of the results and voting patterns does not give rise to an inference of fraud".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Blake |first1=Aaron |title=A conservative group debunks Trump's voter-fraud claims (yet again) |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2021/12/09/trumps-voter-fraud-myth-dies-another-death-conservative-group-debunks-it-again/ |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=December 9, 2021}}</ref>

Gableman's 13-month investigation found no evidence of election fraud and cost taxpayers $2 million. Vos fired Gableman and multiple parties referred him to the Office of Lawyer Regulation of the [[Wisconsin Supreme Court]] on ethics complaints.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Redman |first1=Henry |title=Third ethics complaint filed against Gableman |publisher=Wisconsin Examiner|url=https://wisconsinexaminer.com/2023/03/03/third-ethics-complaint-filed-against-gableman/ |date=March 3, 2023}}</ref>

===Mike Lindell reinstatement prediction===
{{Main|Mike Lindell#Attempts to overturn 2020 presidential election}}
On March 29, 2021, businessman and Trump supporter [[Mike Lindell]] predicted on Steve Bannon's podcast that Trump would be back in office on "August 13", the day after his three-day cyber fraud conference in [[Sioux Falls, South Dakota|Sioux Falls]], stating "it'll be the talk of the world". When President [[Joe Biden]] remained in office, Lindell moved his prediction for Trump's return to September 30, and then to the end of 2021.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/critics-mock-trump-reinstatement-day-b1902484.html |first=Craig |last=Graziosi |title=Critics mock believers in Trump's 'reinstatement day' |date=August 13, 2021 |access-date=November 21, 2021 |website=[[The Independent]] }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Harvey|first=Josephine|date=24 November 2021|title=Mike Lindell Finally Reveals His Supreme Court Complaint, And Critics Have Notes|url=https://news.yahoo.com/mike-lindell-finally-reveals-supreme-025852008.html|url-status=live|access-date=2021-11-27|website=news.yahoo.com|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211124040540/https://news.yahoo.com/mike-lindell-finally-reveals-supreme-025852008.html |archive-date=November 24, 2021 }}</ref>

[[File:Subverting Justice - How the Former President and His Allies Pressured DOJ to Overturn the 2020 Election.pdf|thumb|Senate report on Trump's efforts to overturn the election]]

=== Senate Judiciary Committee report ===
{{Main|Aftermath of the January 6 United States Capitol attack#U.S. Senate investigation}}
On October 7, 2021, the [[Senate Committee on the Judiciary]] published their report on Trump's efforts to pressure the [[United States Department of Justice|Department of Justice]] to overturn the results of the 2020 election.<ref name="Johnson2021">{{cite news |last1=Johnson |first1=Kevin |title='Subverting Justice': Senate panel details the 9 times Trump pressured DOJ to overturn election results |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2021/10/07/senate-details-donald-trumps-push-doj-overturn-2020-election/6032581001/ |date=October 7, 2021 |access-date=October 9, 2021 |work=[[USA Today]]}}</ref>

===Election law reform efforts===

The [[Electoral Count Reform and Presidential Transition Improvement Act of 2022|Electoral Count Reform and Presidential Transition Improvement Act]] was passed on December 23, 2022.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Parks |first=Miles |date=December 23, 2022 |title=Congress passes election reform designed to ward off another Jan. 6 |url=https://www.npr.org/2022/12/22/1139951463/electoral-count-act-reform-passes |work=[[NPR]]}}</ref>  The Enhanced Election Security and Protection Act was also proposed in July 2022<ref>{{cite news |date=20 July 2022 |title=Senators announce deal on electoral college reforms in wake of January 6 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/live/2022/jul/20/biden-climate-crisis-emergency-us-politics-latest-live?page=with:block-62d843688f0883b6bb6b1002#block-62d843688f0883b6bb6b1002 |access-date=January 4, 2023 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> but was not passed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/117th-congress/senate-bill/4574|title=S.4574 - 117th Congress (2021-2022): Enhanced Election Security and Protection Act &#124|website=Congress.gov|date=July 20, 2022 |publisher=Library of Congress|access-date=October 14, 2024}}</ref>

=== Post-election voter restriction efforts by Republicans ===
{{#invoke:Excerpt|main|Republican efforts to restrict voting following the 2020 presidential election|only=paragraph|paragraph=1}}

=== Impact on secretaries of state ===
In multiple U.S. states, officials who work for the secretary of state received threats following the election and were still receiving threats as of October 2021. Law enforcement generally was not prepared to provide ongoing security for these officials, as their positions had never before been considered high-risk.<ref>{{Cite web|last1=Dovere|first1=Isaac|last2=Herb|first2=Jeremy|date=October 26, 2021|title='It's absolutely getting worse': Secretaries of state targeted by Trump election lies live in fear for their safety and are desperate for protection|url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/10/26/politics/secretaries-of-state-personal-threats-trump-election-lies/index.html|url-status=live|access-date=October 26, 2021|website=[[CNN]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211026220755/https://www.cnn.com/2021/10/26/politics/secretaries-of-state-personal-threats-trump-election-lies/index.html |archive-date=October 26, 2021 }}</ref>

=== House Select Committee on the January 6 Attack ===
{{Main|United States House Select Committee on the January 6 Attack}}
In July 2021, the House Select Committee on the January 6 Attack was formed, largely along party lines.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Freking |first=Kevin |date=2021-07-02 |title=A look at 8 lawmakers appointed to probe Jan. 6 attack |url=https://apnews.com/article/capitol-siege-government-and-politics-268a3d4fed79bec580beed75b7925e6e |url-status=live |access-date=2021-12-20 |website=[[Associated Press]] |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210702053820/https://apnews.com/article/capitol-siege-government-and-politics-268a3d4fed79bec580beed75b7925e6e |archive-date=July 2, 2021 }}</ref>

At the first public hearing on June 9, 2022, the committee said that Trump had engaged in a [[United States House Select Committee on the January 6 Attack public hearings#7PartPlan|seven-part conspiracy]] to overturn a [[Free and fair election|free and fair]] democratic election,<ref name="NYT-20220609lb">{{cite news |last=Broadwater |first=Luke |title='Trump Was at the Center': Jan. 6 Hearing Lays Out Case in Vivid Detail |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2022/06/09/us/politics/trump-jan-6-hearings.html |date=June 9, 2022 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=June 10, 2022 }}</ref><ref name="NYT-20220609pb">{{cite news |last=Baker |first=Peter |title=Trump Is Depicted as a Would-Be Autocrat Seeking to Hang Onto Power at All Costs – As the Jan. 6 committee outlined during its prime-time hearing, Donald J. Trump executed a seven-part conspiracy to overturn a free and fair democratic election. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2022/06/09/us/politics/trump-jan-6-hearing.html |date=June 9, 2022 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=June 10, 2022 }}</ref> and they discussed it in the hearings that followed. According to Bennie Thompson, chair of the committee: "Jan. 6 was the culmination of an attempted coup, a brazen attempt, as one rioter put it shortly after Jan. 6, to overthrow the government ... The violence was no accident. It represents Trump's last stand, most desperate chance to halt the transfer of power." Trump, according to the committee, "lied to the American people, ignored all evidence refuting his false fraud claims, pressured state and federal officials to throw out election results favoring his challenger, encouraged a violent mob to storm the Capitol and even signaled support for the execution of his own vice president".<ref name="NYT-20220609lb" /><ref name="NYT-20220609pb" /> On October 21, 2022, the committee subpoenaed Trump's testimony and relevant records.<ref name="TrumpSubpoena">{{Cite web |date=October 21, 2022 |title=Bennie G. Thompson and Liz Cheney to President Donald J. Trump |url=https://january6th.house.gov/sites/democrats.january6th.house.gov/files/20221021%20J6%20Cmte%20Subpeona%20to%20Donald%20Trump.pdf |access-date=October 21, 2022 |website=january6th.house.gov}}</ref> He sued the committee and never testified.<ref name="january6th.house.gov">{{Cite web |last1=Thompson |first1=Bennie |last2=Cheney |first2=Liz |date=2022-11-14 |title=Thompson & Cheney Statement on Donald Trump's Defiance of Select Committee Subpoena |url=https://january6th.house.gov/news/press-releases/thompson-cheney-statement-donald-trump-s-defiance-select-committee-subpoena |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221115005338/https://january6th.house.gov/news/press-releases/thompson-cheney-statement-donald-trump-s-defiance-select-committee-subpoena |archive-date=2022-11-15 |access-date=2022-11-15 |website=Select Committee to Investigate the January 6th Attack on the United States Capitol (january6th.house.gov) |language=en}}</ref><ref name="TrumpSues2022Nov11">[https://www.documentcloud.org/documents/23302179-trumpvselectcttecomp111122 Complaint for Declaratory and Injunctive Relief], Trump v. Select Committee et al. (S.D. Fla., November 11, 2022) (No. 9:22-cv-81758).</ref> On December 19, 2022, the committee criminally referred him to the Justice Department,<ref name="ReferenceA"/> though the [[United States Justice Department investigation into attempts to overturn the 2020 presidential election|Justice Department was already investigating]].

=== 2021 German federal election ===
During the [[2021 German federal election]], the [[Center for Monitoring, Analysis and Strategy]] (CeMAS) found that false claims of voter fraud had become commonplace on [[Telegram (software)|Telegram]] in Germany, with accusations against [[Dominion Voting Systems]] being common despite the company's technology not being used in German elections.{{efn|Since March 2009, all [[elections in Germany]] have been conducted exclusively with paper ballots which are tabulated by hand.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bmi.bund.de/EN/topics/constitution/electoral-law/bundestag-elections/bundestag-elections-node.html |title=How Bundestag elections work |work=[[Federal Ministry of the Interior and Community]] |access-date=January 17, 2023 }}</ref>}} CeMAS researcher Miro Dittrich said, "We have seen far-right actors try to claim election fraud since at least 2016, but it didn't take off. When Trump started telling the '[[Big lie#Donald Trump's false claims of a stolen election|big lie]],' it became a big issue in Germany, sometimes bigger than the pandemic, because [[German far-right|far-right groups]] and the [[Alternative for Germany|AfD]] are carefully monitoring the success Trump is having with this narrative."<ref>{{Cite news |last=Stanley-Becker |first=Isaac |date=September 25, 2021 |title=Election fraud, QAnon, Jan. 6: Far-right extremists in Germany read from a pro-Trump script |language=en-US |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2021/09/25/german-election-far-right-trump/ |access-date=2022-11-23 |issn=0190-8286}}</ref>

=== Justice Department investigations ===
{{Main|United States Justice Department investigation into attempts to overturn the 2020 presidential election}}

By March 2022, Justice Department investigations of participants in the Capitol attack had expanded to include activities of Trump's inner circle leading up to the attack. A federal grand jury was empaneled.<ref>{{cite news |title=Justice Dept. Widens Jan. 6 Inquiry to Range of Pro-Trump Figures |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2022/03/30/us/politics/justice-dept-widens-jan-6-inquiry.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=March 30, 2022 |first1=Alan |last1=Feuer |first2=Katie |last2=Benner |first3=Maggie |last3=Haberman |author-link3=Maggie Haberman }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Justice Dept. Investigation of Jan. 6 Confronts Sprawling Cast of Characters |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2022/04/05/us/politics/trump-allies-january-6.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=April 5, 2022 |first1=Alan |last1=Feuer |first2=Luke |last2=Broadwater |first3=Maggie |last3=Haberman |author-link3=Maggie Haberman |access-date=January 17, 2023 }}</ref> Later in 2022, a [[Smith special counsel investigation|special counsel]] was appointed.<ref name="2022Nov18SpecialCounsel">{{Cite web |last1=Tucker |first1=Eric |last2=Balsamo |first2=Michael |date=2022-11-18 |title=Garland Names Special Counsel To Lead Trump-Related Probes |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/trump-justice-department-merrick-garland-special-counsel_n_6377d286e4b0e771d953dcb6 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221118185227/https://www.huffpost.com/entry/trump-justice-department-merrick-garland-special-counsel_n_6377d286e4b0e771d953dcb6 |archive-date=2022-11-18 |access-date=2022-11-18 |website=HuffPost |language=en}}</ref>

On August 1, 2023, [[Federal prosecution of Donald Trump (election obstruction case)|Trump was indicted]]. The indictment described six alleged co-conspirators.<ref name="cnnaug1">{{Cite news |last1=Sneed |first1=Tierney |last2=Lybrand |first2=Holmes |last3=Cohen |first3=Marshall |last4=Cohen |first4=Zachary |last5=Cole |first5=Devan |last6=Rabinowitz |first6=Hannah |last7=Polantz |first7=Katelyn |date=August 1, 2023 |title=Donald Trump has been indicted in special counsel's 2020 election interference probe |url=https://www.cnn.com/2023/08/01/politics/donald-trump-indictment-grand-jury-2020-election/index.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230801220818/https://www.cnn.com/2023/08/01/politics/donald-trump-indictment-grand-jury-2020-election/index.html |archive-date=August 1, 2023 |access-date=August 1, 2023 |publisher=CNN |language=en}}</ref> However, following Trump's election to the presidency in November 2024, the case was dismissed at the request of special counsel [[Jack Smith (lawyer)|Jack Smith]], who cited the DOJ's policy of not prosecuting sitting Presidents.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Brooke Singman |first=Andrea Margolis |date=2024-11-25 |title=Judge grants Jack Smith's request to dismiss Jan. 6 charges, appeal in classified records case against Trump |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/judge-grants-jack-smiths-request-dismiss-jan-6-charges-appeal-classified-records-case-against-trump |access-date=2024-11-25 |website=Fox News |language=en-US}}</ref> In January 2025, Smith resigned, and the special counsel released its report, saying that "the admissible evidence was sufficient to obtain and sustain a conviction at trial."<ref name="report-release">{{Cite web |date=January 14, 2025 |title=Justice Dept. releases Trump special counsel report on Jan. 6 case |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/2025/01/13/trump-jan-6-classified-documents-investigations-report-jack-smith/ |access-date=January 14, 2025 |newspaper=The Washington Post}}</ref> With Trump in office again, the Office of Special Counsel announced on August 1, 2025 that it had opened an investigation into Smith, alleging that his investigations into Trump's actions had been politically motivated.<ref>{{Cite web |last=O'Connor |first=Lydia |date=August 1, 2025 |title=Special Counsel Office Investigating Jack Smith: Report |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/donald-trump-live-updates_n_688d0894e4b022c2fdde8724/liveblog_688d4685e4b00b7bc191d4f6 |access-date=August 1, 2025 |website=HuffPost |language=en}}</ref>

=== Civil lawsuits ===
{{Main|Trump fake electors plot#Wisconsin}}
In May 2022, a civil lawsuit was filed in Dane County, Wisconsin, against the ten Trump supporters who had presented themselves as alternate electors for that state.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Date |first=S.V. |date=17 May 2022 |title=Fake Wisconsin Trump Electors, Already Under DOJ Investigation, Now Face Civil Suit, Too |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/wisconsin-trump-fake-electors-lawsuit_n_6282c518e4b050d951957ae3 |access-date=17 May 2022 |website=[[HuffPost]]|language=en}}</ref>

===Continuing subversion efforts and 2024 predictions===
[[File:20240524 Trump groundwork for election denial.svg|thumb|To sow election doubt, Trump has escalated use of "rigged election" and "election interference" statements in advance of the 2024 election compared to the previous two elections—the statements described as part of a "heads I win; tails you cheated" rhetorical strategy.<ref name=NYTimes_20240524 />]]

As of 2025, Trump has publicly continued to insist that the 2020 election was rigged and stolen, while still providing no evidence.<ref name=":7">{{Cite web |last=Welch |first=David |date=2022-04-02 |title=Trump Rallies in Michigan to Put His Stamp on Republican Primary |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2022-04-03/trump-rallies-in-michigan-to-put-his-stamp-on-republican-primary |access-date=2022-04-02 |website=[[Bloomberg News|Bloomberg]]|language=en-US}}</ref>{{Obsolete source|reason=Source cited is three years older than the year stated in the text.|date=February 2025}} It has been reported that Trump had admitted his loss to a group of historians in {{nowrap|mid-2021}}, saying, "We had a deal all set, and then when the election was rigged and lost, what happened is that the deal went away".<ref name=":9" />

On September 27, 2021, American legal scholar [[Laurence Tribe]] and colleagues described the legal background of the attempt to overturn the 2020 election, and named possible ways of averting the use of such a strategy in the future.<ref name="BG-20120927">{{cite news |last1=Tribe |first1=Laurence H. |last2=Buchanan |first2=Neil H. |last3=Dorf |first3=Michael C. |date=September 27, 2021 |title=How to prevent the legal strategy that nearly undid the last election from ending democracy - Congress needs to act and the executive branch needs to step up. |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2021/09/27/opinion/how-prevent-legal-strategy-that-nearly-undid-last-election-ending-democracy/ |access-date=October 1, 2021 |newspaper=[[The Boston Globe]]}}</ref> On December 23, 2021, Tribe and colleagues wrote that Attorney General [[Merrick Garland]] ought to be "holding the leaders of the Jan. 6 insurrection{{snd}}all of them{{snd}}to account" to "teach the next generation that no one is above the law".<ref name="NYT-20211223">{{cite news |last1=Tribe |first1=Laurence H. |last2=Ayer |first2=Donald |last3=Aftergut |first3=Dennis |date=December 23, 2021 |title=Will Donald Trump Get Away With Inciting an Insurrection |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/12/23/opinion/trump-capitol-riot-january-6th.html |url-access=limited |url-status=live |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20211228/https://www.nytimes.com/2021/12/23/opinion/trump-capitol-riot-january-6th.html |archive-date=2021-12-28 |access-date=December 23, 2021 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]]}}{{cbignore}}</ref>

[[Joshua Keating]] warned that the playbook used up until this point to challenges the legitimacy of election results could result in a 'coup trap,' where countries suffering a coup attempt are more likely to see another.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Keating |first=Joshua |author-link=Joshua Keating |date=November 13, 2020 |title=Whatever Trump Is Doing, It Isn't a "Coup": But the long-term effect could be similarly damaging. |url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2020/11/trump-coup-detat-autogolpe.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201217225614/https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2020/11/trump-coup-detat-autogolpe.html |archive-date=December 17, 2020 |access-date=November 21, 2021 |website=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Harkness |first=Kristen A. |date=June 1, 2016 |title=The Ethnic Army and the State: Explaining Coup Traps and the Difficulties of Democratization in Africa |url=https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/10.1177/0022002714545332 |journal=Journal of Conflict Resolution |volume=60 |issue=4 |pages=587–616 |doi=10.1177/0022002714545332 |issn=0022-0027 |s2cid=54538341 |hdl-access=free |hdl=10023/9391}}</ref> On December 17, 2021, ''The Washington Post'' published an opinion piece by three retired generals on the need to be prepared for a possible insurrection in 2024.<ref name="WP-20211217">{{cite news |last1=Eaton |first1=Paul D. |last2=Taguba |first2=Antonio M. |last3=Anderson |first3=Steven M. |date=December 17, 2021 |title=Opinion: 3 retired generals: The military must prepare now for a 2024 insurrection |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2021/12/17/eaton-taguba-anderson-generals-military/ |access-date=December 18, 2021 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]}}</ref>

''The New York Times'' reported later in April 2022 that Trump supporters were continuing to seek ways to overturn the election. John Eastman, state and federal legislators, and right-wing news outlets continued to press for state legislatures to rescind electoral votes for Biden, and to bring new lawsuits asserting large-scale voting fraud. The ''Times'' reported that Trump was privately insisting he could be returned to power as he also continued to consider another run for the presidency in 2024. Legal experts expressed concerns that efforts were being made to undermine public confidence in democracy to lay the groundwork for baselessly challenging future elections. Former federal appeals court judge [[J. Michael Luttig]], a prominent conservative attorney for whom Eastman clerked, remarked:<blockquote>At the moment, there is no other way to say it: This is the clearest and most present danger to our democracy. Trump and his supporters in Congress and in the states are preparing now to lay the groundwork to overturn the election in 2024 were Trump, or his designee, to lose the vote for the presidency.<ref name=":10" /><ref>{{cite news |title=John Eastman reportedly pressures Wisconsin legislature to decertify 2020 election |url=https://thehill.com/news/3265620-john-eastman-pressures-wisconsin-legislature-to-decertify-2020-election/ |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |date=April 12, 2022 |first1=Kelsey |last1=Carolan |first2=Rebecca |last2=Beitsch |access-date=June 13, 2022 }}</ref></blockquote>

On May 1, 2022, investigations by the House Select Committee into fundraising efforts by the Republican National Committee, based on their promotion of Trump's "[[Big lie#Donald Trump's false claims of a stolen election|big lie]]", have been supported by a federal judge.<ref name="WP-20220502">{{cite news |last=Hsu |first=Spencer S. |title=Judge rejects RNC bid to block email, fundraising data from Jan. 6 panel – House probes whether Trump, RNC profited from and stoked violence through false, inflammatory claims of election fraud |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/dc-md-va/2022/05/02/rnc-jan6-salesforce-fundraising-lawsuit/ |date=May 2, 2022 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=May 2, 2022 }}</ref>

On May 22, 2022, ''The New York Times'' presented a detailed analysis of the continuing efforts by Trump and his allies to further promote "the big lie" and related lies in their attempts to overturn and influence future elections, including those in 2022 and 2024.<ref name="NYT-20220522">{{cite news |last1=Corasaniti |first1=Nick |last2=Yourish |first2=Karen |last3=Collins |first3=Keith |title=How Trump's 2020 Election Lies – Have Gripped State Legislatures |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2022/05/22/us/politics/state-legislators-election-denial.html |date=May 22, 2022 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=May 22, 2022 }}</ref><ref name="NBC-20220522">{{cite news |last=Edelman |first=Adam |title=Election deniers who say Trump won in 2020 are running to be top cop in 4 battleground states – At least 15 people who push false claims about the 2020 results are running for attorney general in 14 states, including four swing states, according to a group tracking the races. |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2022-election/election-deniers-say-trump-won-2020-are-running-top-cop-4-battleground-rcna29705 |date=May 22, 2022 |work=[[NBC News]] |access-date=May 22, 2022 }}</ref>

In June 2022, the Republican Party in Texas adopted a statement that the election was illegitimate into its official party platform.<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Paybarah |first1=Azi |last2=Montgomery |first2=David |date=June 19, 2022 |title=Texas Republicans Approve Far-Right Platform Declaring Biden's Election Illegitimate |work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2022/06/19/us/politics/texas-republicans-approve-far-right-platform-declaring-bidens-election-illegitimate.html |access-date=2022-06-20}}</ref>

On July 9, 2022, after the Wisconsin Supreme Court ruling that ballot dropboxes must be placed inside election clerks' offices in the future, Trump called Wisconsin House Speaker Robin Vos and complained about dropboxes in the 2020 election. Vos said he told Trump that such an attempt to overturn the 2020 election was unconstitutional. Trump posted to [[Truth Social]]: "It's now up to Robin Vos to do what everybody knows must be done".<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Gregorian |first1=Dareh |last2=Hillyard |first2=Vaughn |date=20 July 2022 |title=Wisconsin House speaker says Trump called him to overturn 2020 results – 20 months after election |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/wisconsin-house-speaker-says-trump-called-overturn-2020-results-20-mon-rcna39137 |access-date=2022-07-21 |website=[[NBC News]] |language=en}}</ref>

On August 29, 2022, Trump stated on Truth Social that he should be declared the president, or at least a new election should be held.<ref name="newelection">{{cite news |last1=Gage |first1=Brandon |title=Trump demands "new election immediately" in bizarre Truth Social rant |url=https://www.salon.com/2022/08/29/demands-new-immediately-in-bizarre-truth-social-rant-_partner/ |access-date=30 August 2022 |work=[[Salon.com]] |date=29 August 2022}}</ref>

On December 3, 2022, following the release of information by Twitter CEO [[Elon Musk]] documenting Twitter executives' discussion of previously disclosed content moderation relating to the [[Hunter Biden laptop controversy#Social media corporations|''New York Post''<nowiki/>'s story regarding Hunter Biden]], Trump made comments on Truth Social suggesting the "termination" of the [[Constitution of the United States|United States Constitution]] in order to overturn the outcome of the 2020 election.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Astor |first=Maggie |date=2022-12-04 |title=Trump's Call for 'Termination' of Constitution Draws Rebukes |language=en-US |work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2022/12/04/us/politics/trump-constitution-republicans.html |access-date=2022-12-04 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>

At 2023 campaign events, Trump predicted (without evidence) there would be voter fraud benefiting Democrats in the 2024 election.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-10-07 |title=Trump Is Lying About Another Election Being 'Stolen' From Him – The One Still A Year Away |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/trump-2024-election-lies_n_652040d0e4b09f4b8d401148 |access-date=2023-10-07 |website=[[HuffPost]]|language=en}}</ref>

===Post-election allegations of statistical improbabilities===

In the aftermath of the election, numerous claims were made and began to circulate, stating that serious anomalies could be found, suggesting an election fraud. However, a paper entitled "No Evidence For Voter Fraud: A Guide To Statistical Claims About The 2020 Election" written by Justin Grimmer, Haritz Garro and Andrew C. Eggers, was published by the conservative [[Hoover Institution]] (February 3, 2021) concluded that the statistics used to "claim some election facts would be unlikely if there had been no fraud" were either not accurate in the first place or if they were accurate, weren't really surprising.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hoover.org/research/no-evidence-voter-fraud-guide-statistical-claims-about-2020-election |date=February 3, 2021 |title=No Evidence For Voter Fraud: A Guide To Statistical Claims About The 2020 Election |first1=Justin |last1=Grimmer |first2=Haritz |last2=Garro |first3=Andrew C. |last3=Eggers |website=[[Hoover Institution]] }}</ref>

''The Washington Post'' reported in February 2023 that soon after the election the Trump campaign paid researchers from [[Berkeley Research Group]] to examine a wide range of indicators that might suggest the election had been stolen. Trump, Meadows and others were briefed on the findings in December 2020. The analysis found no significant irregularities beyond those commonly found in all elections, and nothing that might have changed the election outcome. The findings were never publicly disclosed, though the Justice Department obtained the analysis and the [[Smith special counsel investigation]] examined the matter.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dawsey |first1=Josh |title=Trump campaign paid researchers to prove 2020 fraud but kept findings secret |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2023/02/11/trump-campaign-report-electoral-fraud/ |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=February 11, 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Jack Smith, Special Counsel for Trump Inquiries, Steps Up the Pace |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2023/02/12/us/politics/jack-smith-special-counsel-trump-investigations.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=February 12, 2023|author1=Maggie Haberman|author2=Glenn Thrush|author3=Alan Feuer}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Dawsey |first1=Josh |title=Trump-commissioned report undercut his claims of dead and double voters |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/elections/2023/03/17/trump-fraud-report-2020/ |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=March 17, 2023}}</ref> The ''Post'' reported in April 2023 that the Trump campaign had hired a second firm, [[Simpatico Software Systems]], days after the election to examine fraud allegations. The company delivered a report late in 2020, finding no evidence of fraud. The [[Ken Block (politician)|company's founder]] was subpoenaed for testimony by the [[Smith special counsel investigation]] in early 2023.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dawsey |first1=Josh |title=A second firm hired by Trump campaign found no evidence of election fraud |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2023/04/27/trump-false-election-fraud-claims/ |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=April 27, 2023}}</ref>

== Reactions ==
=== Republican critiques of the "big lie" ===
{{main|Republican reactions to Donald Trump's claims of 2020 election fraud}}
{{quote box
| width = 25%|Dr. Eastman and President Trump launched a campaign to overturn a democratic election, an action unprecedented in American history. Their campaign was not confined to the ivory tower{{snd}}it was a coup in search of a legal theory... If Dr. Eastman and President Trump's plan had worked, it would have permanently ended the peaceful transition of power, undermining American democracy and the Constitution. If the country does not commit to investigating and pursuing accountability for those responsible, the Court fears January 6 will repeat itself.<br />— ''Judge [[David O. Carter]]'', [[United States district court]]<ref name="JudgeCarterOpinion">{{cite court
|litigants=Eastman v Thompson, et al. |opinion= 8:22-cv-00099-DOC-DFM Document 260 |pinpoint=44 |court=S.D. Cal. |date=May 28, 2022 |url=https://storage.courtlistener.com/recap/gov.uscourts.cacd.841840/gov.uscourts.cacd.841840.260.0.pdf |access-date=June 12, 2022 |quote=Dr. Eastman and President Trump launched a campaign to overturn a democratic election, an action unprecedented in American history. Their campaign was not confined to the ivory tower{{snd}}it was a coup in search of a legal theory. The plan spurred violent attacks on the seat of our nation's government, led to the deaths of several law enforcement officers, and deepened public distrust in our political process... If Dr. Eastman and President Trump's plan had worked, it would have permanently ended the peaceful transition of power, undermining American democracy and the Constitution. If the country does not commit to investigating and pursuing accountability for those responsible, the Court fears January 6 will
repeat itself.}}</ref><ref name="Schmidt_Broadwater_4/10/2022" />
}}

==== Administration dissenters ====
{{See also|Aftermath of the January 6 United States Capitol attack#Trump administration resignations}}
[[Hope Hicks]] told Trump to "move on". Trump replied, "Well, Hope doesn't believe in me". Hicks said, "No, I don't. Nobody's convinced me otherwise."<ref name="auto11" />

[[Kellyanne Conway]] claimed in her book that she told Trump privately to accept the loss, and he told her in response to "go back to your crazy husband".<ref name="auto11" />

[[Matthew Pottinger]], a leading aide on Trump's China policy, quickly quit in what two sources said was an act of protest against the president's response to the rioting. He was followed by at least five other senior foreign policy aides. Transportation Secretary [[Elaine Chao]], who is married to Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell, and Education Secretary [[Betsy DeVos]] also resigned in protest.<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Holland |first1=Steve |last2=Mason |first2=Jeff |last3=Spetalnick |first3=Matt |last4=Shalal |first4=Andrea |date=2021-01-14 |title=Inside Trump's final days: Aides struggle to contain an angry, isolated president |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-finale-insight-idUSKBN29J2J3 |access-date=2022-06-09 |work=[[Reuters]] |language=en}}</ref>

In June 2022, [[Ivanka Trump]] told the panel of the United States House Select Committee on the January 6 Attack that she does not believe the election was stolen and accepted William Barr's conclusion that voter fraud claims have "zero basis".<ref>{{Cite web |last=Singh |first=Maanvi |date=2022-06-10 |title=Ivanka Trump says she does not believe father's claim 2020 election was stolen |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2022/jun/09/ivanka-trump-election-not-stolen-testimony |access-date=2022-06-10 |website=[[The Guardian]] |language=en}}</ref>

==== Consistent critics ====
In 2021, [[Republican Accountability Project|The Republican Accountability Project]] estimated that 6% of national Republicans politicians consistently stood-up for democracy.<ref>{{Cite book |last1=Levitsky |first1=Steven |title=Tyranny of the minority: why American democracy reached the breaking point |last2=Ziblatt |first2=Daniel |date=2023 |publisher=Crown |isbn=978-0-593-44307-1 |edition=First |location=New York |pages=130–132}}</ref> Other prominent Republicans who spoke out against attempts to subvert the election results included Governor [[Larry Hogan]] of Maryland, former House Speaker [[Paul Ryan]], and Representative Liz Cheney of Wyoming, the third-highest-ranking Republican in the House.<ref name="CondemnSchemeUndo">{{Cite news |last1=Mascaro |first1=Lisa |last2=Jalonick |first2=Mary Clare |date=January 3, 2021 |title=Republicans condemn GOP 'scheme' to undo election for Trump |url=https://apnews.com/article/election-2020-joe-biden-donald-trump-elections-coronavirus-pandemic-e8862b01f07347e7b560a8d6c873d476 |access-date=November 21, 2021 |work=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref> Former Republican governor of California, [[Arnold Schwarzenegger]], wrote in ''The Economist'' that "President Donald Trump's actions to destroy faith in our elections and throw centuries of American principles out the window must be met with universal condemnation from all political leaders, regardless of party".<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Schwarzenegger |first1=Arnold |date=January 5, 2021 |title=Judgment Day: Arnold Schwarzenegger on why Republicans must stop Trump |url=https://www.economist.com/by-invitation/2021/01/05/arnold-schwarzenegger-on-why-republicans-must-stop-trump |access-date=January 5, 2021 |newspaper=[[The Economist]]}}</ref>

Longtime Republican strategist [[Steve Schmidt]] stated: "The Republican Party is an organized conspiracy for the purposes of maintaining power for self-interest, and the self-interest of its donor class... It's no longer dedicated to American democracy".<ref name="NYT-20201211">{{Cite news |author=The Editorial board |date=December 11, 2020 |title=The Republicans Who Embraced Nihilism – The Supreme Court thwarts the latest Trumpist attack on American democracy. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/12/11/opinion/republican-election-trump-supreme-court.html |access-date=December 11, 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref><ref name="NCRM-20201209">{{Cite news |last=Chapman |first=Matthew |date=December 9, 2020 |title=The GOP Is an 'Organized Conspiracy' That Exists for 'No Purpose Other Than Power' Says Steve Schmidt |url=https://www.thenewcivilrightsmovement.com/2020/12/the-gop-is-an-organized-conspiracy-that-exists-for-no-purpose-other-than-power-says-steve-schmidt/ |access-date=December 11, 2020 |work=TheNewCivilRightsMovement.com}}</ref><ref name="MSNBC-20201209">{{Cite news |last=Schmidt |first=Steve |display-authors=et al. |date=December 9, 2020 |title=Steve Schmidt says the GOP is an 'organized conspiracy' to gain power – video (2:43) |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=J7QByn_TfCA |access-date=December 11, 2020 |work=[[MSNBC|MSNBC News]]}}</ref><ref name="RCP-20201210">{{Cite news |last=Hains |first=Tim |date=December 10, 2020 |title="Lincoln Project" Founder Steve Schmidt Warns: "The Republican Party Is An Organized Conspiracy" And They Just Crossed The Rubicon |url=https://www.realclearpolitics.com/video/2020/12/10/lincoln_project_founder_steve_schmidt_warns_the_republican_party_is_an_organized_conspiracy_and_they_just_crossed_the_rubicon.html |access-date=December 10, 2020 |work=[[RealClearPolitics]]}}</ref>

All ten living former secretaries of defense{{snd}}including Dick Cheney, Donald Rumsfeld and Robert Gates{{snd}}published an essay on January 3, 2021, stating: "The time for questioning the results has passed; the time for the formal counting of the electoral college votes, as prescribed in the Constitution and statute, has arrived". They also warned of grave consequences of any contemplated military involvement in the situation.<ref name="All10SECDEF" /><ref>{{Cite web |last=Lamothe |first=Dan |date=January 3, 2021 |title=The time to question election results has passed, all living former defense secretaries say |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/former-defense-secretaries-rebuke-trump-election/2021/01/03/1c708f64-4de5-11eb-b2e8-3339e73d9da2_story.html |access-date=January 1, 2021 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]}}</ref>

A former communications director for Senator Ted Cruz told reporters that "the new Ted Cruz, post-Trump, is one I don't recognize...his actions directly played into the hands of the mob".<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Wagner |first1=Meg |last2=Macaya |first2=Melissa |date=January 8, 2021 |title=Cruz's former spokeswoman says she does not recognize him anymore |url=https://edition.cnn.com/politics/live-news/washington-dc-riots-trump-news-friday#h_2a423fc6f3ccf3d2bd39eb06fa16ddfa |access-date=January 9, 2021 |website=[[CNN]]}}</ref>{{Relevance inline|date=February 2024}}

==== Others ====
At least eight sitting Republican senators,{{efn|The senators are [[Roy Blunt]],<ref name="Everett">{{Cite news |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/11/06/gop-pushes-back-trump-false-election-claims-434653 |title=GOP begins pushing back against Trump's false election claims |first1=Burgess |last1=Everett |first2=Melanie |last2=Zanona |work=[[Politico]] |date=November 6, 2020 |access-date=November 6, 2020 |archive-date=November 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201106141222/https://www.politico.com/news/2020/11/06/gop-pushes-back-trump-false-election-claims-434653 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Susan Collins]],<ref name="Everett"/> [[Joni Ernst]],<ref name="ernst-outrageous">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/live/2020/11/19/us/joe-biden-trump-updates#absolutely-outrageous-joni-ernst-bristles-at-trump-teams-groundless-claims-about-election-results |title='Absolutely outrageous.' Joni Ernst bristles at Trump team's groundless claims about election results. |first1=Nicholas |last1=Fandos |first2=Catie |last2=Edmonson |date=November 19, 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=November 22, 2020 |archive-date=November 22, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201122010110/https://www.nytimes.com/live/2020/11/19/us/joe-biden-trump-updates#absolutely-outrageous-joni-ernst-bristles-at-trump-teams-groundless-claims-about-election-results |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Lisa Murkowski]],<ref name="Daly">{{Cite news |url=https://apnews.com/article/pat-toomey-no-evidence-vote-fraud-0ac291da7ab09f6336d24290ef81f53b |title=GOP divided over Trump's baseless claims of election fraud |first=Matthew |last=Daly |work=[[Associated Press]] |date=November 6, 2020 |access-date=November 6, 2020 |archive-date=November 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201106153600/https://apnews.com/article/pat-toomey-no-evidence-vote-fraud-0ac291da7ab09f6336d24290ef81f53b |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Rob Portman]],<ref name="Star Tribune">{{Cite news |url=https://www.startribune.com/republicans-break-with-trump-over-push-to-halt-vote-count/572984782/ |title=Some in GOP break with Trump over baseless vote-fraud claims |first=Matthew |last=Daly |work=[[Star Tribune]] |date=November 5, 2020 |access-date=November 7, 2020 |archive-date=November 16, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201116035242/https://www.startribune.com/republicans-break-with-trump-over-push-to-halt-vote-count/572984782/ |url-status=live}}</ref> Mitt Romney,<ref name="Daly"/> [[Ben Sasse]]<ref name="Everett"/> and [[Pat Toomey]].<ref name="Daly"/>}} members of the second Bush administration,{{efn|Statements were made by [[George W. Bush]],<ref name="Bradner">{{Cite news |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/11/08/politics/george-w-bush-congratulates-biden/index.html |title=Bush congratulates Biden, says election was 'fundamentally fair' and 'its outcome is clear' |first=Eric |last=Bradner |work=[[CNN]] |date=November 8, 2020 |access-date=November 8, 2020 |archive-date=November 16, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201116035324/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/11/08/politics/george-w-bush-congratulates-biden/index.html |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Andrew Card]],<ref name="DeCiccio">{{Cite news |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/11/11/former-bush-chief-of-staff-cites-9/11-warns-about-slow-transition.html |title=Former Bush chief of staff cites 9/11 Commission, warns about slow transition |first=Emily |last=DeCiccio |publisher=[[CNBC]]|date=November 11, 2020 |access-date=November 14, 2020 |archive-date=November 16, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201116035402/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/11/11/former-bush-chief-of-staff-cites-9/11-warns-about-slow-transition.html |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Dan Coats]],<ref name="Coats">{{Cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/andrewsolender/2020/11/13/ex-trump-intelligence-chief-dan-coats-among-20-new-republicans-calling-biden-president-elect/ |title=Ex-Trump Intelligence Chief Dan Coats Among 20 New Republicans Calling Biden President-Elect |first=Andrew |last=Solender |work=[[Forbes]]|date=November 13, 2020 |access-date=November 21, 2020 |archive-date=November 13, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201113222354/https://www.forbes.com/sites/andrewsolender/2020/11/13/ex-trump-intelligence-chief-dan-coats-among-20-new-republicans-calling-biden-president-elect/ |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Ari Fleischer]],<ref name="Goldmacher">{{Cite news |last1=Goldmacher |first1=Shane |last2=Cochrane |first2=Emily |date=November 12, 2020 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/11/12/us/politics/trump-republican-party-election.html |title=Small Cracks Emerge in G.O.P. Support for Trump's Baseless Fraud Claims |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=November 13, 2020 |archive-date=November 16, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201116035355/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/11/12/us/politics/trump-republican-party-election.html |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Condoleezza Rice]],<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/condoleezza-rice-calls-for-respect-and-empathy-and-gets-the-exact-opposite-11604940045 |title=Condoleezza Rice calls for 'respect' and 'empathy' from both sides – and gets the exact opposite |first=Shawn |last=Langlois |work=[[MarketWatch]]|date=November 9, 2020 |access-date=November 13, 2020 |archive-date=November 16, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201116035355/https://www.marketwatch.com/story/condoleezza-rice-calls-for-respect-and-empathy-and-gets-the-exact-opposite-11604940045 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Tom Ridge]]<ref name="Shepherd">{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2020/11/06/republicans-split-trump-election-fraud/ |title=GOP splits over Trump's false election claims, unfounded fraud allegations |first=Katie |last=Shepherd |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=November 6, 2020 |access-date=November 7, 2020 |archive-date=November 16, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201116035335/https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2020/11/06/republicans-split-trump-election-fraud/ |url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Karl Rove]].<ref name="Perkins">{{Cite news |last=Perkins |first=Tom |date=November 6, 2020 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/nov/06/republicans-break-ranks-with-donald-trump-over-baseless-vote-claim |title=Donald Trump's baseless vote fraud claim opens cracks in Republican ranks |work=The Guardian |access-date=November 6, 2020 |archive-date=November 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201106152002/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/nov/06/republicans-break-ranks-with-donald-trump-over-baseless-vote-claim |url-status=live}}</ref>}} and former members of the Trump administration condemned Trump's claims of fraud{{When|date=February 2024}}.{{efn|The former members included [[National Security Advisor (United States)|National Security Advisor]] [[John Bolton]],<ref name="Crowley">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/11/06/us/politics/trump-election-republicans.html |title=Trump's False Election Fraud Claims Split Republicans |first=Michael |last=Crowley |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=November 6, 2020 |access-date=November 6, 2020 |archive-date=November 16, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201116035304/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/11/06/us/politics/trump-election-republicans.html |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Director of National Intelligence]] [[Michael Chertoff]],<ref name="Coats"/> and [[H. R. McMaster]], [[National Security Advisor (United States)|Assistant to the President for National Security Affairs]] (2017–2018).<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/live/2020/11/15/us/joe-biden-trump |title=Presidential Transition: As More Republicans Break With Trump, He Refuses to Budge |first1=Hailey |last1=Fuchs |first2=Melina |last2=Delkic |first3=Chris |last3=Cameron |date=November 15, 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=November 15, 2020 |archive-date=November 16, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201116035425/https://www.nytimes.com/live/2020/11/15/us/joe-biden-trump |url-status=live}}</ref>}}

House Minority leader Kevin McCarthy initially spoke against Trump's schemes as "doomed to fail" before the attack. During the attack, he implored Trump to intervene. Six days after the attack, he said in a radio interview that he supported a bipartisan commission and grand jury to investigate and that Trump "told me personally that he does have some responsibility". The next day, he stated on the House floor that Trump "bears responsibility for Wednesday's attack on Congress by mob rioters". However, after meeting with Trump at [[Mar-a-Lago]] on January 28, 2021, the tone of McCarthy's public comments "changed markedly". McCarthy ultimately opposed the formation of a bipartisan [[January 6 commission]] and the House committee.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sayers |first1=Devon M. |last2=Gangel |first2=Jamie |last3=Nobles |first3=Ryan |date=January 28, 2021 |title=McCarthy and Trump discuss Republicans' plans to win House majority at Florida meeting Thursday |url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/01/28/politics/donald-trump-kevin-mccarthy-meeting/index.html |access-date=January 17, 2023 |publisher=[[CNN]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Neidzwadek |first1=Nick |date=January 13, 2021 |title=McCarthy says Trump 'bears responsibility' for Capitol riot |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2021/01/13/mccarthy-trump-responsibility-capitol-riot-458975 |access-date=January 17, 2023 |work=[[Politico]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Herb |first1=Jeremy |date=May 18, 2021 |title=McCarthy won't support January 6 commission and sides with Republicans downplaying the insurrection |url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/05/18/politics/kevin-mccarthy-opposes-1-6-commission/index.html |access-date=January 17, 2023 |work=[[CNN]]}}</ref>

The ''[[New York Post]]'', which had promoted Trump's celebrity in New York since the 1980s<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2016/04/2016-donald-trump-tabloids-new-york-post-daily-news-media-213842/ |date=May 2016 |title=Confessions of a Trump Tabloid Scribe |first=Susan |last=Mulcahy |website=[[Politico]] |access-date=January 5, 2021}}</ref> and had twice endorsed his presidential candidacy, published a front-page editorial in December asking the president to "stop the insanity" and "end this dark charade", asserting that he was "cheering for an undemocratic coup". The editorial continued: "If you insist on spending your final days in office threatening to burn it all down, that will be how you are remembered. Not as a revolutionary, but as the anarchist holding the match." The ''Post'' characterized his former national security advisor Michael Flynn's suggestion to declare martial law as "tantamount to treason".

''The Wall Street Journal'' editorial board on December 20, 2020, wrote "As he leaves office he can't seem to help reminding Americans why they denied him a second term" and "his sore loser routine is beginning to grate even on millions who voted for him".<ref>{{Cite news |date=December 20, 2020 |title=Trump's Bad Exit |language=en-US |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/trumps-bad-exit-11608504571 |access-date=October 29, 2021 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/12/28/business/media/new-york-post-trump-editorial.html |title=Murdoch's New York Post Blasts President's Fraud Claims |first=Marc |last=Tracy |date=December 28, 2020 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=January 1, 2021}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/12/28/media/new-york-post-donald-trump-editorial/index.html |date=December 28, 2020 |title=New York Post to Donald Trump: Stop the insanity |first=David |last=Goldman |website=[[CNN]] |access-date=January 1, 2021}}</ref>

In 2011, Fox News created a "Monday Mornings with Trump" segment during which Trump would call in to ''[[Fox & Friends]]'' to offer his views on current affairs, and the hosts of that program continued to be supportive of Trump during his presidency.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Stelter |first=Brian |date=September 15, 2020 |title=Trump says weekly calls on 'Fox & Friends' are returning; Fox says maybe not |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/09/15/media/fox-and-friends-trump-interview/index.html |website=[[CNN]] |access-date=January 1, 2021}}</ref> On January 4, 2021, host [[Ainsley Earhardt]] stated that many conservatives "feel like it was rigged", although host [[Steve Doocy]] responded: "That's the case that Donald Trump and his lawyers have put out. They said there is all this evidence. But they haven't really produced the evidence." Host [[Brian Kilmeade]] stated that he had another "worry" about "[[2021 United States Capitol attack|the protest the president is calling for]] on Tuesday and Wednesday [as Congress convened to certify the election results]. I mean, this is the type of anarchy that doesn't work for anybody, Republicans or Democrats, in the big picture."<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mediaite.com/tv/ainsley-earhardt-says-conservatives-feel-election-was-rigged-after-co-hosts-repeatedly-point-out-there-is-no-evidence/ |work=Mediaite |first=Ken |last=Meyer |title=Ainsley Earhardt Says Conservatives 'Feel' Election Was Rigged |date=January 4, 2021 |access-date=January 1, 2021}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Hall |first=Colby |date=January 4, 2021 |url=https://www.mediaite.com/tv/steve-doocy-and-brian-kilmeade-agree-its-long-past-time-for-trump-to-show-evidence-of-voter-fraud-this-sort-of-anarchy-doesnt-work-for-anybody/ |title=Steve Doocy and Brian Kilmeade Agree It's Long Past Time for Trump to Show Evidence of Voter Fraud |work=Mediaite |access-date=January 1, 2021}}</ref>

=== Description as attempted coup ===

==== Before the Capitol attack ====
Multiple media outlets{{efn|The outlets are ''[[The Atlantic]]'',<ref>{{wikicite |id=Tufekci-2020 |reference={{Cite web |last=Tufekci |first=Zeynep |date=December 7, 2020 |title=This Must Be Your First |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2020/12/trumps-farcical-inept-and-deadly-serious-coup-attempt/617309/ |quote=the word coup may not technically capture what we're seeing |access-date=December 8, 2020 |website=[[The Atlantic]] |archive-date=December 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201208201028/https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2020/12/trumps-farcical-inept-and-deadly-serious-coup-attempt/617309/ |url-status=live}}}}</ref> [[Bloomberg News]],<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2020-11-19/trump-s-coup-attempt-will-be-a-very-costly-failure |first=Mark |last=Gongloff |title=Trump's Coup Attempt Will Be a Very Costly Failure |website=Bloomberg.com |date=November 19, 2020 |publisher=[[Bloomberg News]] |access-date=November 22, 2020 |archive-date=November 20, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201120013158/https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2020-11-19/trump-s-coup-attempt-will-be-a-very-costly-failure |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="Niquette_12/13/2020">{{Cite news |last=Niquette |first=Mark |title=Biden Nod From Electors Could Seal His Win With Some in GOP |website=[[Bloomberg News]] |date=December 13, 2020 |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-12-14/biden-s-nod-from-electors-could-seal-his-win-with-some-in-gop |access-date=December 14, 2020 |quote=It's mind-boggling to me that we have people that are actually trying conduct a coup and take the votes away from the voters.}}</ref> ''[[The Economist]]'',<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.economist.com/united-states/2020/11/21/donald-trumps-refusal-to-concede-is-harming-america |access-date=January 1, 2021 |title=Donald Trump's refusal to concede is harming America |date=November 21, 2020 |newspaper=[[The Economist]]}}</ref> ''[[The Financial Times]]'',<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.ft.com/content/14a69082-1e42-4c02-8319-f3750690c8c8 |access-date=November 21, 2021 |title=Donald Trump is not done with America yet |website=[[Financial Times]]|date=November 12, 2020 |last1=Luce |first1=Edward }}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'',<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/nov/11/donald-trump-presidency-coup-power-election-joe-biden |title='It must be made to fail': Trump's desperate bid to cling to power |first=Tom |last=McCarthy |date=November 11, 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=November 22, 2020 |archive-date=November 22, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201122035428/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/nov/11/donald-trump-presidency-coup-power-election-joe-biden |url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[New York (magazine)|The Intelligencer]]'',<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2020/12/congress-will-likely-vote-on-trumps-election-coup.html |access-date=November 21, 2021 |first=Ed |last=Kilgore |title=Every Republican in Congress May Have to Vote on Trump's Coup |work=[[New York (magazine)|The Intelligencer]] |date=December 10, 2020}}</ref> ''[[The Nation]]'',<ref>{{Cite magazine |url=https://www.thenation.com/article/politics/trump-coup-election/ |title=People Are Taking the Wrong Lesson From Trump's Failed Coup |first=Elie |last=Mystal |date=December 12, 2020 |magazine=[[The Nation]] |access-date=November 21, 2021 }}</ref> ''[[The New Yorker]]'',<ref>{{Cite magazine |url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/our-columnists/the-coup-stage-of-donald-trumps-presidency |date=November 20, 2020 |title=The Coup Stage of Donald Trump's Presidency |first=Masha |last=Gessen |magazine=[[The New Yorker]] |access-date=November 22, 2020 |archive-date=November 22, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201122010559/https://www.newyorker.com/news/our-columnists/the-coup-stage-of-donald-trumps-presidency |url-status=live}}</ref> ''The New York Times'',<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/01/05/opinion/trump-republicans-election.html |access-date=November 21, 2021 |title=Opinion &#124; Never Forget the Names of These Republicans Attempting a Coup |first=Thomas L. |last=Friedman |date=January 6, 2021 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |archive-date=January 10, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210110092736/https://www.nytimes.com/2021/01/05/opinion/trump-republicans-election.html |url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[Salon (website)|Salon]]'',<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.salon.com/2020/12/11/dont-look-past-trumps-coup-attempt-this-is-a-dark-moment-in-american-history/ |access-date=November 21, 2021 |first=Chauncey |last=Devega |title=Don't look past Trump's coup attempt: This is a dark moment in American history |date=December 11, 2020 |website=[[Salon.com]] }}</ref> ''[[The San Francisco Chronicle]]'',<ref name="SFC-20201210">{{Cite news |work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] |publisher=Editorial Board |title=Editorial: The enduring cost of Trump's attempted coup |url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/opinion/editorials/article/Editorial-The-enduring-cost-of-Trump-s-15789752.php |date=December 10, 2020 |access-date=December 10, 2020}}</ref> ''The Washington Post'',<ref name="WP-20201119">{{Cite news |first1=Philip |last1=Rucker |first2=Amy |last2=Gardner |first3=Josh |last3=Dawsey |title=Trump uses power of presidency to try to overturn the election and stay in office |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trump-uses-power-of-presidency-to-try-to-overturn-the-election-and-stay-in-office/2020/11/19/bc89caa6-2a9f-11eb-8fa2-06e7cbb145c0_story.html |date=November 19, 2020 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=December 10, 2020}}</ref> and ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]''<ref>{{Cite magazine |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2020/12/donald-trump-house-gop-coup |date=December 10, 2020 |access-date=January 5, 2021 |title=106 House Republicans Back Trump's Bid to Overthrow the Government |first=Bess |last=Levin |magazine=Vanity Fair}}</ref>}} characterized the efforts as an attempted coup. A number of scholars and pundits preferred to use the more precise term [[autocoup]].<ref>{{Cite interview |last=Scarborough |first=Charles Joseph |subject-link=Joe Scarborough |interviewer-last=Scarborough |interviewer-first=Mika Emilie Leonia Brzezinski |interviewer-link=Mika Brzezinski |title=Morning Joe |url=https://archive.org/details/MSNBCW_20201201_110000_Morning_Joe/start/5005/end/5072 |access-date=January 17, 2023 |work=[[MSNBC]] |date=December 1, 2020 |quote=Just so people who think this, to call this a coup is hyperbolic, or an attempted coup, you just look at the [[Special:PermanentLink/991335238|definition in Wikipedia]]: it says, "Typically, it's an illegal, unconstitutional attempt to seize power by a political faction". Definition of a coup. Of course, if he's already in power, it'd be an "[[autocoup]]". But at the same time, you look at the definition, and if... I guess I would just say to Trump defenders, if it's not an attempted coup, if it's not an "illegal unconstitutional attempt to seize power by a political faction" when he's trying to call people to the White House to get them to change their votes, trying to call the Governor of Arizona to try to stop him from doing legally what he has to do which is to certify the election results, trying to get those in Michigan and Wayne County to illegally not certify the votes there... if Republicans don't think it's a coup or doesn't fit this definition of a coup in [[Four corners (law)|all four corners]] then I'd love to hear what they would call it.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Nakamura |first=David |date=January 5, 2021 |title=With brazen assault on election, Trump prompts critics to warn of a coup |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trump-election-coup/2021/01/05/26afcfc0-4f6c-11eb-bda4-615aaefd0555_story.html |access-date=January 6, 2021 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |issn=0190-8286}}</ref><ref name="DeBruin20201111">{{Cite news |date=November 11, 2020 |title=No, Trump is not attempting a 'coup.' Here's why the distinction matters.: It's important that we describe the crisis accurately. That will shape our response. |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/outlook/2020/11/11/coup-trump-election-concede-military/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201123183158/https://www.washingtonpost.com/outlook/2020/11/11/coup-trump-election-concede-military/ |archive-date=November 23, 2020 |access-date=November 21, 2021 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |department=PostEverything · Perspective |quote=Because Trump is attempting to remain in power, rather than remove someone else from it his efforts come closer to what scholars call an attempt at a "self-coup" – or, using the Spanish term, an {{lang |es |[[autogolpe]]}} – in which a head of state attempts to remain in power past his or her term in office. |surname=De Bruin |given=Erica}}</ref><ref name="Narea20201114">{{Cite web |last=Narea |first=Nicole |date=November 14, 2020 |title=3 scholars say Trump isn't staging a coup – but he still poses a threat to democracy |url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2020/11/14/21561952/trump-coup-2020-election-biden-president |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201218120206/https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2020/11/14/21561952/trump-coup-2020-election-biden-president |archive-date=December 18, 2020 |access-date=November 21, 2021 |website=[[Vox (website)|Vox]]}}</ref>

On November 14, Jonathan Powell argued that any illegal or unconstitutional attempts to overturn the results would make it a coup.<ref name="Narea20201114" /> On December 7, [[Daniel Drezner]] argued that violence would be necessary for the coup definition to be met.<ref name="Drezner20201207">{{Cite web |surname=Drezner |given=Daniel W. |date=December 7, 2020 |title=It's not a coup. It's not even a bad coup: Coup-coup-kachoo! |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/outlook/2020/12/07/its-not-coup-its-not-even-bad-coup/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201217052502/https://www.washingtonpost.com/outlook/2020/12/07/its-not-coup-its-not-even-bad-coup/ |archive-date=December 17, 2020 |access-date=November 21, 2021 |issn=0190-8286 |quote=To be clear, the takeaway from this is not to relax completely. However ineptly, Trump and his legal team ''are'' trying to overturn the results. The effect on GOP public attitudes is disheartening. {{Citeref |Tufekci is correct to observe |id=Tufekci-2020 |style=plain}} that the watchword is vigilance. That said, what is happening is not a coup, or even an attempt at a coup. It is a ham-handed effort to besmirch the election outcome by any easily available means necessary. That is not good, but it is very different from Turkey's myriad coups. |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |department=PostEverything · Perspective}}</ref> When news broke about Trump's December 27, 2020 call with Rosen telling the Justice Department to say the election was "corrupt and leave the rest to me", [[Ari Melber]] on MSNBC described Trump's activities up through that time as a [[soft coup]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Melber |first=Ari |date=July 30, 2021 |title=Trump 'Soft Coup' Busted By 2021 Leak Of Secret DOJ Notes |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=emErv76P5Dg |access-date=2022-06-15 |work=MSNBC The Beat |language=en}}</ref> On a January 4, 2021 podcast, [[Steve Bannon]], while discussing the planning for the upcoming events and speech by Trump on January 6 at [[The Ellipse]], said: "Live from our nation's capital, you're in the field headquarters of one of the small divisions of the bloodless coup".<ref name="CNN_7/15/2022">{{cite web |date=July 15, 2022 |title=CNN Transcripts |url=https://transcripts.cnn.com/show/nday/date/2022-07-15/segment/05 |access-date=July 20, 2022 |website=[[CNN]]}}</ref><ref name="Peltz_10/29/2021">{{cite web |last=Peltz |first=Madeline |date=October 29, 2021 |title=Leading up to January 6, Steve Bannon publicly bragged about his behind-the-scene role fomenting the insurrection |url=https://www.mediamatters.org/steve-bannon/leading-january-6-steve-bannon-publicly-bragged-about-his-behind-scene-role-fomenting |access-date=July 20, 2022 |website=[[Media Matters for America]]}}</ref>

According to [[I Alone Can Fix It|a July 2021 book]] by ''Washington Post'' reporters [[Philip Rucker]] and [[Carol Leonnig]], during the weeks following the election, [[Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff]] [[Mark Milley]] became concerned that Trump was preparing to stage a coup, and held informal discussions with his deputies about possible ways to thwart it, telling associates: "They may try, but they're not going to fucking succeed. You can't do this without the military. You can't do this without the CIA and the FBI. We're the guys with the guns." The book also quoted Milley saying: "This is a [[Reichstag fire|Reichstag]] moment. The gospel of the [[Führer]]." Milley reportedly told police and military officials preparing to secure Joe Biden's presidential inauguration: "Everyone in this room, whether you're a cop, whether you're a soldier, we're going to stop these guys to make sure we have a peaceful transfer of power. We're going to put a ring of steel around this city and the Nazis aren't getting in." The book also stated that a friend told Milley they were concerned that Trump's allies were attempting to "overturn the government".<ref name="auto7">{{Cite web |last=Thebault |first=Reis |date=July 14, 2021 |title=Top U.S. military official draws parallels between Trump, Hitler |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/nation-world/joint-chiefs-chairperson-feared-potential-reichstag-moment-aimed-at-keeping-trump-in-power/ |access-date=November 21, 2021 |website=[[The Seattle Times]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last1=Gangel |first1=Jamie |last2=Herb |first2=Jeremy |last3=Cohen |first3=Marshall |last4=Stuart |first4=Elizabeth |date=July 15, 2021 |title='They're not going to f**king succeed': Top generals feared Trump would attempt a coup after election, according to new book |url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/07/14/politics/donald-trump-election-coup-new-book-excerpt/index.html |access-date=November 21, 2021 |website=[[CNN]]}}</ref>

==== During or after the Capitol attack ====
{{See also|International reactions to the January 6 United States Capitol attack}}
Representative [[Adam Kinzinger]] (R-IL),<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Wagner |first1=Meg |last2=Macaya |first2=Melissa |last3=Hayes |first3=Mike |last4=Mahtani |first4=Melissa |last5=Rocha |first5=Veronica |last6=Alfonso |first6=Fernando III |date=January 6, 2021 |title=Republican congressman tweets: "This is a coup attempt" |url=https://edition.cnn.com/politics/live-news/congress-electoral-college-vote-count-2021/ |access-date=April 7, 2021 |website=[[CNN]]}}</ref> as well as New York Attorney General [[Letitia James]]<ref>{{Cite web |last=Reisman |first=Nick |date=January 6, 2021 |title=Cuomo, AG James Call U.S. Capitol Riot a Failed Coup |url=https://spectrumlocalnews.com/nys/capital-region/ny-state-of-politics/2021/01/06/james-calls-u-s--capitol-riot-a--coup-attempt- |access-date=January 11, 2021 |website=spectrumlocalnews.com}}</ref> described the event as a coup attempt. On March 28, 2022, [[United States district court]] Judge [[David O. Carter]] ordered Attorney [[John C. Eastman|John Eastman]] to hand over documents to the [[United States House Select Committee on the January 6 Attack|house select committee]]. In the court's opinion, Judge Carter wrote that Eastman and Trump's campaign was "a coup in search of a legal theory".<ref name="JudgeCarterOpinion" /> Later that day, US Representative [[Bennie Thompson]] (D-MS), chairman of [[United States House Select Committee on the January 6 Attack|House January 6th committee]], read the relevant paragraph of Judge Carter's opinion into the committee record.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-03-28 |title=Thompson & Cheney Opening Statements at Select Committee Business Meeting |url=https://january6th.house.gov/news/press-releases/thompson-cheney-opening-statements-select-committee-business-meeting-2 |access-date=2022-06-13 |website=Select Committee to Investigate the January 6th Attack on the United States Capitol |language=en}}</ref><ref>(Video) {{Cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gh0NLhcHSlw&t=1031s |title=Business Meeting Recommending the House Cite Peter Navarro & Daniel Scavino Jr for Criminal Contempt |date=2022-03-28 |publisher=U.S. House Select Committee to Investigate the January 6th Attack on the United States Capitol |access-date=June 13, 2022 |via=youtube}}</ref>{{Relevance inline|discuss=Is reading the paragraph into the record that relevant here?|date=February 2024}} Sen. Mitt Romney (R-UT) described the events as an "insurrection", language also echoed by President-elect Biden.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Swanson |first=Ian |date=January 6, 2021 |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/senate/532955-romney-trump-caused-this-insurrection |title=Romney: Trump caused 'this insurrection' |website=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |access-date=April 7, 2021}}</ref>

Professors [[Inderjeet Parmar]],<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Parmar |first=Inderjeet |date=2021 |title=Trump's Coup and Insurrection: Biden's Challenge and Opportunity |journal=Insight Turkey |volume=23 |issue=1 |pages=35–50 |article-number=https://www.insightturkey.com/ |doi=10.25253/99.2021231.4 |jstor=26989815 |s2cid=233825478 |issn=1302-177X|doi-access=free }}</ref> [[Timothy D. Snyder]],<ref>{{Cite news |last=Davis |first=Charles R. |date=January 14, 2022 |title=Yale history professor Timothy Snyder told Insider he fears American democracy may not survive another Trump campaign |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/timothy-snyder-fears-democracy-may-not-survive-another-trump-campaign-2022-1 |access-date=2022-06-18 |work=[[Business Insider]] |language=en-US |quote=Well, I mean, obviously things could be worse. The January 6th insurrection a year ago could have succeeded. We could be living in a country that is wracked by civil and indeed violent conflict after Donald Trump succeeds in, at least temporarily, staying in power, thanks to some kind of conspiracy of his supporters, the Department of Justice, supporters in Congress and so on, right? So things could be worse. And I wouldn't wanna deny that. Unfortunately, that scenario is not one that is just in the rearview mirror. It's also one that is right in front of us. The problem with a failed coup, which is what January 6th, 2021, is, is that it is practice for a successful coup. So what we're looking at now is a kind of slow-motion practice for a repetition of all of that, but this time with the legal parts of it more fully prepared. What I'm afraid of is that now, in the shadow of a big lie{{snd}}namely, that Trump actually won{{snd}}the states are preparing the legal steps that will enable Trump to be installed as president the next time around. And that in turn will lead to a terrible sort of conflict, the kind that we haven't seen before.}}</ref> and scholars at the [[Brookings Institution]] called the event a coup<ref name="TrumpOnTrial">{{Cite report |url=https://www.brookings.edu/research/trump-on-trial/ |title=Trump on Trial: A Guide to the January 6 Hearings and the Question of Criminality |last1=Eisen |first1=Norman |last2=Ayer |first2=Donald |date=2022-06-06 |publisher=Brookings Institution |language=en-US |quote=[Trump] tried to delegitimize the election results by disseminating a series of far fetched and evidence-free claims of fraud. Meanwhile, with a ring of close confidants, Trump conceived and implemented unprecedented schemes to{{snd}}in his own words{{snd}}"overturn" the election outcome. Among the results of this "Big Lie" campaign were the terrible events of January 6, 2021{{snd}}an inflection point in what we now understand was nothing less than an attempted coup. |last3=Perry |first3=Joshua |last4=Bookbinder |first4=Noah |last5=Perry |first5=E. Danya |author-link=Norm Eisen |author-link2=Donald B. Ayer |access-date=January 17, 2023}}</ref> and other academics describe the event as a [[self-coup]].<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Pion-Berlin |first1=David |author-link=David Pion-Berlin |last2=Bruneau |first2=Thomas |last3=Goetze |first3=Richard B. |date=April 7, 2022 |title=The Trump Self-Coup Attempt: Comparisons and Civil–Military Relations |journal=Government and Opposition |language=en |publisher=Cambridge University Press |volume=58 |issue=4 |pages=789–806 |doi=10.1017/gov.2022.13 |issn=0017-257X |s2cid=248033246 |doi-access=free}}</ref><ref name="ProvostHarvey">{{Cite book |last=Harvey |first=Michael |url=https://www.taylorfrancis.com/chapters/edit/10.4324/9781003110361-1/introduction-michael-harvey |title=Donald Trump in Historical Perspective |date=2022 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1-003-11036-1 |editor-last=Harvey |editor-first=Michael |chapter=Introduction: History's Rhymes |doi=10.4324/9781003110361-1 |quote = As with the Beer Hall Putsch, a would-be leader tried to take advantage of an already scheduled event (in Hitler's case, Kahr's speech; in Trump's, Congress's tallying of the electoral votes) to create a dramatic moment with himself at the center of attention, calling for bold action to upend the political order. Unlike Hitler's coup attempt, Trump already held top of office, so he was attempting to hold onto power, not seize it (the precise term for Trump's intended action is a 'self-coup' or 'autogolpe'). Thus, Trump was able to plan for the event well in advance, and with much greater control, including developing the legal arguments that could be used to justify rejecting the election's results. (p3)}}</ref>

=== "Trump won" and "big lie" <span class="anchor" id="Trump won"></span> ===
{{Main|Big lie#Donald Trump's false claims of a stolen election}}
"Trump won" is a political slogan adopted by Trump supporters who, contrary to the election results, believe that Trump won the 2020 U.S. presidential election.<ref>{{Cite news |date=January 5, 2021 |title=US election 2020: The people who still believe Trump won |language=en-GB |work=[[BBC News]] |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-55481521 |access-date=June 29, 2021}}</ref><ref name=buzzfeednews>{{Cite web |title=The People Still Going To Trump Rallies Are Committed To Trump's Fantasy: "He's Our True President" |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/kadiagoba/trump-rally-ohio-election-fantasy |date=June 27, 2021 |first=Kadia |last=Goba |access-date=June 29, 2021 |website=[[BuzzFeed News]] |language=en}}</ref> These claims were described by former US Attorney General [[William Barr]] as "bullshit" in sworn deposition testimony,<ref>{{Cite news |last=Parton |first=Heather Digby |author-link=Digby (blogger) |date=2021-06-28 |title=Bill Barr calls "bullshit" on Trump's Big Lie – but it is much too late now |language=en |url=https://www.salon.com/2021/06/28/bill-barr-calls-bullshit-on-trumps-big-lie--but-it-is-much-too-late-now/ |work=[[Salon.com]] |access-date=2022-06-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Barr |first=William |title=January 6th Committee Public Hearing, sworn deposition testimony of former US AG William Barr |language=en |publisher=[[C-SPAN]] |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lZJ56cXSI-o&t=1055s |date=June 10, 2022 |access-date=June 12, 2022 }}</ref> and are called a "big lie" by many, including Senator Mitt Romney.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Romney |first=Mitt |date=2021-02-18 |title=Romney Releases Statement for Congressional Record on Impeachment Trial |language=en-US |url=https://www.romney.senate.gov/romney-releases-statement-congressional-record-impeachment-trial/ |website=romney.senate.gov |access-date=2022-06-12}}</ref>

In the two weeks after the election, a large majority of Trump supporters thought the election was illegitimate.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Frankovic |first=Kathy |date=November 19, 2020 |title=Trump voters still see Biden's victory as illegitimate |url=https://today.yougov.com/topics/politics/articles-reports/2020/11/19/trump-voters-biden-poll |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201130002554/https://today.yougov.com/topics/politics/articles-reports/2020/11/19/trump-voters-biden-poll |archive-date=November 30, 2020 |access-date=December 1, 2020 |website=[[YouGov]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Pramuk |first=Jacob |date=November 24, 2020 |title=Almost no Trump voters consider Biden the legitimate 2020 election winner |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/11/23/2020-election-results-almost-no-trump-voters-consider-biden-the-winner.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201201073121/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/11/23/2020-election-results-almost-no-trump-voters-consider-biden-the-winner.html |archive-date=December 1, 2020 |access-date=December 1, 2020 |work=[[CNBC]]}}</ref> According to a September 2022 poll, 61% of Republicans still believed Biden won in 2020 due to "voter fraud".<ref>{{cite news |last=Murray |first=Mark |date=September 27, 2022 |title=Poll: 61% of Republicans still believe Biden didn't win fair and square in 2020 |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/meet-the-press/meetthepressblog/poll-61-republicans-still-believe-biden-didnt-win-fair-square-2020-rcna49630 |access-date=January 4, 2023 |website=[[NBC News]]}}</ref>{{Better source needed|reason=Need a source that analyzes belief in the big lie over time|date=February 2024}}

{{As of|2021|06}}, some still believed that Trump would be restored to power by some extraordinary process, possibly later in 2021.<ref name="buzzfeednews" /><ref>{{Cite news |last=Thomas |first=Phil |date=June 26, 2021 |title=Conspiracy theory that Trump will be reinstated in August has officials worried, report claims |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/trump-reinstated-august-conspiracy-theory-b1873357.html |access-date=June 29, 2021 |website=[[The Independent]] |language=en}}</ref> These beliefs have led to calls for violence on social media, sparking concerns from the [[United States Department of Homeland Security|Department of Homeland Security]] about violence by right-wing extremists in mid-2021.<ref>Multiple sources:
* {{Cite news |last1=Cohen |first1=Zachary |last2=Sands |first2=Geneva |date=June 30, 2021 |title=DHS raises alarms over potential for summer violence pegged to August conspiracy theory |url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/06/30/politics/dhs-summer-violence-warnings-conspiracy/index.html |access-date=June 30, 2021 |publisher=[[CNN]]}}
* {{cite news |last=Dilanian |first=Ken |date=August 11, 2021 |title=Feds warn of potential violence fueled by false election claims |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/politics-news/feds-warn-potential-violence-fueled-false-election-claims-n1276567 |access-date=August 13, 2021 |publisher=[[NBC News]]}}
* {{cite news |last=Sands |first=Geneva |date=August 13, 2021 |title=Calls for violence online similar to before January 6 Capitol attack, DHS Intel chief says |url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/08/13/politics/violence-online-similar-january-6-dhs-intel-chief/index.html |access-date=August 13, 2021 |publisher=[[CNN]]}}</ref> A CNN/SSRS poll conducted in August–September 2021 found that Republicans' enthusiasm for voting in future elections was higher among those believing that "Trump won" and with holding that belief as central to their identity as Republicans.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Enten |first=Harry |date=10 December 2021 |title=Voters who think Trump won are the most enthusiastic to vote in 2022 |url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/12/10/politics/republicans-fraud-turnout-analysis/index.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211210163319/https://www.cnn.com/2021/12/10/politics/republicans-fraud-turnout-analysis/index.html |archive-date=December 10, 2021 |access-date=2022-01-07 |website=[[CNN]]}}</ref>

=== Corporate reactions ===
{{see also|List of companies that halted U.S. political contributions in January 2021}}

On January 5, the Chief Executive of the [[United States Chamber of Commerce]] commented that "efforts by some members of Congress to disregard certified election results&nbsp;... undermines our democracy and the rule of law and will only result in further division", while almost 200 business leaders signed a statement from the [[Partnership for New York City]] declaring that such a move would "run counter to the essential tenets of our democracy".<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Politi |first1=James |last2=Weaver |first2=Courtney |date=January 5, 2021 |title=Donald Trump vows to 'fight like hell' to remain in White House |url=https://www.ft.com/content/5f839764-a441-4b7f-ba42-c5867ce1ce6f |access-date=January 5, 2021 |website=[[Financial Times]]}}</ref> On January 6, the [[National Association of Manufacturers]] called for Vice President Pence to invoke the [[Twenty-fifth Amendment to the United States Constitution]] and remove Trump from office.<ref>{{Cite web |date=January 6, 2021 |title=Manufacturers group calls on Pence to invoke 25th Amendment |url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/live-update/pro-trump-mob-breaches-u-s-capitol/manufacturers-group-calls-on-pence-to-invoke-25th-amendment |access-date=January 7, 2021 |website=[[PBS NewsHour]]r |agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref>

During the riot, a [[Cumulus Media]] executive told its radio hosts that they must stop spreading the idea of election fraud. The memo said the election was over and that "there are no alternate acceptable 'paths'", and thus the radio hosts must immediately "help induce national calm".<ref>{{Cite news |last=Farhi |first=Paul |date=January 11, 2021 |title=Talk-radio owner orders conservative hosts to temper election fraud rhetoric |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/media/cumulus-radio-conservative-election-fraud/2021/01/11/e12ec46e-537c-11eb-a817-e5e7f8a406d6_story.html |access-date=January 11, 2021 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]}}</ref>

Many large corporations pledged to suspend donations to officials and candidates who opposed the certification of Biden's victory, hindered the peaceful transfer of power, or incited violence. While many companies did so, most had resumed such contributions within a year, either directly or through their lobbyists.<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Mehta |first1=Seema |last2=Moore |first2=Maloy |last3=Stiles |first3=Matt |date=2021-04-20 |title=Most corporations stood by pledges to not fund politicians who voted against Biden's victory |url=https://www.latimes.com/politics/story/2021-04-19/corporations-pledge-donations-politicians-opposed-election-certification-biden |access-date=2023-02-17 |website=[[Los Angeles Times]] |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last1=Rappeport |first1=Alan |last2=Ngo |first2=Madeleine |last3=Kelly |first3=Kate |date=2022-01-06 |title=Corporations Donated Millions to Lawmakers Who Voted to Overturn Election Results |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2022/01/06/us/politics/congress-corporate-donations-2020-election-overturn.html |access-date=2023-02-17 |work=[[The New York Times]] |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last1=Birnbaum |first1=Emily |last2=Wilson |first2=Megan |last3=Fuchs |first3=Hailey |date=February 15, 2022 |title=These companies stopped campaign donations to election objectors. Their lobbyists did not. |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2022/02/15/jan-6-lobbying-companies-election-00008827 |access-date=2023-02-17 |website=[[Politico]] |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last1=Birnbaum |first1=Emily |last2=Bass |first2=Dina |date=2022-12-14 |title=Tech Firms Are Giving Money to Election Deniers Again |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2022-12-14/at-t-comcast-amazon-among-companies-giving-to-election-deniers-again |access-date=2023-02-17 |website=Bloomberg.com |language=en}}</ref>

