=====Behind the scenes=====
[[File:BBC Television Shakespeare Tewkesbury.jpg|thumb|The [[Battle of Tewkesbury]]. Note the similarity in the costumes of the two sets of combatants. It is virtually impossible to tell the Yorkists from the Lancastrians.]]
This episode was filmed on the same set as ''The First Part of Henry the Sixt''<!--Not a typo--> and ''The Second Part of Henry the Sixt''.<!--Not a typo--> However, designer Oliver Bayldon altered the set so it would appear to be falling apart, as England descended into an even worse state of chaos.<ref name="Warren"/> The cyclorama around the set was repainted with grey rolled over the gauze. Said Bayldon: "The adventure playground has become burned and charred - colours have been subdued to black and grey, and the colour of charred timber".<ref name="Wilders3H6">{{cite book | editor-last=Wilders | editor-first=John | title=Henry VI, Part 3 | series=The BBC TV Shakespeare | location=London | publisher=BBC Books | year=1983 | pages=20–31 | isbn=9780563200215}}</ref> The fights were designed to have very strong violence here, deliberately in contrast to the "knockabout" violence of ''The First Part''.<ref name="Wilders1H6"/>

The scene where Richard kills Henry has three biblical references carefully worked out by Howell: as Richard drags Henry away, his arms spread out into a crucified position; on the table at which he sat are seen bread and wine; and in the background, an iron crossbar is illuminated against the black stone wall.<ref>Willis, p. 181.</ref> Howell's editing uses more frequent cuts as the tetralogy progresses, emphasising the growing violence and tension in a divided England.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Cook |first1=Hardy M. |date=1992 |title=Jane Howell's BBC First Tetralogy: Theatrical and Televisual Manipulation |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/43796568 |journal=Literature/Film Quarterly |volume=20 |issue=4 |pages=326–331 |doi= |jstor=43796568 |access-date=10 September 2025}}</ref> Although the tetralogy takes place over decades, Howell chose not to focus on heavy ageing makeup. As Shakespeare's fidelity to historical fact is often not accurate, and the theatricality of the plays was already being emphasised, Howell decreed that any ageing makeup would be restricted to minor details.<ref name="WildersR3"/>

The ''Prefaces to Shakespeare'' episode for ''The Third Part of Henry the Sixt'' was presented by Brewster Mason who had played Warwick in the 1963 RSC production ''The Wars of the Roses'' directed by John Barton and Peter Hall. The ''Shakespeare in Perspective'' episode was presented by historian Michael Wood.<ref name="Howell"/>

=====Reception=====
Michael Mannheim, in ''Shakespeare on Film Newsletter'', was highly impressed, calling the tetralogy "a fascinating, fast paced and surprisingly tight-knit study in political and national deterioration."<ref name="Mannheim">{{cite journal | last=Manheim | first=Michael | title=The English History Play on screen | journal=Shakespeare on Film Newsletter | volume=11 | issue=1 | date=December 1986 | page=12}}</ref> G.M. Pearce, in ''[[Cahiers Élisabéthains]]'', admired the many touching moments throughout, and was impressed by Foster's complete transformation across the tetralogy. Pearce found Benson's voice well-suited to the part but annoyed that he didn't seem visibly aged throughout the three plays, while Cooper was more convincing as the Queen than during her character's earlier scenes. Ron Cook created a Richard with a strong personality, bringing out a lot of the script's dark humour, but he was "short on personal charm" and didn't make the most of the poetry in the dialogue.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Pearce |first1=G.M. |date=October 1983 |title=1 Henry VI, 2 Henry VI, 3 Henry VI, Richard III |journal=Cahiers Élisabéthains |volume=24}}</ref> Russell Davies, in ''Time'', praised Cooper and Foster, but found Cook underwhelming: "not so much a lump of foul deformity, more a disaffected pensionee of the [[John_Oaksey#Injured_Jockeys_Fund|Injured Jockeys' Fund]]".<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Davies |first=Russell |date=30 January 1983 |title=TV |magazine=Time}}</ref>

For Stanley Wells, in the ''Times Literary Supplement'', Howell displayed "great cunning" in her direction of the tetralogy, effectively shifting from the anti-naturalistic feel of the earlier instalments to something more palpably realistic. He praised Warwick's death scene for the way Mark Wing-Davey gave a personal significance to choric lines that many actors would treat with a broad emotional style. Foster, as Queen Margaret, was "both charming and vicious, a siren and a spitfire". Her scene taunting York was a highlight of the cycle, with Bernard Hill also showing "splendid authority and fire" as York. However Wells questioned the use of a variety of regional accents, which were effective to help differentiate the many characters played by the same actors, but sometimes seemed at odds with those characters' social status.<ref name="Stanley"/>

