=====Behind the scenes=====
[[File:BBC Comedy of Errors.jpg|thumb|Opening shot of the episode showing the map of the region on the floor of the stylised market set; at the top of the shot is the abbey, top left is the Phoenix, bottom left is the Centaur, bottom right is the Porpentine, top right is a market stall. The entrance to the bay is opposite the abbey, out of shot.]]
Director James Cellan Jones felt very strongly that the play was not just a farce, but included a serious side, specifically represented by the character of Aegeon, who has lost his family and is about to lose his life. In several productions Jones had seen, Aegeon was completely forgotten between the first and last scenes, and determined to avoid this, and hence give the production a more serious air, Jones had Aegeon wandering around Ephesus throughout the episode.<ref>Willis, pp. 260–261.</ref>

The entire production takes place on a stylised set, the floor of which is a giant map of the region, shown in its entirety in the opening and closing aerial shots; all of the main locations (the Porpentine, the Abbey, the Phoenix, the market etc.) are located in a circular pattern around the centre map. While most stage productions have separate actors playing each Antipholus and each Dromio, Jones chose to double-cast the actors and use special effects for the final scene. The proudction's composer, Richard Holmes, appears onscreen as the street band's harpsichord player.<ref>Willis, p.274</ref> The sea backdrop had staples placed through it, so the light would glimmer in the sunlight and then moonlight.<ref>Willis, p.282</ref>

The ''Prefaces to Shakespeare'' episode for ''The Comedy of Errors'' was presented by [[Roger Rees]] who had played Antipholus of Syracuse in a [[The Comedy of Errors (musical)|1976 RSC production]] directed by [[Trevor Nunn]]. The ''Shakespeare in Perspective'' episode was presented by comedian [[Roy Hudd]].<ref>An analysis of this production can be found in {{cite book | last=Coursen | first=H.R. | chapter=''The Comedy of Errors'' on Television | editor-last=Miola | editor-first=Robert S. | title=The Comedy of Errors: Critical Essays | location=London | publisher=Routledge | year=2001 | pages=533–538 | isbn=9780815338895}}</ref>

=====Reception=====
The ''Boston Globe'' arts critic, Ed Siegel, considered this the most accessible and enjoyable of the BBC series thus far with wonderful actors and design. Daltrey was "exhilarating" in his screwball turn as the Dromios.<ref>{{cite news |last=Siegel |first=Ed |date=20 February 1984 |title=It's Rock vs. Shakespeare |work=Boston Globe |page=1}}</ref> In the ''New York Times'', John J. O'Connor enjoyed everything about the production, with Michael Kitchen "deft" and Jones wisely casting greatly experienced actors - Cusack, Gray, and Hiller - for the characters with long speeches. O'Connor liked that Jones stressed the "more ominous aspects" of the play and created a design that emphasised the playing space. He noted that Daltrey's casting was heavily emphasised in the BBC's marketing of the production, and it luckily paid off, with Daltrey capturing "the music and sense" of Shakespeare's words.<ref>{{cite news |last=O'Connor |first=John J. |date=20 February 1984 |title='The Comedy of Errors', Starring Roger Daltrey |work=New York Times |page=C17}}</ref> G.M. Pearce, in Cahiers Élisabéthains, consdiered this a "sparkling production" and appreciated that having the same actor play each twin made the confusion all the more realistic.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Pearce |first1=G.M. |date=April 1984 |title=The Comedy of Errors |journal=Cahiers Élisabéthains |volume=26}}</ref>

Jeanne Addison Roberts, in ''Shakespeare on Film Newsletter'', ranked this production among the very best of the series, with praise for Jones' camera that neither got stuck with endless images of talking heads like ''Julius Caesar'', nor tried to muffle the play's theatricality with naturalism like ''Antony and Cleopatra''. Roberts enjoyed the "sense of spaciousness, mystery and hidden possibilities" in Jones' set, which equalled any stage production. Cusack in particular earned praise, convincing the audience of his pathos and desolation, yet always allowing the audience to enjoy both comedy and tragedy, given the scene parodied him even as it engaged with his sorrow. "We owe... Jones and his company an enduring debt of gratitude".<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Addison Roberts |first1=Jeanne |date=December 1984 |title=The Shakespeare Plays on TV: The Comedy of Errors |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/44711668 |journal=Shakespeare on Film Newsletter |volume=9 |issue=1 |page=4 |doi= |jstor=44711668 |access-date=12 September 2025}}</ref>

In ''Literature/Film Quarterly'', Robert E. Wood appreciated that Jones found a classical unity of place in his set, which felt clearly three dimensional, unlike many previous instalments in the series. Having characters address the camera increased the intimacy of the comedy, which Wood felt the audience was more open to on television than in film. The choice to have the same actor play each twin was risky but successful, as the audience came to know each character separately and then was delighted by the success of the visual effects at the end. Ultimately the techniques of television "sharpen the contrasts inherent in this Shakespearean text without distorting its natural rhythm".<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Wood |first1=Robert E. |date=November 1986 |title=Cooling the Comedy: Television as a Medium for Shakespeare's Comedy of Errors |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/43797524 |journal=Literature/Film Quarterly |volume=14 |issue=4 |pages=195–202 |doi= |jstor=43797524 |access-date=12 September 2025}}</ref>

By contrast, Stanley Wells, in the ''Times Literary Supplement'', found that the comedy raised a chuckle but few outright laughs. While the play could be a delicate dessert on stage, "Here it is not so much a soufflé as a pudding".<ref>{{cite news |last=Wells |first=Stanley |date=6 January 1984 |title=Melancholy Misunderstandings |work=Times Literary Supplement |page=14}}</ref> Roger Warren, in ''Shakespeare Quarterly'', liked Jones' choice of a "quiet, small-scale realism" and his ''[[commedia dell'arte]]'' touches, which were well suited to television. Jones managed throughout to retain the comedy while giving his characters legitimate motivations, rather than simply riotous farce as sometimes shown on stage. Bertish stood out as the strongest performance, and Kitchen nicely distinguished his Antipholi. However, Warren thought Cusack poorly cast, and ruined the opening monologue with his delivery, "running on phrases regardless of sense". In his desire to keep the story intelligible to a television audience, Jones had his actors speak far slower and more clearly in the long final scene than would happen on stage, reducing the "great crescendo of confusion" that occurs in the best productions.<ref name="WarrenA1984">{{cite journal |last1=Warren |first1=Roger |date=Autumn 1984 |title=Shakespeare in England |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/2870376 |journal=Shakespeare Quarterly |volume=35 |issue=3 |pages=334–340 |doi= 10.2307/2870376|jstor=2870376 |access-date=1 September 2025}}</ref>

