=====Behind the scenes=====
For this production, director David Giles chose to go with a stylised setting. He viewed the first three acts as "emblematic" and "heraldic", and stressed this through the bright blue set of Acts 2 and 3. Giles saw the last two acts as "more realistic", and as a result the colours are more muted.<ref>{{cite book | editor-last=Wilders | editor-first=John | title=The Life and Death of King John | series=The BBC TV Shakespeare | location=London | publisher=BBC Books | year=1984 | pages=20–22 | isbn=9780563202769}}</ref> The music for the production was written by [[Colin Sell]]. Leonard Rossiter died in October 1984, the month before the production first aired.

The ''Prefaces to Shakespeare'' episode for ''The Life and Death of King John'' was presented by [[Emrys James]] who had played John in a 1974 RSC production directed by John Barton and [[Barry Kyle]]. The ''Shakespeare in Perspective'' episode was presented by the chairman of the British Railways Board [[Peter Parker (British businessman)|Peter Parker]].

=====Reception=====

In the ''Times Educational Supplement'', Nicholas Shrimpton approved of the production even if it was dealing with Shakespeare "at his third best". Costigan came across as a [[spring-heeled jack]], Bloom had "fierce energy and flawless technique", and Rossiter grew stronger as the production goes on to find a "grander and more majestic style" for the dying King.<ref>{{cite news |last=Shrimpton |first=Nicholas |date=30 November 1984 |title=Political Pageant |work=Times Educational Supplement |page=24}}</ref> Joan Hanauer, in the ''[[Sun Sentinel]]'' praised Rossiter in particular as memorable.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hanauer |first=Joan |date=11 January 1985 |title='King John' Looks at Second-Rate Ruler |work=Sun-Sentinel |page=12D}}</ref> In the ''Guardian'', Nancy Banks-Smith credited Rossiter with a "gloriously eccentric and really very human performance, making a funny, pitiful fellow creature out of a cypher".<ref>{{cite news |last=Banks-Smith |first=Nancy |date=26 November 1984 |title=Haul of fame |work=Guardian |page=11}}</ref> Peter Kemp, in the ''Times Literary Supplement'', found Giles' production a "very credible" approach to a difficult text. Bloom was moving, Rossiter at his best in John's downfall, and Morris, with "poisonous aplomb" played Elinor as "a glittery-eyed, leathery-skinned old reptile". Costigan stood out in a "fresh, forceful performance" with "engaging verve and trenchancy".<ref>{{cite news |last=Kemp |first=Peter |date=7 December 1984 |title=Hasty History |work=Times Literary Supplement |page=1416}}</ref> 

In the ''Observer'', Julian Barnes admired Rossiter's strong, accomplished performance, although concluded that Shakespeare's text has a shapeless plot and tedious events. As a result, Giles' cheap, "cardboard" production was not enough to make the play a success.<ref>{{cite news |last=Barnes |first=Julian |date=2 December 1984 |title=Rossiter's double farewell |work=Observer |page=26}}</ref> For Dennis Hackett, in the London ''Times'', Rossiter, Bloom, and Costigan all deserved plaudits but things were let down by the "insubstantial nature and limited mood of the sets".<ref>{{cite news |last=Hackett |first=Dennis |date=26 November 1984 |title=Television: King John |work=Times of London}}</ref> John J. O'Connor, in the ''New York Times'', also agreed that the design was "singularly disappointing", aiming for stylisation but "the effect is merely chintzy". However Bloom and Morris in particular were compelling and Giles kept the action running smoothly, even though the production sounded better than it looked.<ref>{{cite news |last=O'Connor |first=John J. |date=11 January 1985 |title='Shakespeare Plays' Presents 'King John' |work=New York Times |page=C24}}</ref> 

John Engstrom, writing for the ''Boston Globe'', liked the lead performances and the visual contrast between the French and English courts, but concluded the play made "pretty tedious viewing".<ref>{{cite news |last=Engstrom |first=John |date=11 January 1985 |title=Television |work=Boston Globe}}</ref> Scott Colley, in ''Shakespeare on Film Newsletter'', admired Costigan, who was dignified as well as satirical, and Rossiter finding both "menace and desperation" in John. Particularly interesting was Coy, playing a Dauphin who had more sense of character growth and "a sense of self" than usually seen. Claire Bloom brought great subtlety to a role that could easily become melodramatic: "when Bloom is on camera, the set is not cramped and the stone walls do not so insistently resemble painted styrofoam". But the production was sometimes lifeless, feeling more like the BBC filling a gap in the canon than seeking to add new dimensions to the text. Where most of the recent productions in the series had a particular aesthetic, this was a visual disappointment.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Colley |first1=Scott |date=December 1985 |title=The BBC-TV King John |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/44712309 |journal=Shakespeare on Film Newsletter |volume=10 |issue=1 |page=6 |doi= |jstor=44712309 |access-date=15 September 2025}}</ref> In the ''Christian Science Monitor'', Christopher Swan was also unsatisfied by a surface-level production of a play that moral force and fascinating imagery. The reason the lesser-known plays often succeeded in the series was because they were "discovered" by the director, whereas Giles seemed to just set up a scene and then breeze through it. Rossiter was not at his best as King John and the two child princes struggled visibly with the language. However Bloom was exceptionally well-spoken as Constance, and Costigan stood out, speaking "as though fresh from Liverpool's pubs, yet [making] the anachronism work".<ref>{{cite news |last=Swan |first=Christopher |date=7 January 1985 |title=PBS' King John is a Lesson in How Not to Do Shakespeare |work=Christian Science Monitor |page=28}}</ref>

